SYMPTOM_TEXT: Sudden fatigue, fever, chills and nausea. Lasted about 7 hours.

Last year I seemed to have a reaction but it was flushing. This year approximately one hour after getting the injection, I experienced a dry, continuous hacking cough. HISTORY: No history of health conditions or illness.

Patient experienced vasovagal syncope about 5 minutes after receiving the vaccination.  She was very nervous about the needle before getting the immunization but was acting normal and coherent directly following the shot.  Her friend then received his shot, whom was also very nervous. They were both encouraged to stay in our waiting area and as they were collecting their belonings she lost her balance and fell.  I left the pharmacy to help her up.  She said she was fine and got up and started to walk and then fell again, losing conciousness for a few seconds cutting her lip on her teeth.  Myself and her friend helped her to a chair and I gave her a gauze pad for her lip.  She refused an ambulence and said she felt okay, just a little light headed.  They stayed for about 30 minutes and decided to go to an urgent care to get checked out just in case.

Will also use OTC tylenol and topical benadryl to treat current symptoms.  No trouble with range of movement with arm.

Patient had lethargy and slightly elevated heart rate the evening of the second day after vaccination. The following morning the patient was still lethargic and had a heart rate over 200. Patient was taken to an urgent care, then to a local hospital. The local hospital noted SVT with a heart rate of 280. Three doses of adenosine were administered followed by an esmolol drip up to 40mcg/kg/min. Blood pressure was normal and the heart rate only came down to 250. Patient's potassium was slightly off, likely due to hemo lysis. Patient vomited once. Patient was then flown to a regional hospital. In-flight, two additional doses of adenosine were given with the final dose resulting in sustained conversion. Esmolol was continued at 30mcg/kg/min until the patient was transitioned to oral atenolol 1mg/kg twice daily. Approximately one month later patient was admitted again with SVT with heart rate of 160. Patient converted when the IV was being put in and was crying. Digoxin was added to his daily medication regimen.
LAB_DATA: ECG during both episodes indicated SVT; Multiple ECG and echocardiograms after the events were normal; CBC looked normal; afebrile;

Patient received vaccine 9/16/20. Started having symptoms 9/28/20 evening - soreness/pain at site of injection, fever, body aches, generalized joint pain, dry cough, cold sweats, scratchy/dry throat. On 9/29/20 evening developed vesicular rash to BUE, BLE and trunk.

I was given the shot about 2 pm. It was very high on the left arm almost to the shoulder. It hurt more than usual going in. I went home. By .5 pm I could not move my left arm at all without severe pain. This continued for 3 days - no possible use of the arm at all. On day 4 I could move forward and backward a couple of inches still no movement to the side without severe pain.  Slowly I regained movement. At 2 weeks I could raise my arm forward strait out in front of me and sideways 1/2 way to a T position At 3 weeks I could raise my arm forward and straight up over my head and sideways to a T position.  It's now been 4 weeks and I can raise my arm over my head both forward and sideways, Going sideways hurts a little.  Also reaching behind me or doing a swimming motion hurts a little.  If I do a motion that hurts a little, my shoulder will ache deep inside for a few minutes afterwards. I also had the usual vaccine effects of low grade fever and not much energy for about 3 days after the shot.
LAB_DATA: A week after the vaccination I returned to the doctor's office because my shoulder still hurt and I could not use my arm. I was told by a physician's assistant that the shoulder pain could not be from the vaccination because the shot was in the muscle.  She said I probably have arthritis.  An x-ray was taken and showed no arthritis.  I was told on a phonecall that the radiologist thought he "might have seen something", and recommended an MRI.  I declined to have that test based on such vague information.
OTHER_MEDS: 81mg aspirin multivitamin, 500mg vitc, 400IU vit E, 1000UI vit D3 1000mg glucosamine/msm complex
HISTORY: History of asthma especially in high air pollution and on farms - No recent attacks

improperly stored administered PROQUAD; This spontaneous report was received from a nurse, referring to a patient of unknown age and gender. Information regarding the patient's medical history and historical drugs was not provided.   On 15-SEP-2020, the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored dose of measles, mumps, rubella and varicella (oka-merck) virus vaccine live, recombinant human albumin (rHA) (PROQUAD), lot #T013540 for prophylaxis (dose, vaccination scheme frequency, route of administration and anatomical site of vaccination were not reported).   The vaccine was stored in a temperature of 6 degree Fahrenheit (ï¿½F) to 14ï¿½F (11.7ï¿½F) for 25 minutes as recorded by a data logger. There was no previous temperature excursion reported.  Lot No. T013540 has been verified to be a valid lot number for measles, mumps, rubella and varicella (oka-merck) virus vaccine live, recombinant human albumin (rHA) (PROQUAD), expiration date reported and verified as 17-OCT-2021.

vaccination to patient with improperly stored vaccine; No additional adverse events reported; This spontaneous report was received from a nurse referring to a currently 2-month-old patient of unknown gender. The patient's pertinent medical history, concomitant medications, and previous drug reaction or allergies were not reported.  On an unknown date of 2020, the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored dose of rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ) at a dose of 0.5 milliliter, for prophylaxis (route of administration, vaccination scheme frequency, anatomical location, were not reported; the lot number and expiration date were unknown by the reporter). The administered dose of the vaccine experienced a temperature excursion which went from 28 degrees Fahrenheit (F) to 33.9 (F), and then to 50.2 F in a timeframe of 7 hours and 10 minutes. There was not previous temperature excursions and the data logger was not involved. There was no adverse event reported. The patients concurrent conditions, known allergies/reactions, medical history and concomitant medications were not reported.   On an unspecified date, the patients were vaccinated with improperly stored doses of Measles, Mumps, Rubella and Varicella (Oka-Merck) Virus Vaccine Live (PROQUAD) (Lot # S022914 with expiration date 19-JAN-2021; Lot # T013541 with expiration date 17-OCT-2021; and lot # T009932 with expiration date 16-SEP-2021) and varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) (Lot # S024366 with expiration date 06-AUG-2021; Lot # T002846 with expiration date 23-JAN-2022; and lot # T010308 with expiration date 24-MAR-2022)  (dose, route of administration and anatomical location not provided) for prophylaxis. Shingles; Spot that still itches not marks or sot; Spot-like rash; This case was reported by a consumer via interactive digital media and described the occurrence of shingles in a adult patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   On 6th April 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, less than a year after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced shingles, localized itching and spot-like rash. On an unknown date, the outcome of the shingles, localized itching and spot-like rash were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the shingles, localized itching and spot-like rash to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. Patient reported that after receiving Shingrix experienced shingles and asked about when its to get the shot again. Patient reported about still experiencing spot that still itches not marks or sot. The reporter did not consent to follow up. There was a discrepancy regarding capturing event shingles. Query had been raised to HUB, it was unknown whether the patient experienced shingles after the dose. In addition, it was unknown whether the patient had 1st dose but as per notes, it seems that this was the patient's 1st dose and yet to receive 2nd one

Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient had a history of chemical allergies and asthma. On 9th September 2020, the patient was stung by a wasp on her right shin and she had a bad reaction to the wasp sting and had finished a steroid pack treatment of 4 mg of prednisone last on night of 19th September 2020. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hemorrhage post-delivery; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; Uterine leiomyoma; Endometriosis of pelvis; This is an observational study case, received from other health professional on 28-Sep-2020, and concerned a 37-year-old, female, pregnant subject of body weight: 151 lbs, height: 65 inches and body mass index (BMI): 25.1, enrolled in a prospective observational study on pregnancy outcomes in women immunized with Afluria QIV, a seasonal quadrivalent vaccine, during pregnancy.  The subject's concurrent medical history included pregnancy at advanced maternal age and BMI increased.  The subject's concomitant medication included calcium gummies and Vita Med MD Redichew RX ((6s)-5-methyltetrahydrofolate glucosamine, colecalciferol, folic acid, mecobalamin, pyridoxine hydrochloride, riboflavin), both used as supplement.  The subject's obstetrical history included no previous pregnancies. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformations (MCMs) and no relevant maternal or paternal medical history with MCM. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.  The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 22-Dec-2019. The estimated delivery date (EDD) and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 27-Sep-2020. The type of pregnancy was singleton.  On 18-Mar-2020, at gestational age of 12 weeks (calculated per LMP), the subject was vaccinated with Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL) (influenza vaccine; dose, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported) (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for an influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was P100126099 (the expiry date was not reported).  On an unknown date in 2020, unknown amount of time after vaccination, the subject developed uterine leiomyoma and endometriosis of pelvis.  On 04-Mar-2020 and 15-Apr-2020, the ultrasound scan revealed no MCMS.   On 12-May-2020, maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein screening (MSAFP) / serum markers revealed no MCM.  On 09-Sep-2020, at gestational age of 37.4 week (as reported), the subject delivered live birth, female neonate via caesarean method of delivery. The neonate's birth weight was 2807 grams, head circumference was 33 cm, and body length were 48,9 cm. The appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration (APGAR) score at one minute was 8, at five minutes was 9 and at 10 minutes was not provided. There was no MCM noted at birth. On the same day, the subject experienced post-delivery haemorrhage.  On the same day, the subject recovered from the event 'hemorrhage postpartum'.  The event of 'hemorrhage postpartum' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment to Afluria QIV.  Company comment: Postpartum haemorrhage, uterine leiomyoma and endometriosis were associated with the use of the suspect product - Afluria QIV. On an unknown date in 2020, unknown amount of time after vaccination, the subject developed uterine leiomyoma and endometriosis of pelvis making chronology unclarified. On 09-Sep-2020, approximately 6 months after vaccination, postpartum haemorrhage was reported - chronology seems unsuggestive. Several studies suggest that symptomatic endometriosis and symptomatic uterine fibroids appear together. Almost 20% of patients with symptomatic fibroids also had endometriosis. On the other hand, 26% of patients with symptomatic endometriosis also had fibroids. Both events are assessed as unrelated to the product and more likely related to pregnancy and maternal endocrine influence. Postpartum haemorrhage is a reasonable consequence of these 2 events making causality also unrelated to the product. Vaccine exposure during pregnancy is assessed as unrelated per company conventions.; Sender's Comments: Postpartum haemorrhage, uterine leiomyoma and endometriosis were associated with the use of the suspect product - Afluria QIV. Cellulitis; The vaccine was given incorrectly (too low); This spontaneous case was received on 28-Sep-2020 from a pharmacist (reference number: SEQW20-02481) and concerned a female patient of unknown age.  The patient's concurrent condition included diabetes. The patient's concomitant medications included metformin for unreported indication.   On 15-Sep-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Fluad Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, mf59l; dose: 0.5 ml, anatomical location: left deltoid, indication, route of administration: not reported). The batch number reported was 279791, expiry date: 28-May-2021.   On 16-Sep-2020, one day after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent, the patient developed pain, redness, swelling and itching.  On an unknown date in Sep-2020, the patient came by the pharmacy and was advised to use unspecified cream. The patient was seen by her physician and was diagnosed with cellulitis. The patient's physician felt the vaccine was given incorrectly (too low) and this caused the cellulitis (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine administered at inappropriate site'). The physician prescribed Bactrim (sulfamethoxazole, trimethoprim) as treatment. The patient had an upset stomach due to Bactrim, as reported. The pharmacy was not able to see the injection site again to verify that the vaccine was given too low.  On an unknown date in Sep-2020, redness, swelling and itching had resolved and the patient recovered from the event.   The reporter did not provide a causality assessment. The patient's physician felt the vaccine was given incorrectly (too low) and this caused the cellulitis.   The event of cellulitis was considered to be medically significant by a Physician.  Company comment: A female patient of unknown age developed cellulitis, one day after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent vaccine. Chronology is plausible. Reportedly, the patient developed pain, redness, swelling and itching which was diagnosed as cellulitis. The patient's physician felt the vaccine was given incorrectly (too low) and this caused the cellulitis (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine administered at inappropriate site'). The physician prescribed Bactrim (sulfamethoxazole, trimethoprim) as treatment. With information available, causal role of the suspect vaccine is assessed as possibly related. Although from the report seems that events were at vaccination site, it was not clear and therefore the case does not meet BC definition of cellulitis at injection site. SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient has been admitted due to an apparently acute-onset anoxic brain injury and unresponsive event two days after receiving the Varivax and Havrix vaccines, with leading diagnoses of inborn error of metabolism vs. myocarditis. The night prior to the event she seemed well, and she slept in her parents bed overnight, awakening multiple times for her bottle and behaving normally. The following morning the patient was found unresponsive in the parents' bed. Initial evaluation showed diffuse hypoxic-ichemic brain injury on CT head, EEG with diffuse slowing, hypoglycemia, leukocytosis, myocardial dysfunction on echocardiogram, and hypotension requiring pressors. She was intubated and admitted to the PICU. Started on empiric antibiotics, though LP could not be obtained. Blood viral and bacterial testing was negative. MRI shows small multifocal infarcts. She is now extubated and improving, with underlying etiology unclear

Additional information: On 05 September 2019, a pharmacist telephonically prescribed a Shingrix vaccination to be administered to the patient by an unsupervised intern. As a direct and proximate consequence, she suffered from Transverse Myelitis, was permanently paralyzed in her left leg, and forced to take medication for severe and chronic pain that interferes with sleep. On awakening the morning of 06 September 2019, she had sharp pain in her back and legs. She went to doctors and was prescribed a muscle relaxant. Over the next few weeks, the condition worsened into weakness in her legs. She did not connect the condition to the vaccination she had received the day earlier. On 23 October 2019, she had a nerve conduction study done. The study showed severe peripheral neuropathy. She consulted with her acupuncturist determined that the cause of the problem was most likely the Shingrix vaccination. As per records dated 21 September 2020, she had shingles and/or been previously vaccinated with Zostavax. She received a Zostavax vaccination in October 2017, only two years prior to being vaccinated with Shingrix.

The patient spent overnight in the hospital and had a lot of tests and was released the following day.  The morning of her vaccination, she was fine and then she went to clean the shower and she remembered nothing after that point.  She came out of the bathroom and her husband said that she went to get her shoes which she always put under her coffee table and she kept repeating an asking, are these my shoes.  Later that day around 1:30 PM, they had no eaten yet and she felt nauseous and had a headache in the back of her head.  The patient ate some noodle soup but did not remember and her husband brought out some banana bread and she couldn't remember that she had baked it the day before. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had the shot Tues aft. at my store pharmacy. Later that night I noticed mild muscle pain and a slight fever, but this is not unusual for me. I usually have a mild reaction to the flu vaccine, and it only lasts about a day. However, the pain spread to my ribs and was bad enough to wake me during the night, and by the Wed morning I was in a lot of discomfort. I went into the bathroom to take my usual pills, and immediately vomited them up, along with the glass of water I drank. I called out from work and returned to bed, where I slept pretty much all day and was too nauseous to eat or drink. The next morning  (Thu) I was feeling a little better, though not well enough to go to work. I was able to eat a bit of toast and some tea, but nothing more substantial. Friday I was mostly well, and then by the weekend I had pretty much recovered, except for some lingering nausea, which comes and goes, and may be unrelated. This is the worst reaction I've ever had to the flu vaccine, and a doctor friend of mine suggested I report it. I'm sorry I don't have more info, but it was given at the store pharmacy. My husband and daughter received theirs at the same time and were fine.
PRIOR_VAX: Yes, very mild fever/muscle aches with flu vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 2 hours of vaccination, I was feeling pressure in my upper chest and developed a persistent cough.  My eyes became dry and itchy, felt swollen.  In another couple hours my head was foggy. I felt weak and had stabbing body aches. Within 12 hours of vaccination the chest pressure increased to a concerning degree; I had a runny nose, felt chills; my temp had gone from 98.2 to 100. Six hours later it was 96.  Next day the chills and stabbing body aches were gone. My eyes were still itchy.  My hands were swollen. The cough continued. I took Lung Tonic to decrease the pressure feeling in my chest; it did.  Later that day my temp returned to 98. The next day I felt better but began coughing up globs of yellow mucus. That continued 2 or 3 more days.  Currently, 10 days post-vaccination, my hands are still swollen, my eyes are still a bit itchy feeling, and the cough is minimal.
OTHER_MEDS: Amlodipine Besylate 5mg Aspirin 81mg Glucosamine Sulfate 750mg Melatonin 10mg Vitamins: C, D, E

polymyalgia rheumatica; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation and refers to a patient of unknown  age and gender. Information regarding medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant medications was not provided. In or around 01-OCT-2016, the patient was inoculated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (strength, dose, frequency, lot # and expiration date were not reported) for routine health maintenance and for it's intended purpose the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unspecified date, shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), Plaintiff suffered an abrupt onset of arthralgias and myalgias with aching, burning, excruciating and intermittent pain located in shoulders, hips, and knees bilaterally. Plaintiff was diagnosed with polymyalgia rheumatica. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), Plaintiff's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). Plaintiff also experiences mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result Plaintiff sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Plaintiff suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of Defendants' conduct, Plaintiff has suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages.  Upon internal review, polymyalgia rheumatica was determined to be medically significant.

Bilateral Parsonage-Turner syndrome; right upper extremity pain/left upper extremity (pain followed by weakness); right upper extremity weakness/left upper extremity (pain followed by weakness; atrophy of the bilateral shoulders; upper extremity reflexes absent; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of parsonage-turner syndrome in a 54-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingles vaccine) for prophylaxis.   On an unknown date, the patient received Shingles vaccine. On an unknown date, several days after receiving Shingles vaccine, the patient experienced parsonage-turner syndrome (serious criteria hospitalization), pain in upper extremities (serious criteria hospitalization), weakness of upper extremities (serious criteria hospitalization), atrophy (serious criteria hospitalization) and absent reflex. The patient was treated with immunoglobulins nos (Immunoglobulin), prednisone and non-drug therapy (Physical Therapy (Nos)). On an unknown date, the outcome of the parsonage-turner syndrome, weakness of upper extremities, atrophy and absent reflex were unknown and the outcome of the pain in upper extremities was recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the parsonage-turner syndrome, pain in upper extremities, weakness of upper extremities, atrophy and absent reflex to be related to Shingles vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of Bilateral Parsonage-Turner syndrome (PTS), in a female patient aged 54-year-old, who was vaccinated with Unspecified Shingles vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis.   The patient was a right-handed dominant female chef at a local university. No information on patient medical or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was reported.  On an unspecified date, the patient had received unspecified Shingles vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age at vaccination was not reported but it could be between 53 and 54 years.   On an unknown date, a few days after receiving vaccination, the patient developed right upper extremity (RUE) pain which was quickly followed by RUE weakness. The patient saw an outside neurologist at that time, and after an extensive workup that included magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), electromyography (EMG), nerve conduction studies (NCS), and lumbar puncture (LP), no organic cause was discovered, and based on patient clinical examination a functional disorder was suspected (giveway/collapsing weakness). Five months later, a similar series of symptoms occurred in the left upper extremity (pain followed by weakness). No further workup was done at that time, and the patient did not receive treatment due to the belief that her symptoms were psychogenic. Despite spontaneous resolution of pain, the patient presented to the emergency room for persistent weakness four months later (nine months after the initial event involving the RUE). On physical examination during her most recent admission, profound symmetric weakness was noted in her bilateral upper extremities. The weakness was more severe proximally (2/5 strength in deltoids; 3/5 biceps, triceps, wrist extensors, wrist flexors, and intrinsic hand muscles; 4/5 finger flexors and extensors), and significant atrophy of the bilateral shoulders was noted. The patient upper extremity reflexes (biceps, triceps, brachioradialis) were absent bilaterally, with preservation of her lower extremity reflexes. Sensation to pinprick, light touch, vibration, and temperature were diminished symmetrically up to the shoulder in her bilateral upper extremities. During the patient most recent/final admission, the patient received an evaluation that included MRI with gadolinium of the brain, cervical spine, thoracic spine, and brachial plexus, along with Lumbar puncture (LP). LP for cerebro spinal fluid (CSF) showed volume: 1.5 mL, clear and colorless CSF, red blood cell (RBC): 1/mcL; white blood cell (WBC): 4/mcL (normal range: 0-5/mcL); lymphocytes: 98% (normal range: 40-80%); monocytes: 2% (normal range: 15-45%); differential based on: 100 cells; glucose: 66mg/dL (50-80mg/dL); protein: 23.0 mg/dL )normal range: 15.0-60.0 mg/dL); Meningitis/encephalitis panel by PCR was negative; west nile virus AB igM was 0.02 IV (normal range: less than equal to 0.89); IgG and IgM monos GM1, IgG and IgM Asialo, GM1 and IgG and IgM Disialo, GD1B: all were negative. EMG of her bilateral upper extremities revealed evidence of an active denervating process involving C5 through T1 distribution in both upper extremities. No genetic testing was done, but the patient denied any family history of similar symptoms.  The case was considered as serious due to hospitalization.  Treatment included intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) and prednisone. The patient was also referred to physical therapy.  Outcome of the event was of reported.  The authors commented "It is our belief that PTS was triggered in our patient secondary to the vaccine she received, though it is rarely possible to pinpoint a definite etiology. Many associations with PTS have been documented including infection, surgery, anesthesia, rheumatic disease, trauma, stressful exercise, pregnancy, radiation therapy, and vaccination. Given the lack of family history, our suspicion of hereditary PTS was low, though we cannot rule it out as a contributing factor as no genetic testing was done. In the case of this particular patient, her first EMG was done too early to be of diagnostic value for her, as significant abnormalities often do not appear until three weeks after onset in PTS. In most cases, the differential is broad and the history (especially time of onset) may not always be clear, so delaying EMG testing is not always reasonable. As suggested by this case, threshold for a repeat EMG in patients with persistent, recurrent, or worsening symptoms without a diagnosis should be low. In our patient, 38 weeks passed before the diagnosis was established, which was well beyond the suggested therapeutic window for prednisone mentioned above. This is actually shorter than the mean time of 43.8 weeks for diagnosis according to one review, although the median was significantly shorter at 10.5 weeks. We treated this patient with IVIG and prednisone. There is no strong evidence as to how a patient with PTS should be treated in the chronic phase, but there is reported efficacy in case reports from the use of IVIG both as monotherapy and in combination with prednisone. In the acute phase, the pain is often so intense that it is necessary to treat with opiates, tricyclics, or anti-epileptic drugs. In the case of this patient, the pain had already resolved spontaneously, so there was no indication for pain management. We also referred this patient to physical therapy, which is utilized for both range of motion and strengthening. Caution must be used in early reinnervation stages, as overloading injured muscles can retard axonal regeneration and muscle reinnervation. Limited EMG follow-up testing may be utilized to demonstrate the extent of reinnervation and guide advancement of strengthening regimen, but is not absolutely necessary. Although the diagnosis of PTS was significantly delayed in this patient, this does not necessarily mean that the suspicion of a functional disorder was incorrect. Functional disorders may be diagnosed based on positive findings, such as Hoover's sign, drift without pronation, give way weakness, and so on, and are not always a diagnosis of exclusion. With this in mind, it is important to consider that a patient may display these positive findings as part of a functional overlay to an organic neurologic disorder".  The authors concluded "In a patient presenting with shoulder pain followed by weakness, PTS should always be included in the differential diagnosis, especially if the initial workup does not reveal an obvious etiology. PTS is primarily a clinical diagnosis, and EMG findings are often unrevealing in the acute phase (up to three weeks). A functional disorder, even when correctly diagnosed secondary to positive findings as mentioned in the discussion, does not exclude an underlying organic neurologic disorder. In some cases, an organic neurologic disorder may even be considered a risk factor for a functional disorder. Current treatment options for PTS are limited, but there is evidence that oral prednisone within the first month may be beneficial, so a timely diagnosis is of increased importance. Given that EMG findings may not be apparent until three weeks after symptom onset, the threshold for ordering a repeat EMG should be low in patients without a strong diagnosis".

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pharmacist states that they were having an event and two patients ages 11,16 were inadvertently given the Flublok immunization; Initial information received on 03-Oct-2020 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a pharmacist.  This case was issued in publication with one other linked case 2020SA273639 (cluster)  This case involves a 11 years old patient for whom pharmacist states that they were having an event and two patients ages 11,16 were inadvertently given the flublok immunization (Product administered to patient of inappropriate age) was reported while he/she received vaccine INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE [FLUBLOK QIV].  The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.   On 03-Oct-2020, the patient received a 0.5 ml dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE (lot UJ463AA, Expiry date:19-MAR-2021) via intramuscular route in the left arm for prophylactic vaccination.  On an unknown date (of unknown latency), the patient developed a non-serious pharmacist states that they were having an event and two patients ages 11,16 were inadvertently given the flublok immunization (reported to be wrong product administered) following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVALENT RECOMBINANT VACCINE.  No lab details were reported.   It was not reported if the patient received a corrective treatment.  On an unknown date, the event outcome was reported to be not applicable.  This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holders compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: administered improperly stored VARlVAX; This spontaneous report was received from a medical assistant referring to a 12-month-old male patient. Information about concomitant medication, pertinent medical history, drug reactions or allergies was unknown.  On 28-AUG-2020, the patient received improperly stored varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) (also reported as therapy start date unknown) (lot # S038701, expiration date: 01-DEC-2021, dose was not reported, subcutaneous) for prophylaxis (reported as "well check") (product storage error). The varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) was reconstituted with properly stored sterile diluent (MERCK STERILE DILUENT). The vaccine was exposed to temperature from minus 9 Celsius degree to 8 Celsius degree (also reported as minus 6.1 Celsius degree) (multiple excursions). The time frame was unknown by reporter. No previous temperature excursion. Another varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (VARIVAX) vaccine (lot# S032355, expiration date: 14-OCT-2021, dose was not reported, subcutaneous) was involved. The vaccine was exposed to temperature from minus 14 Celsius degree to minus 10 Celsius degree for 116 hours and from minus 9 Celsius degree to 8 Celsius degree for 13 hours. Time frame was reported as 129 hours. No previous temperature excursion. Data logger was involved for both vaccines.

The patient did not receive any concomitant medications   On 29-Sep-2020, the patient received a 0.7 ml dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE (lot UJ510AB, expiry date: 30-Jun-2021) once via intramuscular route in the left deltoid for prophylactic vaccination   On 30-Sep-2020 the patient received a 0.7 ml dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE (lot UJ510AB, expiry date: 30-Jun-2021) once via intramuscular route in unknown administration site for prophylactic vaccination.  It was of actual medication error due to extra dose administered and incorrect product storage.  The vaccines were deemed not suitable for use due to the shipment that arrived late. The nurse reported that the patient was accidently given the vaccine on 29-Sep-2020 from the batch. The patient was called back to get revaccinated with a vaccine that was suitable for use. On 30-Sep-2020, she was accidently given a dose from the same batch as the day before. The vaccine was put away to avoid being used but was still used. The prescriber was not wanting to revaccinate the patient due to having two doses of the high dose in two days. There were  total  6-pateints that received the doses on 29-Sep-2020. The reporter had information on the above mentioned patient. There were no details about other 5 patients whether they got revaccinated with vaccines that were suitable for use.   At the time of report, no adverse event was reported.  This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the regulatory authority. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error.

For past 4 years, patient had not had a SLE flareup, and also had not had blood clot in past 4 years.  Patient's lab work for SLE had been extremely healthy for past 4 years, with no indication of SLE or APS involvement.  Patient had been feeling healthy, with energy, and had easily went on a 3 mile run just 12 hours, the night before the shot.  So, the following symptoms, typical of a SLE flareup for the patient were abrupt and sudden, upon the flu shot injected at 9:15 AM on 9/29/2020.  Within 2 hours of flu shot, had Lupus red skin and Lupus red rash spots on cheeks.  Within 2 1/2 hours, had additional Lupus hard tissue on face in 1" to 2" section that was bright red.  From 3 hours to 3 days after shot, had bright red face on entire face.  Within 12 hours had extreme dizziness, nausea (but no stomach pain or cramping), and vomiting (food or water) that lasted for 3 days.  No fever, but clammy skin for 3 days.  Within 24 hours, had blood clot on lower right thigh, a few inches higher than a prior blood clot (about 20 years ago) when diagnosed with Antiphospholipid Syndrome, secondary to SLE.
LAB_DATA: Could not get in to be seen, and no EKG available to check blood clot within a two-hour's drive.  Patient attended a virtual visit with primary care a week later.
CUR_ILL: Systemic Lupus E (SLE), APS, secondary to SLE, Reynaud's.   Hypertension,

Patient developed exercise-induced anaphylaxsis following this vaccine. By fall of 2014, he was unable to exercise fully without breaking into hives, vomiting and requiring a visit to the ER due to constriction of air flow in his throat.  When exercising, his legs would begin to tingle and his body would develop hives and his face would swell.   In April of 2015, patient was diagnosed with exercise induced anaphylaxsis and  was tested for allergies by a local allergist.  He had never been allergic to anything but had now developed a life threatening allergy  to shellfish, treenuts. and a variety of fruits. He has has over ten ER visits and requires an Epipen with him at all times.  Patient began losing his hair shortly after the first dose of Gardisil in July 2013 (Lot No. H021861). Mood swings and depression also presented and his mental outlook was severely affected.   In April of 2019, patient was unable to walk  due to dizziness and weakness and was incorrectly diagnosed with "Labyrinthitis".   In August 2019, patient visited a primary care doctor to see why his hands, feet, and scalp were numba and tingling. Thyroid was checked but levels were normal.  Another bout of dizziness and loss of balance presented in  early  February 2020.  Following a visit and MRI with an ENT, the patient was rushed to the hospital on Feburary 24th where a battery of blood tests and a spinal tap confirmed multiple layers of lesions in his brain - he was diagnosed with MS.  He is currently a patient with a doctor.
LAB_DATA: Allergy tests -  March 2015 Hospital - MS diagnosis - Feb 24- 27, 2020  Doctor ordered battery of Blood tests Feb. 25, 2020; Spinal tap 2/25/2020; follow up spinal for neck and spine 6/2020
CUR_ILL: Epstein Barr noted in blood test
PRIOR_VAX: Gardisil 07/02/2013    Lot No. H021861  Merck & Co.  Adverse event- hair loss, depression, anxiety, extreme change in mood from

Acute pain in upper arm significantly more severe than flu vaccine, started almost immediately.  I did some aerobic exercise 1 hour after the vaccine.  Two hours after the vaccine, I started to feel minor body aches that increased in severity throughout the evening.  By bedtime movement was uncomfortable and I spend a largely sleep less night.  The next day,  was suffering from a low-grade fever (<100 F) and general body aches (that made it difficult to move), headache and minor stomach upset.  I took an advil to in the morning to decrease the symptoms.  I took another in the afternoon.  By the evening (after dinner) the symptoms significantly resolved.  I still have minor aches 40 hours after the vaccine but feel well enough to resume normal activity.  The most acute phase of the symptoms were severe enough that I would not have been able to go into work under normal (non-Covid) circumstances.    Symptoms are definitely NOT severe enough that I would ever consider NOT having the vaccination, but they are definitely the most notable reaction I've can every recall having to a vaccination.

Administered shingrix and flu shot to patient. Shortly after, patient stated that she felt light headed. I stayed by her side throughout whole incident. She kept saying she was light headed in the chair. She exhibited no signs of allergic reactions like difficulty breathing or hives. She passed in chair for a few seconds. We positioned her on the ground and we called 911 for assistance. EMTs were sent. I went into the pharmacy to get epinephrine and benadryl. I came back out and she was sitting up. She was breathing fine with no symptoms of anaphylaxis. She was speaking to me throughout the rest of the duration. She was breathing fine and I asked her to verify. She stated that she was breathing fine and that she still felt light headed. I gave her a single dose of liquid benadryl and monitored her to see if I would need to use epinephrine. I did need to use epinephrine. I relayed info. to EMTS when they arrived. EMTs stated patient had low bp and took her to hospital.
LAB_DATA: Not a test. She came back to pharmacy a few hours later. Hospital released her and said it had to do with low blood pressure. She thanked for helping her during this time.
OTHER_MEDS: To my knowledge patient takes no medications currently.
HISTORY: Patient stated that she had no health conditions. She stated that occassionally her blood pressure is low.

The patient's concomitant medications were not reported.   The physician reported that, at the age of 2-3 weeks the infant experienced gastrointestinal symptoms, that included mucus in stool, at this time, it was confirmed by the reporter that the patient did not receive the vaccine of rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ), but was diagnosed with milk protein allergy. The patient's mother changed the diet of infant by herself, and the symptoms were resolved.   On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ), administered by oral route, as prophylaxis (formulation, strength, lot number and expiration date were not reported).   On approximately 10-SEP-2020 (also reported as "2-3 weeks ago"), the patient experienced a reaction, which was described as "increased frequency of bowel movements" (frequent bowel movements) and "streaks of blood and mucus in the stool" (haematochezia and mucous stools), at this time; the patient was strictly breast fed, as a precaution the physician recommended to the patient's mother stopped the ingest dairy and soy products (food allergy), because these gastrointestinal issues could be saw in infants that were having a dairy allergy usually to cow's milk. The physician reported that, the patient's mother stopped all dairy and soy intake and the infant had improved by his 2 month well visit.   On an unspecified date in 2020, at the age of 2 months, the patient received the second dose of rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ), administered by oral route, as prophylaxis (formulation, strength, lot number and expiration date were not reported), however; within 24 hours the patient's mother had call to their office reporting that the infant had been "fussy" (irritability), and was having "frequent bowel movements and blood and mucus in the stool" (frequent bowel movements, haematochezia and mucous stools) as had been noted after administered the first dose.   The physician felt that rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ) may caused gastrointestinal symptoms in babies with milk protein allergy.   The outcome of frequent bowel movements, haematochezia and mucous stools, regarding with the administration of the first dose was recovered; the outcome of food allergy was not provided, the outcome of frequent bowel movements, haematochezia and mucous stools, regarding with the administration of the second dose was not reported. The causal relationship between rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ) with the events frequent bowel movements, haematochezia and mucous stools was reported as related, and with the event of food allergy and irritability was not provided.   Upon internal review, haematochezia was determined to be medically significant event.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Gastrointestinal disorder; Mucous stools

paralyzed from neck down; fever; an infection related to catheter; Initial information was received on 05-Oct-2020 regarding an unsolicited valid serious case from a consumer/non-health care professional (caregiver). Medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s), concomitant medications and family history were not provided.   On an unknown date in Dec-2007, the patient received a dose of suspect INFLUENZA VACCINE produced by unknown manufacturer (lot number and expiry date not reported) once via an unknown route in unknown administration site for prophylactic vaccination.  On an unknown date, the patient was paralyzed from neck down (paralysis) 5 hours following the administration of INFLUENZA VACCINE. He was taken to the hospital for 2 days and got back the use of everything but his legs, and then the hospital discharged him to a rehabilitation center that was more reactive, than preventative. The event paralysis was assessed as medically significant.  Case details: The family (2 nurses in the family) felt that the patient had Guillen's Barre, however this was never officially diagnosed. The patient died in the rehabilitation center within a week due to an infection related to his catheter (device related infection) even though he was not running a fever. At the very end he ran a fever (pyrexia, non-serious event), but they did not put him on the appropriate antibiotics. No autopsy was completed.  The event device related infection was assessed as medically significant and led to death.  No laboratory data was provided.   It was not reported if the patient received a corrective treatment.  At the time of report, the outcome of paralysis and pyrexia was unknown while the event device related infection was fatal.  The cause of death was reported as device related infection.  Information on lot number was requested.; Sender's Comments: This case involves an 89 years old male patient who had paralysis, pyrexia and died due to device related infection after vaccination with INFLUENZA VACCINE (produced by unknown manufacturer). Concomitant medications included meningococcal vaccine a/c/y/w conj (dip tox) (MENACTRA) lot no: U6575AA, expiration date: 08May2021, and diphtheria vaccine toxoid, pertussis vaccine acellular, tetanus vaccine toxoid (TDAP) lot no: U6621BA, expiration date: 21Mar2022, both received on 26Mar2020 for immunization. The patient previously received TDAP and MENACTRA doses as it was reported that TDAP and Menactra vaccines had been administered before to the patient with no adverse reaction. The healthcare professional wanted to know if it is okay to give second dose of TRUMENBA if patient had an adverse reaction to it on 27Mar2020. The female patient was 16 years old at the time of events: rash on face, facial swelling, throat was tightening but no trouble breathing, and swollen lips. She said the patient also got 2 other vaccines administered at the same time, but the TRUMENBA was the only new vaccine. She stated that the doctor would like to know if it is recommended to give the second TRUMENBA vaccine, since the patient may have had a possible reaction to TRUMENBA. She added that after receiving the TRUMENBA vaccine, the patient had a rash on her face the following morning (27May2020) and tried cetirizine cetirizine (ZYRTEC). The rash got worse, with the patient experiencing facial swelling, and saying it felt like her throat was getting tight, but the patient's throat was not closing. The patient did not have any trouble breathing. The patient was given a steroid and an epinephrine (EPI-PEN) injection because the patient's lips were swollen, as well. No relevant tests done. The patient recovered from the events.   No follow-up attempts are needed. No further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Based on the close temporal relationship, the association between the events "rash on face, facial swelling, throat was tightening but no trouble breathing, and swollen lips" with TRUMENBA can not be fully excluded.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

This case involves patient (unknown demographic) who received INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B VACCINE [FLUZONE QUADRIVALENT] During administration time the vaccine leaking out during an injection and syringe has been disposed of at the time of this report (syringe issue), spraying into a patient left eye and the vaccine spilled on the left eye (exposure via eye contact), the vaccine spilled on the arm and clothing (exposure via skin contact) and did not receive a full dose (underdose).  Medical history, medical treatment, concomitant medication, vaccination and family history were not provided.    On an unknown date, the patient received a dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B VACCINE (lot UJ471AB and expiry date: 30-Jun-2021) via an unknown route in the arm for prophylactic vaccination.  It was actual medication error case due to underdose and exposure via eye contact and exposure via skin contact (latency on same day). It was reported that Fluzone Quadrivalent spraying into a patient left eye due to the vaccine leaking out during an injection. The Pharmacist reported that the needle was on tight; that after the event the needle was checked and was tight; that there was no damage noted to the syringe on inspection after the event; that the syringe has been disposed of at the time of this report; that she knows the needle was injected into the arm and the vaccine was being administered; that the consumer did not receive a full dose; that the consumer reports the needle never penetrated his arm or that the injection was not in all the way; that the consumer is a physician; that the vaccine spilled on the arm, clothing, and the left eye.  It was also the case of Syringe issue.  At the time of report no adverse event was reported. Breaking out on her upper thighs/ big lesions then spread to arms, chest and whole body; Having trouble picking things; Fatigued; 2 different types of eruptions; Hyper reaction to flu vaccine; This spontaneous case was received on 05-Oct-2020 from other non-health professional via Agency (reference number: SEQW20-02890) and concerned a 76-year-old female patient.  The patient's concurrent conditions included allergy to sulfa which caused her muscle paralysis, and meloxicam allergy. The patient was not taking any concomitant medications and stated she was very healthy.   On 08-Sep-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Afluria Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, dose: 0.5 ml; anatomical location: deltoid; route of administration: not reported) for influenza prophylaxis. The batch number and expiry date were not reported. The patient had no problem at the time of administration.  On 10-Sep-2020, two days after receiving Afluria Quadrivalent, the patient was fatigued, had trouble picking things up and started breaking out on her upper thighs, it was tiny at first, then by the second week had developed into big lesions then spread to arms, chest and whole body.  On an unknown date in 2020, the patient saw dermatologist that reported the patient had two different types of eruptions and diagnosed her with hyper reaction to flu vaccine. She was prescribed prednisone, at dose of 40 mg, for two weeks and a return appointment on 29-Oct-2020.  On 02-Oct-2020, the patient started treatment with prednisone, at dose of 40 mg.   At the time of initial reporting on 05-Oct-2020, the patient had not recovered from events 'fatigue' 'hypersensitivity reaction' and 'movement disorder' but was recovering from events 'skin lesion' and 'skin eruption', as it was reported that the rash was much improved.  The events 'hypersensitivity reaction', 'skin lesion' and 'skin eruption' were considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Department.  The reporter assessed the event of 'hypersensitivity reaction', 'skin lesion' and 'skin eruption' to be related to Afluria Quadrivalent. The reporter did not provide a causality assessment for other events.  Company comment: Hypersensitivity, skin lesion, rash, movement disorder and fatigue were associated with the use of the suspect product - Afluria Quadrivalent. Causality was assessed as possibly related  for all events due to plausible chronology and absence of any other confounding factor.; Reporter's Comments: The patient saw dermatologist that reported the patient had two different types of eruptions and diagnosed her with hyper reaction to flu vaccine.; Sender's Comments: Hypersensitivity, skin lesion, rash, movement disorder and fatigue were associated with the use of the suspect product - Afluria Quadrivalent. Causality was assessed as possibly related  for all events due to plausible chronology and absence of any other confounding factor.
CUR_ILL: Allergic reaction to analgesics; Sulfonamide allergy

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Seizure-like activity; Incontrollable muscle movement; Mood change; Muscle weakness; Cramps; Tired; Nausea; Headache; This spontaneous case from the was received on 05-Oct-2020 from other non-health professional via Med Communications (reference number: SEQW20-02860) and concerned a 51-year-old, male patient.   The patient had no relevant medical history and was not taking any concomitant medications.  On 27-Sep-2020, the patient was vaccinated with Flucelvax QIV (influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular and anatomical location: deltoid) for influenza prophylaxis. The batch number reported was 287096 and expiry date was not reported.   On 01-Oct-2020, four days after receiving Flucelvax QIV, the patient experienced seizure-like activity, incontrollable muscle movement, mood change, muscle weakness, cramps, nausea, headache and was tired.   At the time of initial reporting on 05-Oct-2020, the patient had not recovered from the events, as it was reported that the symptoms were still ongoing.   The reporter assessed the events as non-serious.   The event of 'seizure' was considered to be serious due to the criterion of medical significance by a Physician within Seqirus' Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  This case is linked to cases 202004934 (the corresponding spouse case) and 202004935 (the corresponding daughter case).  Company comment: A 51-year-old, male patient experienced seizure (seizure like symptoms), dyskinesia, mood altered, muscular weakness, muscle cramps, nausea, headache and fatigue four days after receiving Flucelvax QIV vaccine. The patient had no relevant medical history and was not taking any concomitant medications. More information regarding diagnostic findings is needed. Causality is assessed as possibly related for all events due to plausible chronology and no alternative aetiology provided. Brighton Collaboration criteria for generalised tonic-clonic seizure could not be assessed due to insufficient information.; Sender's Comments: A 51-year-old, male patient experienced seizure (seizure like symptoms), dyskinesia, mood altered, muscular weakness, muscle cramps, nausea, headache and fatigue four days after receiving Flucelvax QIV vaccine. experienced syncope following administration of GARDASIL 9; This spontaneous report was received from a physician via Company representative and refers to a female patient of unknown age. On 02-OCT-2020, the patient was vaccinated with hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) intramuscular injection (dose, anatomical location, lot # and expiration date were not reported) for human papillomavirus (HPV) prevention.  On the same day, after receiving hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9), the patient was advised to wait for 15 minutes, before leaving the clinic, but she decided to leave immediately. She experienced syncope when she got in her car to drive away, and went back inside the clinic. She was examined by the physician. It was unknown if any laboratory diagnostics or studies were performed. The patient recovered quickly on the same day without any treatment, and was able to go home without further event. SYMPTOM_TEXT: My daughter received her vaccines on 5/12/20 at 12 months old. She had a virus on  5/2-5/4-20 with a 104-105 degree fever with no other symptoms. She was cleared for her vaccines on 5/12/20 since no fever was present. On 5/28/20 she started getting a rash then got petechiae and had a nose bleed the morning of 5/29/20. I took her to the pediatrician who immediately sent us to have a platelet count at the hospital. The Platelet count came back at 2,000 and we immediately went to the ER.  After more testing and a few questions on other counts they ruled out Leukemia. The Doctors told me it was ITP most likely caused by the MMR vaccine in addition the active virus from 5/2/20. After a platelet transfusion her platelet levels increase and a month later they were back to normal.  They did warn me that she could possibly have reactions to other vaccines and their was  a small chance she could develop an autoimmune disorder from the ITP.
LAB_DATA: Platelet levels at 2,000 and petechiae as diagnosis
CUR_ILL: May 2-May 4, 2020 my daughter had a fever of 103-105 degrees for 3 days with no other symptoms. She had her vaccines on May 12, 2020. She developed ITP with platelet levels at 2,000 on May 28, 2020 and had to be hospitalized and receive a platelet transfusion.
HISTORY: We are not sure of any long-standing health conditions that will affect her in the future

The patient complained of pain at the injection site. She said "I could feel it going in more than I thought I would." This was her first flu vaccine ever.  Patient did not appear to have any additional swelling after approximately 3 minutes post-injection.  It did not appear to be worsening. Overall, pressure was held over the site for about 7 minutes.  Patient was given an ice pack and advised to keep rotating ice off and on the site as tolerable to decrease the swelling.  The patient did not appear to have symptoms of respiratory distress or anaphylaxis. Patient appeared otherwise healthy after injection.

Patient experienced redness, warmth, and limited range of motion

Less than 48 hours after flu vaccine I began to experience shoulder pain and limited range of motion that gradually worsened over the course of 2-3 weeks.  Simple tasks that required me to lift my arm up, such as getting dressed and combing my hair became very difficult and painful.  I have also had difficulty sleeping due to shoulder pain at night.  My family doctor diagnosed me with subacromial bursitis caused by improper administration of the flu vaccine.  He explained that the vaccine was administered too high on my arm and entered the joint rather than my deltoid muscle.  At present my family doctor has prescribed Voltaren cream to reduce inflammation and pain.  As of today, 10/15/2020, symptoms have not yet subsided and treatment with Voltaren continues.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received Fluarix in left arm and Trumenba in right arm the morning of 10/9/20.  Mom called at about 3:00pm that day to report that he said he "felt a little funny" after the Trumenba in right arm was administered but they didn't think anything of it.  45 min after the vaccine he c/o h/a.  Mom became concerned and called us when he called for her and he was in the bathroom floor saying he had the worst h/a he had ever had and he felt nauseous.  Provider advised that he drink down about 30 oz of Gatorade now and then continue to hydrate throughout the day with water. Provider recommended that if he continued to feel concerned to take him to the hospital.  Mom said she didn't feel the need to take him to the hospital. Redness and tactile warmth lasted until 10/10/20 and patient said he "felt like he was coming down with something" but by that night, he was completely fine.

On 14th September 2020, the patient experienced hives, joint pain, mobility decreased, pruritus and pain. On an unknown date, the patient experienced hypersensitivity reaction, tingling lips and temporomandibular joint arthralgia. The patient was treated with prednisone. Rechallenge with Shingrix was positive. On an unknown date, the outcome of the hypersensitivity reaction, mobility decreased, pain and drug dose administration interval too long were unknown and the outcome of the pain in arm, tenderness, fatigue, joint pain, tingling lips and temporomandibular joint arthralgia were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the hives and pruritus were recovering/resolving. Arm achiness and tenderness and fatigue which presented a few hours after the injection.  It became worse the following day and the next day and then started to resolve after 3-4 days.  2 months to the day that the second dose was received, joint pain and hives presented.  The joint pain started in her shoulders. She could not lift her arms away from her body.  Pain in the joints of her hands and feet. The pain would present after basic activities such as carrying her groceries caused elbow and wrist pain. She had a dental appointment and felt pain in her right jaw joint following that appointment from having her mouth open. The hives presented in various areas around her whole body. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Expired vaccine administered.  Vaccine expiration date was 6/30/2020., vaccine administered on 10/14/2020. Patient denied negative reaction after administration, no signs/symptoms of a reaction.  Per  recommendation of  a website, repeat vaccine should be administered.  Based on that recommendation the visit provider will contact the patient to disuss/ arrange repeat clinic visit for a second vaccine..   What should we do if a dose of expired vaccine is given to a patient?  The dose should be repeated. If the expired dose is a live virus vaccine, you should wait at least 4 weeks after the previous (expired) dose was given before repeating it. If the expired dose is not a live vaccine, the dose should be repeated as soon as possible. If you prefer, you can perform serologic testing to check for immunity for certain vaccinations (e.g., measles, mumps, rubella, varicella, and hepatitis A).

improperly stored vaccine administered to patient; This spontaneous report was received from a registered nurse and refers to a 11-year-old patient of an unknown gender. The patient's pertinent medical history, concomitant medications and previous drug reactions or allergies were not reported.  On 07-OCT-2020, the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored vaccine hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast)(GARDASIL 9) lot # S010729, expiration date 01-DEC-2021, 0.5 milliliter for prophylaxis (route of administration and anatomical location were not reported). SYMPTOM_TEXT: Per H&P:  Presenting for evaluation of laceration to the left medial forehead after the patient hit his head on an open car door.  Patient says he was under the car working and when he rolled out from under it the door was open and he went to sit up hitting the side of his head.  Patient states he hit his head so hard he initially saw stars however he denies loss of consciousness, headache, neck pain, nausea or vomiting. Per provider note: Patient's tetanus was updated today as it has been over 10 years since his last vaccination.  patient discharged home.   Per H&P:  Presenting via EMS for evaluation of possible allergic reaction.  Patient states he first felt dizzy and then nauseated and like his throat was closing.  He then experienced cough, chest pain and vomited twice.  EMS gave the patient 125 of Solu-Medrol, 50 of Benadryl, 0.5 epi IM and 2 of mag with improvement of his breathing and chest pains. He is now complaining of his entire body aching.  He denies any drug use prior to the incident.  Patient was seen in the emergency department today for a closed head injury and laceration repair with Dermabond and received a tetanus shot at that time.  Patient thinks that his reaction may be related to that as symptoms onset approximately 1 hour after discharge home. Had a tetanus shot in the past and tolerated it without complications.  Denies syncope, blurred vision, fever or abdominal pain.   In summary, patient is a 19 y.o. male presenting for evaluation by EMS for possible anaphylaxis after receiving tetanus shot in the emergency department earlier today.  Patient states that the resume the shot he had no symptoms and was discharged.  Approximately 1 hour after his discharge he began to experience dizziness, nausea, the sensation that his throat was closing.  Which also developed into cough, chest pain and 2 episodes of emesis.  Patient had pain all over and asked his mom to call 911.  EMS gave Solu-Medrol, Benadryl, epinephrine and mag with improvement of his breathing and chest pains in route.  Patient presents complaining of his entire body aching and some itching on the upper thighs.  Denies syncope, blurred vision, fever abdominal pain. ï¿½ ï¿½ In the emergency department, the patient's vital signs are stable.  He is in mild distress secondary to diffuse myalgias.  Physical exam shows evidence of anaphylaxis with allergic shiners swelling of the eyelids.  Patient speaking in full sentences, no respiratory distress, lungs are clear to auscultation.  Remainder of exam is benign.  Given that patient was treated in route for anaphylaxis and his symptoms were resolving, plan is to monitor for 4 hours after epi dose for reemergence of his symptoms.  I gave patient 1 dose of Pepcid for itching.  EKG showed sinus bradycardia with no evidence of ischemic changes.  Lab studies were not obtained.  On signout, patient's vital signs are stable and he was resting comfortably.  If patient has no additional symptoms over the monitoring period, he may be discharged home with an EpiPen.  If his symptoms recur, he will be admitted for further monitoring and evaluation.  Patient signed out to Dr.

HISTORY: Per H&P: Patient is a 19 y.o. male with PMH significant for ADHD, PTSD, Depression

10/15/2020  At approximately 1000 Fluarix influenza vaccine was administered to the client during a mobile clinic at the Agency. It was explained to the nurse that the patient fainted but did not fall. He was place in a chair and the nurse was called summoned. Upon examination he was alert and oriented to self, time, and place; lips were pale; pulse regular, grade +2. He did not feel hot to the touch. He denied any pain or nausea. He was given one can of apple juice to drink. He stated he had eaten breakfast before coming to the clinic. After several minutes of monitoring, he denied any nausea and stated he was feeling slightly better, however his lip continued to be pale. He had a general appearance of not being well and RN felt he should be seen by a provider. He was carried by his mother to the clinic housed in the medical building. RN explained to the provider the events as they occurred and actions taken. Concern was also expressed about patient's continued appearance of ill health and this was the rationale for seeking additional evaluation. The provider agreed and accepted care.  At approximately 1445 patient's mother presented again to the mobile clinic with the patient. She stated she had taken the patient home after being evaluated in the clinic and had since vomited twice. she was concerned it was related to the influenza vaccine. When questioned the patient stated to the RN he was feeling better but did complain of a headache. Again, he was not hot to the touch but continued to look in ill health. It was strongly recommended to the mother that she take him to either an urgent care facility or Emergency Department for further evaluation as he was exhibiting headache, nausea and vomiting.  10/16/2020  @ 0810 - Spoke with mother to retrieve additional health information about the patient to complete the VAERS documentation. She states patient is much better today.
Fever of 99.3, felt shaky and nauseous

She later had to put an ice-pack over it for comfort. The appearance of the skin lesions remains unchanged the next morning 10/16/20 when she presented to employee health clinic. This largest area of erythema also has two overlying clear fluid-filled bullas, with the larger bulla measuring 4 cm X 2.2 cm and the smaller bulla measuring 1 cm X 1 cm.  Patient reports sensation of burning and pin-prick pain overlying the affected skin region that is worse with touch. Denies any shortness or breath or any other symptoms.

After a few days, I noticed increased sensitivity on my abdomen and back, in one wide band a little below my rib cage on the front.  In addition I got a rash about one inch in diameter on my abdomen within that band.  It is sore, red, bumpy, has little vesicles in it.  My doctor (nurse practitioner) confirms that it seems to be shingles itself.  It is quite painful from back to front on the skin, and sometimes deeper in my abdomen.

He was very dismissive. I have two doctorate?s, yet he spoke to me like if I didn?t fit the most common side effects then my experience couldn?t be possible. (10:00 AM 10/16/20 is when I called the pharmacy that administered the shot).
