SYMPTOM_TEXT: Hypotension; Sepsis; Loose stool; suspected vaccination failure; influenza A/H1pdm09/influenza A H1 2009 (Influenza A virus type: H1N1); Chills; Rhinorrhea; recurrent high fevers; Dry cough; left upper lobe pneumonia; Tiredness; Death NOS; Legionella pneumophila; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of unknown cause of death in a 66-year-old female patient who received Flu unspecified (Flu vaccine) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included fludarabine, melphalan, alemtuzumab, total body irradiation, tacrolimus (prophylaxis) and rituximab (detectable circulating EBV DNA prior to transplant). Concurrent medical conditions included angioimmunoblastic t-cell lymphoma and chronic myelomonocytic leukemia (received a matched related donor (MRD) stem cell transplant (SCT) (in October 2018)).   On an unknown date, the patient received Flu vaccine. In February 2019, less than a year after receiving Flu vaccine, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), h1n1 influenza (serious criteria hospitalization), chills (serious criteria hospitalization), rhinorrhea (serious criteria hospitalization), fever (serious criteria hospitalization), dry cough (serious criteria hospitalization) and legionella pneumophila infection (serious criteria GSK medically significant). In July 2019, the patient experienced unknown cause of death (serious criteria death and GSK medically significant). On an unknown date, the patient experienced lobar pneumonia (serious criteria GSK medically significant), hypotension (serious criteria hospitalization), sepsis (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), loose stools (serious criteria hospitalization) and tiredness. The subject was treated with oseltamivir, antibiotics nos, baloxavir marboxil and azithromycin. On an unknown date, the outcome of the unknown cause of death was fatal and the outcome of the vaccination failure, h1n1 influenza, chills, rhinorrhea, fever, legionella pneumophila infection, lobar pneumonia, hypotension, sepsis, loose stools and tiredness were unknown and the outcome of the dry cough was recovered/resolved. The subject died in July 2019. The reported cause of death was unknown cause of death.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the unknown cause of death, vaccination failure, h1n1 influenza, lobar pneumonia, hypotension, sepsis, chills, rhinorrhea, fever, dry cough, loose stools, legionella pneumophila infection and tiredness to be related to Flu vaccine.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the suspected vaccination failure in a 66-years-old female patient, who was vaccinated with unspecified seasonal influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. This case corresponds to table 1 reported in this literature article. The patient was a part of the study which described the clinical and virological responses to oseltamivir and baloxavir treatment in five allogeneic SCT recipients, and molecular characteristics of the influenza virus population before and after treatment. [It was used baloxavir to treat five allogeneic SCT recipients that were still symptomatic and shedding influenza virus after completing one or more treatment courses of oseltamivir and characterized the viral isolates before and during treatment. Allogeneic SCT patients with influenza A virus infection who received oseltamivir with no resolution of symptoms and were persistently positive for influenza A virus by the FilmArray Respiratory Pathogen two panel were included in the study]. The patient had angioimmunoblastic T-cell lymphoma (AITL) in partial remission and chronic myelomonocytic leukemia (CMML) who received a matched related donor (MRD) stem cell transplant (SCT) (in October 2018). The patient received fludarabine, melphalan, alemtuzumab, and total body irradiation (TBI 400cGy) as conditioning and tacrolimus as post-transplant graft-versus-host disease (GVHD) prophylaxis. Because of detectable circulating EBV DNA prior to transplant, the patient received one dose of rituximab with her transplant conditioning. The patient received Rituximab in prior 6 months. Time duration from SCT was 0.30 years. The patient had not active GVHD. The patient (setting) was from inpatient. No information on patient's family history was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received annual unspecified seasonal influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided. On an unspecified date in February 2019, an unknown period after the vaccination, the patient experienced chills, rhinorrhea, cough, and fever to 39 degree Celsius and was diagnosed with influenza A H1 2009 (Influenza A virus type: H1N1) using the RP2 panel. Nasopharyngeal swab in universal viral transport media (BD) was collected as part of routine clinical care. The patient did not receive immunosuppressive therapy at the time of influenza diagnosis. Oseltamivir therapy was initiated (for 5 days), but 5 days later the patient presented to the emergency department with recurrent high fevers to 40 degree Celsius, chills, rhinorrhea, dry cough, and loose stool. CT chest showed left upper lobe pneumonia, and a repeat RP2 panel was still positive for influenza A virus. The infection type was pneumonia. The patient was admitted to the intensive care unit for hypotension/sepsis and received broad-spectrum antibiotics and baloxavir 40 mg for influenza. The next day, a urinary antigen test for Legionella pneumophila serotype 1 was reported to be positive and antibiotic treatment with azithromycin 500 mg daily was started. The co-pathogen included Legionella. Her symptoms rapidly improved but the patient continued to complain of persistent cough and tiredness, and the RP2 panel was still positive for influenza A. A second dose of baloxavir 40 mg was administered 4 days after the initial dose, and the patient was discharged home two days later. When the patient returned to clinic for follow-up 1 and 3 weeks after discharge, her symptoms were much improved, the patient had no cough, but was positive for influenza A/H1pdm09 at both visits. The influenza outcome was persistent shedding. Neuraminidase sequence was WT (Wild-type) and Polymerase sequence was I38T. This case has been considered as suspected vaccination failure being the time to onset was unknown. On an unspecified date in July 2019, the patient died from progressive disease. It was unknown whether the patient's autopsy was performed or not. [Nasopharyngeal swabs in universal viral transport media (BD) were collected as part of routine clinical care using standard procedures. Influenza was detected using the RP2 panel. Nucleic acid was isolated both using an automated platform (easyMAG) and using QIAamp kit in accordance with the manufacturers' protocols. Nucleic acids extracted using the easyMAG platform were tested by real-time reverse transcriptase-PCR to confirm the presence of influenza virus. Nucleic acids extracted using QIAamp kits were sequenced with next-generation sequencing methods for whole-genome analysis. A total of five patients who were both symptomatic and persistently positive for influenza A on the RP2 panel after receiving oseltamivir were treated with baloxavir. Oseltamivir was administered at the standard dose of 75 mg twice/day orally. Baloxavir was administered orally as a single or two doses of 40 or 80 mg, based on weight, according to manufacturer's instructions. All patients were profoundly immunocompromised because of allogeneic lymphodepleting SCT. In addition, two had received rituximab (monoclonal antibody directed to the lymphocyte surface protein CD20) within 6 months of influenza diagnosis, two had received prolonged immunosuppressive treatment for graft-versus-host disease (GVHD), and one was obese, a predisposing condition for severe influenza. All patients had coinfection with other pathogens, four of them had pneumonia and were hospitalized].  This case has been considered serious due to suspected vaccination failure, death and hospitalization. The author commented, "It has been repeatedly reported that the treatment of influenza in immunocompromised hosts is problematic, requiring prolonged treatment courses, causing an increased risk of the development of antiviral-resistant influenza variants. Moreover, because uncomplicated influenza in this patient population may present with few initial symptoms and no fever, the diagnosis is often delayed, and treatment with NAI is often initiated after the preferred 48-hour window from onset of symptoms. Baloxavir has been recently approved for the treatment of uncomplicated influenza. It has been shown that treatment with baloxavir is associated with a more rapid viral clearance. Here, we describe the treatment of five allogeneic SCT recipients with baloxavir who were still positive for influenza A after oseltamivir treatment. In 4 of these subjects, including those with demonstrated oseltamivir-resistant variants, treatment with baloxavir was followed by clinical improvement and viral clearance. Three patients did not have any detectable NAI resistance-associated changes in the influenza viruses sequenced at the time they received baloxavir, and we cannot exclude the possibility that more prolonged oseltamivir treatment may have also been effective for symptom resolution and viral clearance. We found that one of the treated subjects developed a PA variant after two doses of baloxavir. Although the patient improved and eventually cleared the infection, the potential for transmission of variant virus raises concern. Despite the small patient number and the lack of a control group, our data suggest that baloxavir may be a useful treatment option for infections with influenza virus with NAI-resistant variants, and/or in SCT patients who fail NAI treatment for other reasons. Combination therapy, including baloxavir and oseltamivir, has shown synergistic activity in vitro. This treatment option might be more effective and may decrease the emergence of resistant influenza variants in the immunocompromised host." The author concluded, "Our data suggest that baloxavir treatment can be effective in treating neuraminidase inhibitor-resistant influenza in profoundly immunocompromised patients. Randomized clinical trials are needed to define the role of baloxavir alone and combined with oseltamivir for the treatment of influenza in SCT recipients and other immunocompromised populations." This is 1 of the 3 valid cases reported in the same literature article.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020GSK203425:Same reporter; Reported Cause(s) of Death: death NOS

The patient received oseltamivir for the treatment of influenza and azithromycin for possible associated bacterial pneumonia, both for 5 days with no improvement. A repeat RP2 panel was still positive for influenza A, and a second course of oseltamivir was administered for an additional five days. [The patient received oseltamivir for 20 days]. The patient was seen in clinic weekly for 3 additional weeks and continued to complain of persistent cough with yellow sputum, worsening fatigue with dyspnea on exertion. Chest x-ray was unremarkable. RP2 tests at each visit remained positive for influenza A. The patient therefore received one dose (80 mg, weight-based) of baloxavir (once). At the follow-up visit 5 days later, his symptoms had improved, and the patient was able to walk without experiencing any shortness of breath. At this time, influenza A was not detected. By the following visit two weeks later, cough, congestion, and shortness of breath had resolved, and the patient had resumed normal activity. The influenza outcome was clearance. Neuraminidase sequence was H275Y and Polymerase sequence was WT (Wild-type). This case has been considered as suspected vaccination failure being the time to onset was unknown. [Nasopharyngeal swabs in universal viral transport media were collected as part of routine clinical care using standard procedures. Influenza was detected using the RP2 panel. Nucleic acid was isolated both using an automated platform  and using lavatory kit in accordance with the manufacturers' protocols. Nucleic acids extracted using the platform were tested by real-time reverse transcriptase-PCR to confirm the presence of influenza virus. Nucleic acids extracted using lavatory kits were sequenced with next-generation sequencing methods for whole-genome analysis. A total of five patients who were both symptomatic and persistently positive for influenza A on the RP2 panel after receiving oseltamivir were treated with baloxavir. Oseltamivir was administered at the standard dose of 75 mg twice/day orally. Baloxavir was administered orally as a single or two doses of 40 or 80 mg, based on weight, according to manufacturer's instructions. All patients were profoundly immunocompromised because of allogeneic lymphodepleting SCT. In addition, two had received rituximab (monoclonal antibody directed to the lymphocyte surface protein CD20) within 6 months of influenza diagnosis, two had received prolonged immunosuppressive treatment for graft-versus-host disease (GVHD), and one was obese, a predisposing condition for severe influenza. All patients had coinfection with other pathogens, four of them had pneumonia and were hospitalized]. This case has been considered serious due to suspected vaccination failure. The author commented, "It has been repeatedly reported that the treatment of influenza in immunocompromised hosts is problematic, requiring prolonged treatment courses, causing an increased risk of the development of antiviral-resistant influenza variants. Moreover, because uncomplicated influenza in this patient population may present with few initial symptoms and no fever, the diagnosis is often delayed, and treatment with NAI is often initiated after the preferred 48-hour window from onset of symptoms. Baloxavir has been recently approved by the Regulatory Authority  for the treatment of uncomplicated influenza. It has been shown that treatment with baloxavir is associated with a more rapid viral clearance. Here, we describe the treatment of five allogeneic SCT recipients with baloxavir who were still positive for influenza A after oseltamivir treatment. In 4 of these subjects, including those with demonstrated oseltamivir-resistant variants, treatment with baloxavir was followed by clinical improvement and viral clearance. Three patients did not have any detectable NAI resistance-associated changes in the influenza viruses sequenced at the time they received baloxavir, and we cannot exclude the possibility that more prolonged oseltamivir treatment may have also been effective for symptom resolution and viral clearance. We found that one of the treated subjects developed a PA variant after two doses of baloxavir. Although the patient improved and eventually cleared the infection, the potential for transmission of variant virus raises concern. Despite the small patient number and the lack of a control group, our data suggest that baloxavir may be a useful treatment option for infections with influenza virus with NAI-resistant variants, and/or in SCT patients who fail NAI treatment for other reasons. Combination therapy, including baloxavir and oseltamivir, has shown synergistic activity in vitro. This treatment option might be more effective and may decrease the emergence of resistant influenza variants in the immunocompromised host." The author concluded, "Our data suggest that baloxavir treatment can be effective in treating neuraminidase inhibitor-resistant influenza in profoundly immunocompromised patients. Randomized clinical trials are needed to define the role of baloxavir alone and combined with oseltamivir for the treatment of influenza in SCT recipients and other immunocompromised populations." This is 1 of the 3 valid cases reported in the same literature article.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020GSK203425:Same reporter

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Bloody Diarrhea; gastrointestinal issues; This case was reported by a physician via call center representative and described the occurrence of bloody diarrhea in a 2-month-old female patient who received Rota (Rotarix lyophilized formulation) (batch number FX2TZ, expiry date 5th September 2021) for prophylaxis.   On 16th September 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Rotarix lyophilized formulation (oral). On 30th September 2020, 14 days after receiving Rotarix lyophilized formulation, the patient experienced bloody diarrhea (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and gastrointestinal disorder. On an unknown date, the outcome of the bloody diarrhea and gastrointestinal disorder were recovering/resolving.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the bloody diarrhea and gastrointestinal disorder to be related to Rotarix lyophilized formulation.  Additional case details were reported as follows: The reporter inquired about the incidence of bloody diarrhea in a two month old patient that was given an oral dose of Rotarix. Two weeks later on 30th September 2020, patient started with gastrointestinal issues that on 1st October 2020, developed to bloody diarrhea. No other symptom was confirmed for the patient. The reporter consented to follow up. As per sales data sheet reported batch number was changed from  FX2TZ9521 to FX2TZ.. The gastrointestinal issues was considered as sign and symptoms of bloody diarrhea, and therefore accordingly event onset date was captured as 30 Sep 2020.

AFib; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable physician via Pfizer Sales Representative. A 68-year-old male patient received pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13) intramuscular in the left deltoid muscle on his left arm on 07Oct2019 at 0.5 mg single dose for pneumonia and invasive pneumococcal disease. Medical history included chronic coronary artery disease, Gastrooesophageal reflux disease (GERD), anxiety, and bleeding hemorrhoids.  Concomitant drugs when the patient was on at the time he received the pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) included amlodipine 5 mg once daily orally, acetylsalicylic acid (ASPIRIN 81) at 81 mg once daily orally, atenolol 55mg once a day by mouth, atorvastatin 40mg once a day by mouth, apixaban (ELIQUIS) 5mg twice a day by mouth, losartan 50mg once a day by mouth, sildenafil citrate (VIAGRA) 100 mg, sertraline hydrochloride (ZOLOFT) 150mg once a day by mouth.  Serious adverse event was reported as A-fib with onset date of 07Oct2019and seriousness criterion of hospitalization. The event clinical course was as follows: The patient went into A-fib on 07Oct2019. It was unknown exactly when A-fib began, but the patient went right to the hospital when it did begin. Patient was not in the provider's office when it began, it was sometime later that day, and the patient never told the provider until recent visit this year in Sep. It was unknown if the patient was admitted when he went to the hospital that day.  Outcome of the event was resolved.    Information on the lot/batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information currently provided, A-fib occurrence most likely is associated with the patient underlying cardiovascular condition unlikely related to PREVNAR 13 use.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Anxiety; Coronary artery disease; GERD (Verbatim: GERD); Hemorrhoidal bleeding

Allergic reaction; swelling in his trunk; web-like rash; This case was reported by a pharmacist via call center representative and described the occurrence of allergic reaction in a 70-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) (batch number B4527, expiry date 2nd May 2022) for prophylaxis.   On 2nd September 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular) .5 ml. On an unknown date, less than 2 months after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced allergic reaction, swelling and rash. The patient was treated with benadryl (nos) (Benadryl). On an unknown date, the outcome of the allergic reaction was unknown and the outcome of the swelling and rash were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the allergic reaction to be related to Shingrix. The reporter considered the swelling and rash to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient had 1st dose of Shingrix 0.5 ml (intramuscular) in unknown deltoid. After receiving 1st dose of Shingrix, the patient experienced web-like rash and swelling on his trunk. The reporter was a pharmacist at a pharmacy. The reporter said the patient was advised to take oral Benadryl. On 12th October 2020, patient woke up and still has the same problem and he dose not want to keep taking Benadryl. The patient had no relevant medical history and was not taking any concomitant medications. The patient reported never having any hearing problems and has not had a flu shot in over 20 years.  On an unspecified date in 2020 (reported as 04-Sep-2020 and 04-Oct-2020), the patient was vaccinated with Flucelvax QIV (influenza vaccine, subunit influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, dose: 0.5 ml, anatomical location: right deltoid, route of administration: not reported) for influenza prophylaxis. The batch number reported was 276578, expiry date: 30-Jun-2021.     On 06-Oct-2020 about 5 p.m., the patient experienced hearing loss in her left ear and felt it was plugged up. The patient was having problems hearing on the telephone and would have to switch to the right ear to hear a conversation. On the same date, before bed, the patient took a decongestant and was able to hear some better in the morning.   At the time of initial reporting on 07-Oct-2020, the patient had not recovered from the events.   The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.   The event of 'hearing loss unilateral' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus' Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  Company comment: On an unspecified date in 2020, a patient was vaccinated with Flucelvax QIV vaccine. On 06-Oct-2020, the patient experienced deafness unilateral and ear discomfort. Reportedly, the patient had no relevant medical history and was not taking any concomitant medications. The patient reported never having any hearing problems and has not had a flu shot in over 20 years. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I went to get a flu vaccine at my local pharmacy clinic. I asked for the flublok quadrivalent vaccine because I had read that it was better suited for people with allergies, and who are prone to have allergic reactions. However, the nurse practitioner insisted that I get the flucelvax quadrivalent flu vaccine instead. She told me that she and her children had received the same vaccine, and that they didn't have a bad reaction to it. She told me that both vaccines were very similar. I thought it was odd that she just didn't give me the vaccine I asked for, but I didn't see any reason to press the matter. So I agreed to have the flucelvac quadrivalent vaccine which she kept insisting on. After she administered the flu vaccine to me I left. I didn't live far from the store. I started to feel tingling all over my body about 30 to 45mins after I received the flu vaccine.  When this started happening I thought that I must be having a mild reaction to the vaccine. The tingling and itching lasted all day. I was still itching some the next day, but this time I noticed that my left hand, on the arm that I received the injection was really really sore, and weak. My left arm muscles also ached and felt really fatigued. The muscle ache in my left hand, and arm lasted all day. Later on that night my entire body was experiencing muscle aches, and muscle fatigue. When I went to bed that night I took a Benadryl and went  to sleep. The next day the itching I had experienced had greatly diminished, but I was still experiencing muscle aches and fatigue all over my body. I have to lift heavy things at work, and for the past few days it has been difficult to do  so because of the muscle fatigue I've been experiencing. I am writing a report today, 10/17/20, because it has been a week since I received the flu vaccine, and I am still experiencing mild itching, muscle aches, and muscle fatigue.  I have never had such a bad reaction from receiving a flu vaccine before!
PRIOR_VAX: Flu vaccine 2 years ago.

After I administered the flu vaccine, the patient stood up and I told her we were still processing her significant other's vaccination at the other counter. I told her she can "relax and hang out in flu shot area" while we get his flu shot ready. After we processed his vaccine, I was preparing it at the counter in front of the flu shot station. Her significant other called for my attention and his arms were wrapped around her head and shoulders. This was approximately 5 minutes after administering her flu shot. She was becoming unconscious and she started urinating on herself. Immediately, I called for my technician to dial 911 and a team member. I declared to her significant other that I was going to administer the EpiPen and then administered it to her left thigh. She then regained consciousness and was able to speak to us. Her significant other questioned how much she ate that day and she only ate one meal. While we were waiting for EMS to arrive, I was monitoring her heart rate and breathing. When EMS arrived, she said she had a history of fainting in the past with a nose piercing and has become light-headed when getting blood drawn. On the vaccine screening and consent form, question #3 states. "Do you have a history of fainting, particularly with vaccines?" - she marked no as her answer. She was able to speak, eat, drink, and to stand up to be placed on the stretcher to be assessed by EMS. I called within 24 hours to follow-up with the patient but she did not pick up and I was only able to leave a message.
LAB_DATA: 10-16-20: EMS performed medical tests and vitals.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient, 2/22/1950, received a Fluzone HD vaccine at our pharmacy 10/18/20 at 12:04 pm.  Patient's wife called at 4:05 pm and stated that the patient was experiencing blurred vision and chest tightness/lump in his throat.  I immediately suggested that they call their PCP or go to an urgent care center in case it is an allergic reaction.  She asked if Benadryl was ok to give him. I stated that Benadryl would help if it's an allergic reaction but since he's having a lump feeling in his throat he may need something stronger.  The wife asked if this was common after the vaccine.  I checked facts and comparisons to see if there was information on this and explained to her that there is an oculorespiratory syndrome documented that begins within 2-24 hours after vaccine administration.  I told her that it stated that it was an acute self-limiting reaction that usually resolves within 48 hours and the symptoms include chest tightness, cough, wheezing, difficulty breathing, facial swelling, red eyes and sore throat.  I told her that even though it says it is self-limiting, I would still recommend they call their PCP or go to the urgent care to verify it isn't an allergic reaction or something else.  I also told her that I would document the reaction in his profile.

The patient stated over the phone that she had fever, swelling, soreness and rash around the injection site around 9:00 pm that same day. By morning the fever continued and the rash had started spreading to the front of her arm and up towards her shoulder in the shape of a "T" according to the patient. By the time the patient had called the pharmacy around 4:00 pm, her fever had decreased naturally without medication to 99 degrees, but the swelling, rash, and soreness were still present. She stated that she was starting to feel a little better but it still concerned her. She did not have any anaphylaxis symptoms involving swelling of the face, tongue, or throat at that time. After confirming that she was okay, she was instructed to take oral Benadryl for the reaction, apply hydrocortisone cream to the rash, and take Tylenol for the fever. If her symptoms did not continue to improve or got worse by the next morning, she was to contact her doctor or the emergency room depending on the severity of the symptoms. I called back an hour later to check on her condition. At this time she stated that she felt about the same as an hour ago, and the symptoms had not gotten worse. She forgot to apply hydrocortisone cream to the rash and did that while I was on the phone with her. She was able to repeat back her instructions without problem and understood to contact her doctor or the ER if her symptoms did not start to get better or resolve. During this time she informed that she had never had any issues previously with the influenza vaccine, but did not remember if she had any issues with the pneumonia vaccine since it was over 5 years ago since she had the first dose.

Patient received the vaccine in the left deltoid on 10/07. Patient noticed soreness in his deltoid muscle the day after the vaccine was given, on 10/8, but his pain increased dramatically in intensity on 10/15, roughly 1 week after the vaccine was administered. Patient described a burning sensation which began in his deltoid and radiated down his fingertips, and also radiated to his left scapular region. Patient applied a lidocaine patch to his left scapular region the evening of 10/15, and experienced temporary relief of the pain. However, the pain resumed on 10/17 and interrupted his sleep that night, and patient visited the pharmacy on 10/18. Examination of the patient revealed pinpoint tenderness in the central area of his deltoid muscle and mild warmth to the deltoid region. No redness, induration, or area of flocculance was observed.  Patient was able to abduct his arm 90 degrees easily. Patient was encouraged to continue the lidocaine patches, and also supplement with ibuprofen for 1 week for the pain. Patient was told to contact his primary care physician if his symptoms did not mostly resolve in 1 week's time.

Patient was solely breastfed. Patient became increasingly fussy and irritable immediately after his vaccines on 10/16/2017. His poops started looking and smelling very abnormal (and did not return to normal until months later after initiation of probiotics). on 11/25/2017 I checked his temperature for the first time ever rectally, he was 102. We went to the ER but they sent us home without doing any bloodwork.  Then 12/5/2017 we went to the ER again for fever (as the fevers never went away, they kept occurring daily) and his bloodwork showed he was Neutropenic. His fevers never went away, he had recurrent fevers which led to him being admitted to Hospital on 12/13/2017 for 2 days. It was there that it was discovered he was severely Neutropenic and he was put on Neutropenic precautions. His liver values were also out of range. He was discharged after 2 days later because he was otherwise thriving and there were no explanations for his fevers.  The fevers would frequently occur, almost daily, for months. There were several other trips to the ER per MD advice since that December admission. Further work-up showed his Immunoglobulins were low, his liver enzymes were consistently out of range, his Neutrophils were low several times.  He saw many specialists. We declined further vaccinations due to his recurrent fevers and abnormal bloodwork. An Immunologist, Dr., at Hospital eventually diagnosed Patient with Transient Hypogammaglobulinemia at 9 months of age.
LAB_DATA: There are hundreds of tests that were done by multiple specialists. I expect that if the review of my child's injury is to be properly investigated, as is moral and medical obligation, that his records will be pulled and reviewed by a medical professional. There are months worth of tests and tests results that i could not possibly list here. Please review his medical records as this is necessary for a true and accurate review of his adverse event.

She reported that she was sick in bed for 10 days after getting the dose, she thought that she was going to die, it was horrible and she was sicker than she was when she previously had the Flu (preferred term: Influenza).      She reported that she had Flu and chronic nose bleeds(preferred term: Epistaxis). She stated that within an hour of receiving the dose her nose started bleeding from her left nostril and she stuck a Kleenex in it and the bleeding stopped. She also stated that she thought blood was running down her throat because she started to feel nauseated (preferred term: Nausea) and was nauseated for the 10 days after she took the dose.  Two hours after the bleeding stopped in her left nostril she started to bleed from the right nostril.     She later had chronic bleeding from both nostrils and it was during this time that it was so hard to manage. The nose kept bleeding and on day 5 after getting the dose the bleeding was at the worst and the bleeding slowed down after day 7 when she started to feel better. Her HCP is aware and told her that it could have possibly been a reaction to the preservatives in Flumist (preferred term: Reaction to preservatives). HCP told her to take Ibuprofen for the fever. The fever came back down to 102 degrees Fahrenheit.      She also stated that she was really sick (preferred term: Malaise) for 3 days after she took the dose  and she gradually got better. She also stated that she was actively vomiting (preferred term: Vomiting) for 4 days. She started throwing up on day 2 after taking the dose and she lost 12 pounds (preferred term: Weight decreased) in those 10 days after taking the dose. She also stated that she had Covid 19 (preferred term: covid-19), start date was 09-Mar-2020. She did not get tested because there was no test available at that time. She stated that she only felt bad with Covid 19 for 5 days and she recovered. This case corresponds to table 1 reported in this literature article. The patient was a part of the study which described the clinical and virological responses to oseltamivir and baloxavir treatment in five allogeneic SCT recipients, and molecular characteristics of the influenza virus population before and after treatment. [It was used baloxavir to treat five allogeneic SCT recipients that were still symptomatic and shedding influenza virus after completing one or more treatment courses of oseltamivir and characterized the viral isolates before and during treatment. Allogeneic SCT patients with influenza A virus infection who received oseltamivir with no resolution of symptoms and were persistently positive for influenza A virus by the FilmArray Respiratory Pathogen two panel were included in the study]. The patient had a history of acute myeloid leukemia (AML). The patient underwent a matched related donor (MRD) stem cell transplant (SCT) in November 2016 conditioned with fludarabine, melphalan, and alemtuzumab and received tacrolimus as post-transplant graft-versus-host disease (GVHD) prophylaxis. Time duration from SCT was 2.12 years. The patient had active GVHD. The patient (setting) was from inpatient. The patient's post-transplant course was complicated by cytogenetic disease relapse at 1 year. The patient received two donor lymphocyte infusions, which successfully controlled her malignancy but resulted in GVHD necessitating prolonged immunosuppression with systemic steroids, tacrolimus, and ruxolitinib. No information on patient's family history was provided. The age of vaccination was not provided. On an unspecified date in end of December 2018, an unknown period after the vaccination, the patient was admitted to an outside hospital complaining of shortness of breath, cough, and fever to 39 degree Celsius for 2 days prior to admission. Nasopharyngeal swab in universal viral transport media (BD) was collected as part of routine clinical care. The patient was found to be positive for influenza A. Chest x-ray showed bilateral interstitial opacifications suggesting a possible superimposed bacterial pneumonia. The infection type was pneumonia. The patient required high flow oxygen and was admitted to the intensive care unit. The patient was treated with oseltamivir, broad-spectrum antibiotics, and steroids for possible acute respiratory distress syndrome. Blood cultures were negative. After 4 days, the patient was transferred to the hospital, and on admission, RP2 was positive for influenza A/H1pdm09 (Influenza A virus type: H1N1) and coronavirus 229E. The patient received immunosuppressive therapy at the time of influenza diagnosis included prednisone 20 mg once a day (QD)/Ruxolitinib 5 mg twice a day (BID), Tacrolimus. The patient did not receive Rituximab in prior 6 months. The co-pathogen included rhinovirus/enterovirus. Treatment with oseltamivir for 5 days and broad-spectrum antibiotics for possible bacterial superinfection was continued for 10 days of total course. Despite this treatment, the patient continued to experience profound fatigue, productive cough, and hypoxic respiratory failure requiring oxygen supplementation (2-4L). Chest computerized tomography (CT) performed 3 weeks after admission showed variable change in multilobar pneumonia with improvement within the left upper lobe and progression in the left lower lobe. Weekly RP2 panels during this period were positive for influenza A and coronavirus 229E. Because of the concern for oseltamivir-resistant influenza, the patient received baloxavir (80 mg), once. The patient's respiratory status, cough, and fatigue rapidly improved, and the patient was discharged home four days after baloxavir treatment. A RP2 panel performed at discharge was positive for influenza A/H1pdm09, but it was unable to detect the virus in the same specimen by real-time RT-PCR or next-generation sequencing. The patient missed follow-up appointments because of severe weather conditions and was readmitted for unrelated issues one month after discharge. At that time, the patient was asymptomatic and the RP2 panel was negative for influenza and still positive for coronavirus 229E. The influenza outcome was clearance. Neuraminidase sequence was H275Y and Polymerase sequence was WT (Wild-type). This case has been considered as suspected vaccination failure being the time to onset was unknown.  On an unspecified date in January 2020, the patient succumbed to fatal complications of GVHD. It was unknown whether the patient's autopsy was performed or not. [Nasopharyngeal swabs in universal viral transport media (BD) were collected as part of routine clinical care using standard procedures. Influenza was detected using the RP2 panel. Nucleic acid was isolated both using an automated platform (easyMAG) and using QIAamp kit in accordance with the manufacturers' protocols. Nucleic acids extracted using the easyMAG platform were tested by real-time reverse transcriptase-PCR to confirm the presence of influenza virus. Nucleic acids extracted using QIAamp kits were sequenced with next-generation sequencing methods for whole-genome analysis. A total of five patients who were both symptomatic and persistently positive for influenza A on the RP2 panel after receiving oseltamivir were treated with baloxavir. Oseltamivir was administered at the standard dose of 75 mg twice/day orally. Baloxavir was administered orally as a single or two doses of 40 or 80 mg, based on weight, according to manufacturer's instructions. All patients were profoundly immunocompromised because of allogeneic lymphodepleting SCT. In addition, two had received rituximab (monoclonal antibody directed to the lymphocyte surface protein CD20) within 6 months of influenza diagnosis, two had received prolonged immunosuppressive treatment for graft-versus-host disease (GVHD), and one was obese, a predisposing condition for severe influenza. All patients had coinfection with other pathogens, four of them had pneumonia and were hospitalized].  This case has been considered serious due to suspected vaccination failure, death and hospitalization. The author commented, "It has been repeatedly reported that the treatment of influenza in immunocompromised hosts is problematic, requiring prolonged treatment courses, causing an increased risk of the development of antiviral-resistant influenza variants. Moreover, because uncomplicated influenza in this patient population may present with few initial symptoms and no fever, the diagnosis is often delayed, and treatment with NAI is often initiated after the preferred 48-hour window from onset of symptoms. Baloxavir has been recently approved for the treatment of uncomplicated influenza. It has been shown that treatment with baloxavir is associated with a more rapid viral clearance. Here, we describe the treatment of five allogeneic SCT recipients with baloxavir who were still positive for influenza A after oseltamivir treatment. In 4 of these subjects, including those with demonstrated oseltamivir-resistant variants, treatment with baloxavir was followed by clinical improvement and viral clearance. Three patients did not have any detectable NAI resistance-associated changes in the influenza viruses sequenced at the time they received baloxavir, and we cannot exclude the possibility that more prolonged oseltamivir treatment may have also been effective for symptom resolution and viral clearance. We found that one of the treated subjects developed a PA variant after two doses of baloxavir. Although the patient improved and eventually cleared the infection, the potential for transmission of variant virus raises concern. Despite the small patient number and the lack of a control group, our data suggest that baloxavir may be a useful treatment option for infections with influenza virus with NAI-resistant variants, and/or in SCT patients who fail NAI treatment for other reasons. Combination therapy, including baloxavir and oseltamivir, has shown synergistic activity in vitro. This treatment option might be more effective and may decrease the emergence of resistant influenza variants in the immunocompromised host." The author concluded, "Our data suggest that baloxavir treatment can be effective in treating neuraminidase inhibitor-resistant influenza in profoundly immunocompromised patients. Randomized clinical trials are needed to define the role of baloxavir alone and combined with oseltamivir for the treatment of influenza in SCT recipients and other immunocompromised populations." This is 1 of the 3 valid cases reported in the same literature article.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020GSK205640:Same reporter US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020GSK205641:Same reporter; Reported Cause(s) of Death: death NOS

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Suspected vaccination failure; Shingles/ came down with shingles; This case was reported by a consumer and described the occurrence of suspected vaccination failure in a 63-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis. On an unknown date, the patient received Shingrix and Humira (subcutaneous) at an unknown dose and frequency. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant) and shingles. The action taken with Humira was unknown. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure was unknown and the outcome of the shingles was recovering/resolving.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure and shingles to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were reported as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient received shingrix vaccine and humira and experienced shingles. The reporter did not have the lot number information for humira because the packaging was discarded. The reporter's causality for the event shingle with humira was no reasonable possibility. No concomitant drugs taken by patient. No relevant medical history was reported. No known allergies were reported. This case was considered as suspected vaccination failure as details regarding vaccination schedule, time to onset for target disease and laboratory confirmation were unknown at the time of reporting.

Atrial fibrillation; allergic reaction; flu like symptoms; This spontaneous report was received from a 79 years old male patient referring to himself. The patient had none concomitant medication. Pertinent medical history was reported as atrial fibrillation.   On an unknown date in 2020, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) (Single dose 0.5 ml; route, lot# and expiration date were not reported) given in the arm for preventative measures.     The patient went to his local pharmacy and was given the flu shot and the pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) vaccine. On 04-OCT-2020 (reported as 10 days ago), later that day the patient experienced an allergic reaction were his elbow swelled and it was red (also reported allergic reaction to pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23)). The reaction lasted about 3 days. He also had flu like symptoms which included a fever, aches and pains. The patient explained that he had atrial fibrillation issues as well but he believed that was due to not drinking enough water and staying hydrated and explained that if he did not stay hydrated he had issues with his atrial fibrillation. No treatment was given for AE. The patient had lab diagnostics/studies performed, he had them done annually. Outcome of the events was recovered on an unknown date in October 2020 (reported as 3 days). The patient had not sought medical attention.   The causal relationship between the pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) and the events was not provided.  Upon internal review, atrial fibrillation was determined to be medically significant.

Fainted; nauseous; Felt faint; very pale; Incoherent; Confused; Clearing throat multiple times; This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of fainting in a 12-year-old female patient who received DTPa (Reduced antigen) (Boostrix) (batch number H535B, expiry date 25th September 2021) for prophylaxis. Previously administered products included Dtap vaccine (received on an unknown date) and Flu vaccine (received on an unknown date).   On 12th October 2020, the patient received Boostrix (intramuscular) and FluLaval Tetra 2020-2021 season. On 12th October 2020, less than a day after receiving Boostrix and FluLaval Tetra 2020-2021 season and an unknown time after starting Albuterol, the patient experienced fainting (serious criteria GSK medically significant), nausea, felt faint, pallor, incoherent, confusion and throat clearing. The patient was treated with salbutamol sulphate (Albuterol), dexamethasone and oxygen. On 12th October 2020, the outcome of the fainting and felt faint were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the nausea, pallor, incoherent, confusion and throat clearing were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the fainting, nausea, felt faint, pallor, incoherent, confusion and throat clearing to be related to Boostrix and FluLaval Tetra 2020-2021 season. After coming, she was incoherent, confused and clearing her throat multiple times. Albuterol dexamethasone and oxygen administered. The reporter consented to follow up.

she believes her husband almost went into anaphylactic shock; flu-like symptoms; fever; shivering; softball sized lump under his right arm / in the armpit; fatigue; Swelling of right arm and hand; Pain was also overlapping in the neck and spine; Pain was also overlapping in the neck and spine; pain in the right arm and hand, specially the hand / pain /in his arm and hand /; This case was reported by a physician via call center representative and described the occurrence of anaphylactic shock in a 51-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included shingrix (1st dose received on unknown date in January or February of this year.).   In June 2020, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On 18th September 2020, less than 4 months after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced swelling arm, neck pain, pain in spine and pain in extremity. On an unknown date, the patient experienced anaphylactic shock (serious criteria GSK medically significant), influenza-like symptoms, fever, shivering, axillary lump and fatigue. The patient was treated with prednisone. On an unknown date, the outcome of the anaphylactic shock, influenza-like symptoms, fever and shivering were unknown and the outcome of the swelling arm, neck pain, pain in spine, pain in extremity, axillary lump and fatigue were not recovered/not resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the anaphylactic shock, swelling arm, neck pain, pain in spine, pain in extremity, influenza-like symptoms, fever, shivering, axillary lump and fatigue to be related to Shingrix.  Additional case details were reported as follows: The reporter was patient's wife (consumer) and physician. The patient received first Shingrix injection in January or February of this year. After first injection she stated that there were no concerns. The patient had the second dose administered at a pharmacy at an unknown date. The second injection of Shingrix was received in the first week of June but she could not remember the exact day for either injections.  The patient had developed persistent swelling of the arm and hand after the second dose of Shingrix. Patient assisted to the emergency room on 18th September 2020 due to the pain present in the hand and arm. The pain was also overlapping in the neck and spine.  The second injection he received in his right arm caused a softball sized lump under his right arm, along with pain, and swelling in his arm and hand.  The patient then attended reporter's clinic and reporter prescribed Prednisone on 20th September 2020. The reporter confirmed that patient still presented at day of report swelling and pain in the right arm and hand, specially the hand.  The patient also experienced flu-like symptoms with fever, shivering, fatigue, and pain. The reporter stated that she believes her husband almost went into anaphylactic shock. She stated that they saw the patient's (her husband) doctors but no one knew what was going on and that her husband still had fatigue, pain, swelling, and the lump under his right arm, in the armpit.  The reporter wanted to know if others had these issues. The reporter consented to follow up.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020AMR206672:same patient, same reporter, 1st dose

Severe pain in upper right arm. Unable to lift arm fully starting Tuesday night. Mild fever started Tuesday evening increased to 102 on Wednesday and Thursday. Pain in arm began moving lower in muscle on Thursday including new redness goind down my arm and away from injection site and skin was sore to the touch similar to a sunburn. I went to urgent care and they diagnosed me with an infection. Fever had subsided slightly by then but returned to nearly 102 later that night. Started anti-biotics Thursday evening and by Saturday I finally started getting some relief. No fever after Saturday but arm was very weak. Could not hold my cell phone or do any regular lifting or use of my arm. Had cold feelings in waves inside my arm and down the side of my arm Saturday. On Sunday, strength seemed a little better but I had to keep my arm in a resting position on my leg or by laying down or I would experience sharp pains in my shoulder and back similar to over exertion. Today (Monday) right shoulder is sore, under my arm is sore and still feel some pain in back shoulder blade and some soreness in my right pec. Arm is still weak. No fever since Saturday. Still taking anti-biotics for another 4 days. I contacted pharmacy and they were less than interested in hearing these issues.
LAB_DATA: Visual diagnosis from the doctor at urgent care.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2 days after injections, parent called pediatricians office with concerns about warmth, redness, pain, and swelling at the injection site. Pt came in for exam and was noted to have 7-8 cm diameter of erythema to right thigh. He  was diagnosed with cellulitis and given Keflex for 5 days

SYMPTOM_TEXT: No further AE; temperature excursion involving multiple lot numbers for GARDASIL 9, MMR II, ROTATEQ, and RECOMBIV AX. Many of the vaccines have been administered to patients; This spontaneous report was received from a practice manger and refers to a patient of unknown age and gender. The patient's pertinent medical history, drug reactions, allergies and concomitant medications were not reported.  On 04-AUG-2020, the patient was vaccinated with improperly stored dose of rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ), lot #1660991, expiration date: 27-APR-2021, dose: 1 injection (exact dose, dose #, route of administration and anatomical location were not reported) for prophylaxis.  On 04-AUG-2020, the dose of vaccine was exposed to temperature excursion at 1.1 Celsius degree (C) for 27 hours and 45 minutes and at 9 Celsius degrees for 1 hour and 15 minutes. There were no previous excursions reported. The call was due to digital data logger. No further adverse events were reported.  This is one of multiple reports received from the same reporter.; Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-2010USA001083:Same Reporter

Obtained seasonal flu shot at Pharmacy located at the store location at approx. 4PM on Friday, October 16, 2020. Injected in left upper shoulder. At approx. 7:30pm the same evening, I began having problems breathing and my neck and chest were blotchy red with what looked like hives, but not itchy just hot to the touch. My throat tightened, and my voice became very raspy, and my lips began to tingle but were not swollen. I began coughing to clear my throat, and drinking cold water, but the odd feeling continued to progress. I took my temperature at approx 8:15pm on the same evening and did not have any noticeable change, but my heart rate was increasing. By 8:30pm I called an urgent care facility to obtain their advice, as my primary physician's office was closed. The admin nurse listened as I recounted my situation of getting a flu shot earlier in the afternoon. She suggested I immediately go to the Emergency Room and if I had a Benadryl tablet, to take that immediately before leaving for the ER. I did take one 25mg Benadryl. I arrived at the ER approx 8:50pm, and was immediately triaged. I was admitted by 9:15pm, after having an IV line placed in my left arm. The attending nurse placed EKG leads on my chest to monitor my heart rate and pulse oxygen rate. By approx. 10:34pm the decision was made to give me (all via IV): diphenhydramine, famotidine, and methylprednisolone sodium succinate. The ER doctor on duty, visited with me at approx 11:15pm, at which time I was improving and the most alarming of the symptoms were regressing. I was discharged at approx. 11:45pm and was given a prescription of Prednisone (pill form) to take over the next 5 days to ensure the anaphylaxis symptoms stayed in check. As of Saturday,  October 17th, I was feeling much better and back to normal.
LAB_DATA: Other than being on the EKG and pulse oxygen to check my rates, there were no addition tests or lab results performed.
OTHER_MEDS: Multivitamin, 250 mg magnesium, 1000mg fish oil (all daily).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Upper back pain, stiff neck, body aches

I started getting very sore in my left arm about an hour after the shot.  By 7 PM, I developed a 101 fever, chills, body aches throughout and a very bad headache.  I started taking Tylenol at 9:30 and by 6:30 the next morning, the fever was down to 99 but aches and headache still present.  Went to local clinic thinking could potentially be covid.  Was tested negative for Covid.  Asked doctor there if this could be reaction to flu shot and she said no, only if it was an aerosol.  Continued to take tylenon for next day to deal with aches and headache.  Fever was back to normal by Friday morning.  Friday morning I reached out to my doctor, explained symptoms and they said it was most likely a reaction to the shot.

ER documentation:From RN:  Attempted to return phone call to patient.  Left a voice mail message.  Will try to reach pt one more time.   Returned phone call to 39 year old patient.  Pt states she has a history of multiple sclerosis.  Pt states she received the DTP vaccine 10/15/20, and has been experiencing several side effects.  Pt states her temp was 103 ( TA ) this morning, and is currently 99.4.  States she is experiencing slight body aches, and a persistent frontal headache.  Rates headache 2/10 currently, but states ibuprofen is not helping.  Pt states her fingers and toes were feeling numb and tingling earlier, but that has ceased.  Denies weakness on one side of the body.  Denies blurred, or double vision.  Denies a rash, or vomiting.  States headache is interfering with her normal activities.  Denies difficulty breathing, or swallowing.  Denies chest pain, or fainting.  Denies swelling in back of throat, or tongue.  Denies palpitations.  Reviewed immunization, tetanus and headache, disposition seek medical care within 24 hours.  I advised pt to go to urgent care to be assessed.  Pt verbalizes understanding, but wants to speak with the on call provider.  I instructed pt to call back if no response from on call within 30 minutes.  Pt verbalizes understanding.   From MD Spoke to patient yesterday.  Already feeling better by time of call and temp around 99 degrees.  Taking Advil helps with chills and aches.  She has NO respiratory symptoms and Tmax of about 103 was transient (resolved without meds it seems).  I think very unlikely to be flu or COVID and given the timing of symptoms, most likely a vaccine reaction.  Will add Tdap to her chart and have office file a report.  She agreed to call back immediately with any worsening symptoms, fever that goes back up or if symptoms haven't resolved by Monday.  She's in agreement with plan.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: pneumonia; Information has been received from a lawyer referring to a female patient of unknown age. Information about concurrent condition, history condition and concomitant medication was not reported. On or around 12-SEP-2014, the patient was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (strength, dose, route, lot# and expiration date unknown) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). Shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient was diagnosed with pneumonia. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient's symptoms have resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using the vaccine. The patient also experiences mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of her condition. As a result of the manufacture, marketing, advertising, promotion, distribution and/or sale of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient has suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the event pneumonia was considered to be not recovered and causal relationship was assessed as related.    The lawyer considered the event pneumonia to be disability.   Upon internal review, pneumonia was determined to be medically significant.

Central nervous system demyelination; Information has been received from the authors of the published literature article, titled as stated below.  Since its inception, the polyvalent vaccine against the Quadrivalent human papilloma virus (HPV), HPV rL1 6 11 16 18 VLP vaccine (yeast), has generated some controversies as a temporal relationship between the administrations of the vaccine and the development of a few autoimmune diseases, such as acute disseminated encephalomyelitis (ADEM), multiple sclerosis (MS) and Guillain-Barre syndrome have been reported. There are two cases whose initial presentation of central nervous system (CNS) demyelination followed in close time relationship the administration of Quadrivalent Human Papillomavirus (Types 6,11,16,18) Recomb. Vaccine (GARDASIL).  The patient in this report is the first case- a 19-year-old woman who received two doses of Quadrivalent Human Papillomavirus (Types 6,11,16,18) Recomb. Vaccine (GARDASIL), 3 months apart, and approximately 1 month after the second dose, she developed numbness to the right foot that within 1 day extended to the contralateral foot and was associated with mid-thoracic back  pain. Her neurological examination was only significant for the altered perception to touch to the feet. Deep tendon reflexes were normal and plantar reflexes in flexion. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of cervical and thoracic spine revealed a total of three lesions with characteristic demyelinating appearance, one of those in the thoracic spine was contrast-enhancing. MRI brain demonstrated one additional white matter lesion also consistent with a demyelinating process. Antinuclear antibody titers and serology for Treponema pallidum and Borrelia burgdorferi were negative; angiotensin converting enzyme (ACE) levels, vitamin B12 and folate levels were normal. Cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) was never tested. The patient was treated in the acute setting with high doses of intravenous methylprednisolone and clinical improvement ensued. Demyelinating disease was felt to be the likely diagnosis and approximately 4 months later treatment with natalizumab was initiated. The patient has remained clinically asymptomatic afterwards but the repeated MRI brain at 1 year showed new lesions in the white matter of both hemispheres and a small contrast enhancing area in the right frontal lobe. The patient tested positive for anti-natalizumab antibodies and the medication was discontinued. Alternative therapy for Multiple Sclerosis (MS) has been instituted.   Since agency approval in June 2006, Quadrivalent Human Papillomavirus (Types 6,11,16,18) Recomb. Vaccine (GARDASIL) has been implicated in the development of acute inflammatory polyneuropathy, MS and ADEM. It has been reported that 12 million doses of HPV vaccines have been distributed and 7802 adverse events were recorded. Of the 10 confirmed cases of Guillain-Barre syndrome, five had received concurrent administration of meningococcal ACYW conj vaccine (dip toxoid) (MENACTRA).  The first case reported here was concerning for causality, as no medical problems were present prior to the administration of the vaccine and the criteria for the diagnosis of MS are met on follow-up MRI scan. In the second case, the development of sensory symptoms approximately 3 weeks before exposure to Quadrivalent Human Papillomavirus (Types 6,11,16,18) Recomb. Vaccine (GARDASIL) poses the question of a pre-existing condition, unmasked by the trauma, reaching its full expression in coincidence with the vaccination.  Administration of Quadrivalent Human Papillomavirus (Types 6,11,16,18) Recomb. Vaccine (GARDASIL) exacerbated the clinical course of three patients who had already manifested neurological symptoms consistent with clinically isolated syndrome and converted to clinically definite MS after the vaccination. A case of ADEM following exposure to HPV vaccine was recently reported and under the assumption that ADEM and MS share some pathophysiological and clinical features, it is conceivable that an immunological stimulus capable of inducing a monophasic deregulated immune response in the CNS could potentially lead to a relapsing-remitting chronic course.  It is plausible that in genetically predisposed individuals, the immunological stimulus of a vaccine or even some immunomodulatory therapies may lead to a deranged immune response that could theoretically trigger an autoimmune disease. In this view, the particularly aggressive course of disease demonstrated by the patient in case No 2 could be the result of such a stimulation that could not be controlled with a first line immunomodulatory therapy.  Quadrivalent Human Papillomavirus (Types 6,11,16,18) Recomb. Vaccine (GARDASIL) has raised no concerns about the risks of transmission of the HPV and the benefits of vaccines are undeniable as several diseases can only be treated by active vaccinations. HPV is the causative agent of a potentially highly morbid illness and its prevention will have a large social impact. Considering the overall limited number of adverse events recorded thus far, it is likely that the benefits outweigh the risks of complications. However, we feel that collecting long term data on the effectiveness of the HPV vaccine and documenting the adverse events is imperative.  Upon internal review, the patient's adverse event was determined to be other important medical event since it was treated with intravenous methylprednisolone.  This is one of several reports received from the same source. The second patient was captured in MARRS# 1110USA01072.  Literature report: Demyelinating disease and polyvalent human papilloma virus vaccination. Nov2011  All telephone attempts to obtain follow-up information have been unsuccessful. Additional information has been requested.  Follow up information has been received on 13-OCT-2020 via a social media post. A consumer posted the aforementioned article with a comment "Acute disseminated encephalomyelitis after Quadrivalent Human Papillomavirus (Types 6,11,16,18) Recomb. Vaccine (GARDASIL)". No additional information was reported.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my flu shot on 10/15/2020.  Afterwards the area became red, swollen and hot to the touch.   The next day, 10/16/2020, the redness and swelling had spread, it had also hardened into a knot and it was still hot to the touch.  By the evening of 10/16/2020 the area was continuing to grow in size.  I marked the outside edges with a sharpie marker to be able to determine how much it was increasing in size and also took some pictures.   The next morning, 10/17/2020, the area had only increased slightly in size and the redness had drastically decreased but was still hard and hot to the touch.   On 10/18/2020 the area wasn?t red but had more of a purple hue deep under the skin.  It was less swollen but still hard and it wasn?t as hot as it had been.  A few times throughout the day on 10/18/2020 I reached behind me for something or reached over my head into a cabinet.  Each time I would get what felt like a sharp muscle cramp that started at the injection site and shoot down the back and front side of my upper arm. On 10/19/2020 the area is still hard but less swollen, only slightly warm to the touch and is not discolored but it has a constant aching pain at the injection site.  When I dropped my daughter off at school I tried to reach behind me to pick up her lunch box from the back seat (something I can normally do with no issues) and had severe pain, starting at the injection site and going down the front and back of my upper arm.  I also had no strength and couldn?t pick up the lunchbox.  The remainder of the day movement in any direction caused increased pain starting from the injection site and going down the front and back of my upper arm.  I took ibuprofen, 600 mg, three times throughout the day on 10/18/2020.  Each time it helped for a few hours but then the pain would come back.    On 10/20/2020 there is a discolored area that is a faint brown color at the injection site.  There is still a constant aching pain at the injection site.  When I move my arm, I get a shooting pain down the front of my arm to the bend at the elbow and up the arm to my shoulder.  There is no longer any pain down the back of my arm.
LAB_DATA: Have not seen a doctor or healthcare provider for the reaction at this time.

Patient, never having previously used the pharmacy, contacted the pharmacy on the evening of 10/18/2020 with the complaint of having had shoulder pain over the last two weeks after having received a flu vaccine on Tuesday 10/06/2020. Patient stated that she has gotten the flu vaccine before and never had any problems. She also stated she knows that if the vaccine isn't given in the correct location, that it could cause an injury. She says that the day after receiving the vaccine, her arm became red and swollen until that Friday 10/09/2020 and that since then, the redness and swelling has resolved, but she has had progressively worsening pain since then. She says that the pain is present both with and without movement but is most notable in the sitting position. Patient was advised by pharmacist to seek medical attention if deemed necessary. On Tuesday 10/20/2020 patient contacted the pharmacy to update that she is beginning to feel a lump in the area where the vaccine was administered and that she has scheduled an appointment with an orthopedic doctor for Wednesday 10/21/2020. She will follow up with the pharmacy on any pertient details or results of the appointment.  The immunizing pharmacist has undergone injection technique training and completed a quality care check on vaccine administration. Upon watching surveillance footage of the time the patient presented for the vaccine, the camera angle does not allow full visibility to the entire event to determine if the vaccine was administered in the right location of the deltoid. However, it was noted that the patient was wearing a short sleeve shirt and therefore most likely rolled the sleeve up above her shoulder to expose the entire deltoid muscle. Typically, shoulder injury related to vaccine administration is more likely if the patient is wearing a long sleeve shirt that they aren't able to fully roll up above the shoulder or if they are pulling their shirt down at the neckline because in both instances, the deltoid muscle is not fully exposed. This was not the case with this patient. After having received the vaccine, the patient can clearly be seen walking away unremarkably, never holding her arm or appearing to be in any distress or discomfort from being immunized.

A patient received the MMR vaccine on 07/09/20 at 16:19. Unit RN called  doctor at 18:38 reporting itching from the patient. Vitals were within normal limits. Patient was given 50 mg diphenhydramine, which patient noted was effective. Doctor followed up with patient on 07/10/20. Left ventral forearm had no visible rash, and patient noted rash on right forearm was gone. Abdomen was also free of rash. Patient noted rash on their forehead and chin/neck area. The chin/neck area was affected by wearing a face mask and sweating. Their forehead was erythematous and had acne present. Patient noted the rash arose after receiving the vaccine and was not present before the injection. Patient denied any shortness of breath with rash. Rash was presumed to be due to MMR vaccine. Hydroxyzine was increased to 50 mg TID and 50 mg hydroxyzine 50 mg q24h PRN itching was added to help with further itching. Patient was marked with MMR vaccine allergy. One dose PRN hydroxyzine given 07/11/20, symptoms improved. Per the product insert, M-M-R II vaccine has skin-related adverse effects listed as SJS, erythema multiforme, urticarial, rash, measles-like rash, pruritus, injection site reactions (pain, erythema, swelling and vesiculation). No percentages accompany these adverse effects. This was rated as possible.

They listened to heart and lungs and did not perform a COVID test. They said the onset was not in keeping with the COVID's onset, and I had been exposed and have been very careful being almost 68 years old. I slept all day Friday, as well as most of Saturday and Sunday. Yesterday, 10/5, I started feeling somewhat better but was still very sore in the injection areas and back of my neck. My wife received her annual influenza immunization yesterday at pharmacy at approximately 11: 30 am 08/31/2020. She was immunized with AFLURIA PFS 2020-21 INJ 0.5ML manufactured by SEQIRUS administered intramuscularly in the deltoid area of her left arm. She noticed no adverse effects initially. At approximately 4:30 pm she developed a very uncomfortable fullness in her throat making it hard for her to swallow and drink. She described it as "like having a whole kiwi fruit stuck in her throat". I gave her two 25 mg. Benadryl (diphenhydramine) capsules orally. In about an hour the uncomfortable fullness began to decrease. By 10 pm the uncomfortable fullness was almost gone. The next morning she was back to normal. My wife experienced the same thing one year ago when she received her influenza immunization. The fullness last year was more severe following her receiving the "extra strength" vaccine. Flulaval Quadrivalent (Influenza Vaccine) Product Malfunction in a one-week period beginning on October 4, 2020, our facility received approximately five reports of Flulaval Quadrivalent leaking drug at the at the hub of the syringe. Most cases were noted to have been caught prior to reaching patients. However, in one specific occurrence, the needle was inserted into the patient's deltoid and the syringe plunger was depressed. However, the entire dose escaped from the hub resulting in an insufficient administration. Upon further investigation, it was determined that the needle was indeed appropriately secured to the syringe. Note that the lot # provided only pertains to one associated incident. The products in the other incidents were not isolated. Further, the drug manufacturer representative has been contacted and scheduled to meet with pharmacy leadership in the coming weak.

On 10-SEP-2020 at around 16:30, the patient was vaccinated with measles, mumps, rubella and varicella (oka-merck) virus vaccine live (PROQUAD) once (lot # T013536, expiry date: 17-OCT-2021; dose was not reported) subcutaneously in the right arm for prophylaxis. On the same day, he also received diphtheria toxoid, pertussis acellular 3-component vaccine, poliovirus vaccine inactivated (vero), tetanus toxoid (KINRIX) intramuscularly in the left arm (dose, frequency and indication were not reported).   On that day, he had allergic reaction. At around 18:00 at the dinner table before he ate anything, he became acutely congested, drooling, and he sounded as if he had marbles in his mouth. The mother gave the boy diphenhydramine hydrochloride (BENADRYL), and about 10 minutes after he seemed spaced out for a brief time period. On an unspecified date in September 2020, the patient's symptoms resolved with no residual effects, and he has not had any prior vaccine reactions. Action taken with suspect therapies was not applicable.   The causality between the events and suspect therapies was not reported.

PNEUMONIA; Afib heart condition; This spontaneous report has been received from a currently 98-year-old female consumer concerning herself. Her current conditions included asthma, hypersensitivity, allergy to vaccine, iodine allergy, drug hypersensitivity, food allergy and seasonal allergy. Her historical medication included penicillin.   On an unknown date in 2002, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX 23), 1 dosage form ( reported as 1 vaccination), via intramuscular as prophylaxis (reported as for pneumococcal disease) (lot number and expiry date were unknown by the reporter).         On an unknown date in 2018, the patient experienced a light case of pneumonia (also reported as a small case of pneumonia) which cause her to be taken to the hospital for precaution, however, the small case of pneumonia turned into an atrial fibrillation heart condition.   The outcome of pneumonia and atrial fibrillation was reported as recovered but the recovery date was unknown by the reporter.     The causal relationship between Pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX 23) and the occurrence of pneumonia and atrial fibrillation was considered related.   Upon internal review, pneumonia and atrial fibrillation were considered medically significant events.

permanent vision loss; deteriorating vision; herpes zoster; This spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation referring to a patient (pt) of unknown age and gender. No information about current condition, historical condition and concomitant medication was provided. On or about 26-FEB-2014, the pt was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (dose, strength, route, batch/lot# and expiration date were unknown) at a pharmacy for the long-term prevention of shingles and zoster-related conditions. Subsequently, the pt was treated by a provider for the following injuries resulting from the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) use: herpes zoster, deteriorating vision and permanent vision loss.
