ADMINISTERING MORE THAN PRESCRIBED/DRUG OVERDOSE; NOSE DRIPPAGE OUT OF NOSTRIL THAT RECEIVED FULL DOSE; FULL DOSE ADMINISTERED IN ONE NOSTRIL; NOT FOLLOWING IFU; ADMINISTERED ANOTHER HALF DOSE INTO THE OTHER NOSTRIL; A spontaneous report has been received from a pharmacist. The report concerns a male patient (age 18 years).    No medical history was reported.     No concomitant products were reported.    The patient received Flumist Quadrivalent (influenza virus vaccine live, intranasal) (batch number MH2024) 0.2 ml once/single administration, via nasal route, for vaccine for influenza on 03-OCT-2020.     The report described a medication error for Flumist Quadrivalent. The reported term was "full dose administered in one nostril" (Preferred term: Product administration error). The reported term was "not following ifu" (Preferred term: Wrong technique in product usage process). The report described an overdose for Flumist Quadrivalent. The reported term was "administering more than prescribed/drug overdose" (Preferred term: Overdose) and administered another half dose into the other nostril (Preferred term: Intentional product misuse).    On 03-OCT-2020, the patient experienced nose drippage out of nostril that received full dose (preferred term: Rhinorrhoea).     The outcome of the event(s) of administering more than prescribed/drug overdose, nose drippage out of nostril that received full dose, full dose administered in one nostril, not following ifu and administered another half dose into the other nostril was unknown.     The events were considered non-serious.     The reporter considered the following event(s) related to treatment with Flumist Quadrivalent (influenza virus vaccine live, intranasal): not following ifu.    Summary of follow-up information received by AstraZeneca/MedImmune 13-Oct-2020 received from Pharmacist via spontaneous: Reporter causality added for event not following IFU. Lot number updated for suspect FluMist. Start date of vaccine FluMist updated to 03-Oct-2020 from 04-Oct-2020. Event onset date updated to 03-Oct-2020 for event not following IFU and event onset date 03-Oct-2020 updated for rest of events. Reporter case ID added. Reporter middle name and address updated for Pharmacist. The patient demographic details added. Form completed date updated as follow up. Narrative updated. Corrected report on 16-Oct-2020: Reporter type corrected to patient from patient assistance program for second reporter Valid null flavors added to Reporter 6 (Reference). Overdose ticked on product add info. Order of events and association corrected. general flu like; loss of appetite; shaking on and off; tingling in arms; muscle weakness; general malaise; nausea; muscles aching of left arm left leg; feeling cold then hot; weight loss; Initial information received on 02-Oct-2020 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a consumer or non-healthcare professional.  This case involves a 66-years-old female patient who experienced feeling cold then hot (Feeling of body temperature change), weight loss (weight decreased), general flu like symptoms (influenza like illness), loss of appetite (decreased appetite), shaking on and off (tremor), tingling in arms (paraesthesia), muscle weakness (muscular weakness), general malaise (malaise), nausea, muscles aching of left arm left leg (myalgia), while she received vaccine RABIES (HDC) VACCINE [IMOVAX RABIES].  The patient's medical history, past medical treatment, vaccination, and family history were not provided.  The patient had a bat in her room and woke up with a scratch on her neck. She was unsure if she was bitten by the bat.  Concomitant medication included HyperRab.   The patient received first, second, third and fourth dose of suspect RABIES (HDC) VACCINE (lot number and expiry date not reported) via an intramuscular route in an arm NOS (not otherwise specified) for prophylactic vaccination on 24-Aug-2020, 27-Aug-2020, 31-Aug-2020 and 07-Sep-2020 respectively.   In Aug-2020, the patient developed a non-serious feeling cold then hot (Feeling of body temperature change), weight loss (weight decreased), general flu like symptoms (influenza like illness), loss of appetite (decreased appetite), shaking on and off (tremor), tingling in arms (paraesthesia), muscle weakness (muscular weakness), general malaise (malaise), nausea, muscles aching of left arm and left leg (myalgia) 3 days after each of the 1st, 2nd and 3rd dose of RABIES (HDC) VACCINE.  The patient experienced the symptoms again 10 days after her 4th vaccine that lasted for 7 days.  Relevant laboratory test: blood work and X-rays results came back normal.  The patient had to go to the emergency room (ER) twice due to these symptoms.  The ER gave her fluids.  At the time of this report, the patient had not recovered from events.  There will be no information available on the batch number for this case.

On an unknown date, the patient developed a non-serious almost flu like symptoms (influenza like illness) and just threw up and had virus one right after another (vomiting) on an unknown latency following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE.  Case details:  Reporter would like to know if either of the Flu vaccines are egg free because her husband is allergic to eggs and if FLUBLOK QUADRIVALENT is egg free. It was not reported if the patient received a corrective treatment.  The outcome was unknown for both the events.  There will be no information available on the batch number for this case.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Saturday, October 3, 2020  Flucelvax given 13:00 IM Left arm  Monday, Oct 5 Extreme fatigue in evening  Tuesday, Oct 6 Awakes with drenched pillow, has myalgias and chills in the morning at work, some relief with apap.  Returns home with extreme chills, no fever.  Begins isolation at home.  Wednesday, Oct 7 Chills and sweats.  Covid tests at hospital collected  Thursday, Oct  Chills and night sweats.  Friday, Oct 8 Chills and night sweats 2 neg Covid tests resulted.  Saturday Multiple night sweats, drenching and requiring 3-4 changes of clothes.  Discovered painful left axillary lymph nodes in morning.  Rides bike  Sunday 10/11/20 Night sweats, changing clothes, functional during the day  Monday 10/12/20 Night sweats Sees Dr in afternoon.  Tuesday 10/13/20 Night sweats  Wednesday 10/14/20 Night sweats decreasing,  only one change by morning Attempts to have blood test, refused at lab because covid test was also ordered - employee states that tests cannot be drawn until covid done and negative.  He states that he has 2 negative test posted in the last week, but is still denied.  Confirmed by Dr that this is not lab policy. Gets CXR in the evening at hospital  and starts Zpak at beditime.  Thursday 10/15/20 Awakes in am- no night sweats! Has blood drawn at lab.  Friday 10/16/20 Feeling better, no night sweats.  Continues Zpak.
LAB_DATA: 10/14/20 CXR no acute process CBC, CRP, ESR, Lyme AB IGG/IGM, Ehrlichia AB panel, Bartonella HenselaeAB IGG IGM :  all within normal limits Hepatic panel elevated AST 62 U/L (ref 10-35) and ALT 168 U/L (ref 9-46), but otherwise within normal limits

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within a few hours of receiving the vaccination I started to feel dizzy and light headed, my arms and legs also began to feel weak which was accompanied by a severe headache later that evening. The following day my symptoms seemed to have gotten worst I had a fever along with joint pain and muscle spasms by mid afternoon I started to have chest pains and heart palpitations within next few hours my symptoms continued to get worst they were accompanied with swelling of my lips and an even more rapid heartbeat. I remember going upstairs to sit down and before I made it to the couch I had passed out, I do not recall the length of time but by the time I came to the ambulance was at our home. They completed the regular first responders assessment and advised me that If I continue have cheat pain, to feel light headed or weak that I should go to the hospital. I then made an initial appointment with hospital which at that point I was scheduled for follow up x-rays and examinations. I had never received the flu shot prior, and I had never had any medical issues, on any medication and neither does my family have any history of any medical complications. I exercise 4 to 5 times per week and live and maintain a healthy lifestyle and diet, I do not consume alcohol or smoke. In the months that followed I continue to have unexplained frequently occurring chest pains, shortness of breath and heart palpitations.
LAB_DATA: Stress test, blood test and chest scans. First quarter 2015

After being home for sometime, the patient's wife stated that he started losing vision in left eye. They consulted with a doctor and were told to go to the hospital. The patient's wife stated that he was admitted and several tests were done to check for blockage/or stroke. All tests are coming back normal. The patient is remaining in hospital for more tests to be done. Unknown if this was caused by either vaccine.

passed out cold and was snoring; passed out cold and was snoring; vomiting; This spontaneous report was received from a vaccine coordinator/nurse via a field representative and refers to a 15-year-old female patient. She was in good health and had no significant medical history. Her concomitant therapies included influenza virus vaccine (unspecified) (reported as flu vaccine). There was no information about patient's drug reactions and allergies.  On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) (exact dose, frequency, lot#, expiration date anatomical location and route of administration were not reported). No problems were noted after the first vaccination. On 12-OCT-2020, the patient was vaccinated with the second dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9), 0.5 milliliter, via intramuscular route (frequency, lot #, expiration date and anatomical location were not reported) as vaccination against human papilloma virus (HPV). On the same day, within 5 minutes after vaccination, the patient passed out cold and was snoring. It was stated that when the patient came to, she started vomiting. The patient had not eaten anything prior to coming to the office. She did not seek medical attention and did not receive any treatment for the events. The nurse stated that they followed up with the patient later that day and after some sleep, she felt much better.  The patient recovered from the events on the same day (12-OCT-2020). The causality assessment was not provided.  Upon internal review, the event of passed out cold was determined to be medically significant.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within a couple hours my arm become visibly swollen, red splotchy rash, and felt like my arm was asleep (all the way to my finger tips), the most intense aching pain for 3-4 days  I had a fever over 101.5 degrees F about 18 hours later, I continued to wake up having night sweats for about 10 consecutive nights along with diarrhea for multiple days,  the following two weeks at least I struggled with numerous episodes of light headedness, orthostatic hypotension to the point of my vision going dark.  I also experienced extreme headaches, fatigue, weakness that I have never felt from previous flu vaccine shots  I finally took acetaminophen for the fever which helped it come down to 100 F, all fluids ran right through me for multiple days, and I am still dealing with fatigue and my blood pressure dropping at random times .  The rash is no longer there and swelling has subsided
OTHER_MEDS: No Rx medication, womens multivitamin, vitamin D, zinc, and fish oil.

My daughter splits her vaccines to have 2 every month instead of 4 every other month. Her plan is at ages 2,4,6, and 8 months to receive the DTaP, Hep B, Polio (combo vaccine) and an oral Rotavirus vaccine. At ages 3,5,7, and 9 month to receive the Prevnar and Hib vaccines.  After the initial Prevnar and Hib vaccines, my daughter began to have a bizarre spasm in her sleep. I rushed her back to the doctor, and Dr. confirmed it was not a seizure and to just monitor her. After the initial day of this behavior, it did not reappear. However, after her 5 month visit and receiving the  Prevnar and Hib vaccines, the behavior returned. Again, she would spasm in her sleep every minute on the minute. Along with this, she had an increased heart rate monitored using the owlet smart sock 3. The data for this monitoring is attached. https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1jXxkEHcnqpkfzvy9Gl9uIcX0glPN1DC8ESNslw3F0Zg/edit?usp=sharing
LAB_DATA: After he spasms at 3 months, Dr. pricked her heel to test for bacteria and viruses. Her white blood cell count was elevated slightly most likely due to the administering of her vaccines. No other illnesses were discovered. After the spasms from the 5 month vaccines, they did not prick her heel.
PRIOR_VAX: same vaccination, 3 months old, same brand,  August 17, 2020

I have lost strength in the arm. the symptoms have gradually worsened since the infection. I can no longer do my normal daily functions with my right arm. The pain wakes me up at night."

I had the vaccine at 3:45pm Thursday, Oct 8th, 2020.  While sleeping at about 11pm I awoke with nausea and starting to vomit. I had an bad stomach ache with bloating. I also had a very bad head ache. I do not normally get head aches. I could not fall back asleep. I tried to get up at 6am but was dizzy and unsteady. My husband helped me to the bathroom 4 feet away. Through out Friday I was dizzy, had a very bad head ache and continued to be bloated. I could not eat. Saturday I woke up feeling not as bloated but still with a mild stomach. Later in the day around 4pm I had heart palpitations while sitting out in the back yard. They only lasted about 2 minutes. On Sunday I broke out in a full body rash. Red raised splotches all over my body. I do get this reaction to a cold so I was not concerned. The rash finally started to go away on Tuesday.
PRIOR_VAX: mild rash and throat tightening

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Symptoms starting August 25 with right shoulder pain proceeding to muscular weakness of right shoulder. Diagnostics leading to diagnosis of ParsonageTurner syndrome which effected motor boy nerves and significant weakness and denervation of supraspinatus, infraspinatus,serrated anterior, teres minor and deltoid. Weakness ongoing at this time.
LAB_DATA: Right Shoulder X-ray - August 28,2020 no fracture  Right Shoulder MRI - September 3, 2020 degenerative changes with some possible early muscular atrophy EMG - September 9, 2020 decreased recruitment in infraspinatus Repeat EMG - October 13, 2020 severe denervation of supraspinatus, infraspinatus, serratus anterior, teres minor and deltoid
OTHER_MEDS: Wellbutrin 150 mg Vitamin D Ibuprofen as needed

Upper left arm swollen and extremely red, low grade fever and nausea at first. I have been taking ibuprofen for pain as well as icing the area constantly and using Aloe Vera with lidocaine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient's email report, 10 days after vaccinations:  "First of all, the pharmacist used me for dart practice instead of an injection. I had blood running down my arm from the flu shot (she must have hit a vein?). Still bruised. Secondly, I have had incredible pain in my joints (now easing up). I think the worst pain was in my joint replacements of metal. It seems every other day, I nap for 2 hours after sleeping 10 or 11 hours each night. My energy level has been really low. I've literally been stumbling a bit with my left foot, but better today. My left thumb has been numb for 3 days after tingling and numbness in hands sporadically."  She wrote again on 10/19/20: "I just want to connect to let you know I am still having symptoms following the 2 vaccines. Today, I researched the effects of receiving the flu vaccine and Gulliane-Barre is listed. It completely describes how I am feeling with my odd gait, weakness, and numbness in my left thumb and forefinger. On my morning walk with a friend, I mentioned my gait, and the weakness. She had noticed my foot dragging off and on. It finally caused me to research and the information said it can last several weeks or even months.  I also told last week that I felt like I had an autoimmune situation going on.  It all makes sense. It is very frustrating, but empowering to know that it won't last forever. You would think I have had a stroke to watch me walk. Yet, I knew the traveling pains in different joints over this 3 and a half week period had been an issue from the injections"
OTHER_MEDS: Hormone replacement: Estradiol, progesterone, testosterone, DHEA B complex vitamin D glutathione Resveratrol  NAC Lipoic acid multi-mineral probiotics

I took a Benadryl-type antihistamine  at 12 noon. The welts improved by 2 pm and were fairly cleared up by 4 pm (10/20/2020).  I had a fever. Then the itchy, burning welts came back even worse around 8 pm. They covered my thighs and upper arms. I took a Claritan-type antihistamine  immediately (8 pm). I was miserable and went to bed, trying not to think about the pain and itch. When I got up the next morning (10/21/2020), the welts were gone.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received the injection and then stood up and walked about 8-10 steps and yelled 'Mom' as she fell to the ground. Her mother ran to her side and tried to pick her up off the ground. Staff at the clinic - Nurse and EMS, instructed mom to leave her daughter laying on the ground and elevated the patients legs, while assessing vital signs. The patient opened her eyes and was talking within 30-45 seconds, she then jumped up and started walking and went down again. She continued to talk as we kept her laying on the ground for about 10 minutes. EMS was called for a second assessment. Patient was not transferred to the hospital, she went home with mom. Follow-up call to mom found that she had no other adverse events. Mom followed up with Pediatrician, the thought is most likely a vasovagal syncope event. The pediatrician instructed mom to have the patient lay down for all future injections.

Blistering autoimmune skin reaction following SHINGRIX vaccination in an ulcerative colitis patient:  Co-suspect products included Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included ulcerative (chronic) proctosigmoiditis. Previously administered products included diphenoxylate/atropine, mesalamine, levothyroxine (25mcg), gabapentin (300 mg), nortriptyline (25 mg), naratriptan (2.5 mg), hydroxyzine (25 mg), nitrofurantoin (100 mg), pentosan polysulfate (100 mg) and multiple vitamins. Concurrent medical conditions included alcoholic (drank one glass of wine per week).   In April 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, 40 days after receiving Shingrix, not applicable after receiving Shingrix and an unknown time after starting terbinafine, the patient experienced autoimmune blistering disease (serious criteria GSK medically significant), bullous pemphigoid (serious criteria GSK medically significant), autoimmune blistering disease (serious criteria GSK medically significant), bullous pemphigoid (serious criteria GSK medically significant), pemphigus vulgaris (serious criteria GSK medically significant), transient acantholytic dermatosis, red rash, pustular rash, papular rash, red face, blister, burning sensation in face, weepy, rash, red rash, pustular rash and papular rash. The patient was treated with valaciclovir hydrochloride (Valacyclovir), terbinafine, cephalexin and corticosteroid nos (Corticosteroids Nos). Rechallenge with Shingrix was positive. On an unknown date, the outcome of the autoimmune blistering disease, bullous pemphigoid, autoimmune blistering disease, bullous pemphigoid, pemphigus vulgaris, transient acantholytic dermatosis, red rash, pustular rash, papular rash, red face, blister, burning sensation in face and weepy were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the rash, red rash, pustular rash and papular rash were unknown.   The reporter considered the autoimmune blistering disease, bullous pemphigoid, pemphigus vulgaris, transient acantholytic dermatosis, red rash, pustular rash, papular rash, red face, blister, burning sensation in face and weepy to be related to Shingrix. The reporter considered the autoimmune blistering disease, bullous pemphigoid, rash, red rash, pustular rash and papular rash to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of blistering autoimmune skin reaction/Bullous pemphigoid (BP) in a 74-years old female patient, who was vaccinated with SHINGRIX (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis. The patient was female. The patient had history of ulcerative proctosigmoiditis, controlled with fiber supplement, diphenoxylate/atropine, and mesalamine as needed. The patient drank one glass of wine per week and had never smoked or used any illicit drugs. Other long-term medications include levothyroxine 25mcg, gabapentin 300 mg, nortriptyline 25 mg, naratriptan 2.5 mg, hydroxyzine 25 mg, nitrofurantoin 100 mg, pentosan polysulfate 100 mg and multiple vitamins. No information on patient's family history was provided. On an unspecified date in April 2019, the patient received 1st dose of SHINGRIX (administration route and site unspecified; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided but it could be 73 years or 74 years. On an unspecified date in 2019, 40 days after the 1st dose of vaccination, new rash initially started and appeared erythematous with raised pustules. [The new rash initially started 40 days after her first SHINGRIX vaccination and appeared erythematous with raised pustules]. The patient also developed redness, blisters, and burning on the right side of her face. The patient denied fevers, joint pains, chest pain, shortness of breath or cough. The patient was initially prescribed valacyclovir 1000 mg three times daily for presumed diagnosis of shingles. Despite compliance, the patient was noted to have erythematous plaque-like eruption over the right eye that crossed the midline and was ï¿½ï¿½mildly weepy", along with papular outbreaks around both ears, left upper arm, and right hand. The patient was then treated with cephalexin and terbinafine, however the rash continued to worsen. The patient underwent a biopsy and culture of the rash which showed no growth of aerobic bacteria or fungi. On histology, the biopsy showed ï¿½ï¿½intra-epidermal blister with eosinophils" with comment of ï¿½ï¿½spongiotic vesicles contain eosinophils, as does the upper part of the dermis" and that the findings were evidence for either ï¿½ï¿½re-epithelialized lesions of bullous pemphigoid or an intra-epidermal acantholytic dermatosis such as pemphigus vulgaris." Direct immunofluorescence studies, likely for antibodies such as Desmoglein 1, 3, bullous pemphigoid (BP) 180 and BP 230 for the autoimmune bullous diseases, were recommended by the pathology laboratory, but not obtained by the clinician. It was recommended to correlate with clinical findings. The rash completely resolved after a 20-day steroid taper with topical corticosteroid for 1-2 weeks and then only as needed for flares. On an unspecified date, less than two months after finishing the steroid taper, the patient received 2nd dose of SHINGRIX (administration route and site unspecified; batch number not provided). On an unspecified date, within less than 2 months after the 2nd dose of vaccination, the patient had recurrence of the same rash. The patient was treated with oral corticosteroid for one week, and the rash resolved. [Less than two months after finishing the steroid taper, the patient received the second dose of SHINGRIX and had recurrence of the same rash. The second rash occurrence, treatment, and resolution all occurred within less than 2 months of receiving the second vaccination. The patient presented on two occasions with a rash on her face (forehead, cheeks, ears), anterior chest, arms, legs, and abdomen after receiving the SHINGRIX vaccine in April 2019]. The author commented, "There have been multiple accounts of inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD) patients developing autoimmune blistering skin disorders, and in some cases, these have been associated with specific triggers such as vaccination. Some studies have proposed mechanisms for the pathophysiology of these associations, however there is not a clear consensus on the cause. In terms of overall frequency, one review of 48 cases of patients with autoimmune skin diseases and IBD reported that the most frequently occurring autoimmune skin diseases were linear IgA disease and BP. Another study concluded that pemphigus was significantly associated with ulcerative colitis (UC) with an odds ratio of 1.9 but did not hypothesize a mechanism. BP has also been reported in multiple infants after HSV-1 herpetic stomatitis and after vaccination against diphtheria, tetanus, pertussis, poliomyelitis, hepatitis B, and H. influenzae type b. This study confirmed the presence of BP antigen 180 and resolution of symptoms with oral prednisone treatment. The authors thought that trauma from vaccine injection could have led to activation of Th17 cells and IL-17 production causing proteolytic enzyme and cytokine induced blister formation. These proposed mechanisms share the unifying theme of a specific environmental trigger from vaccination causing an increased immune response that manifests on the skin. We believe there to be enough evidence amongst these studies in the current literature to support a possible association between a vaccination and the development of specific autoimmune disorders, particularly in those who may be predisposed to autoimmune conditions. Additionally, the recurrence of the same reaction after each dose of a vaccine (a positive re-challenge) is further confirmation of a causal association between the vaccine and an adverse reaction. Given the temporal relationship between vaccination, the development of BP, and resolution with steroids with each dose of SHINGRIX, we believe that the SHINGRIX vaccine led to the development of BP in this patient."

On 13-Sep-2020, the patient developed a non-serious sore throat (oropharyngeal pain), achiness (pain) and coughing (cough) (unknown latency) following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE.   The patient took some ALEVE [NAPROXEN SODIUM] and felt decreased these events. At the time of the patient's vaccination, the patient relied on the warning label affixed to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), and the information relayed through patient's healthcare provider(s) that zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was effective in preventing shingles on a permanent basis and did not carry any significant risk of adverse effects, which induced the patient to be vaccinated. Subsequent to the inoculation (date not reported), the patient was treated by a healthcare provider for shingles. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the patient has and will continue suffer ongoing injuries, including but not limited to: mental and physical pain and suffering; medical care and treatment for these injuries; significant medical and related expenses as a result of these injuries, including but not limited to medical losses and costs include care for hospitalization, physician care, monitoring, treatment, medications, and supplies; diminished capacity for the enjoyment of life; diminished quality of life; increased risk of premature death, aggravation of preexisting conditions and activation of latent conditions; and other losses and damages; and will continue to suffer such losses, and damages in the future. The outcome of the event shingles was not reported and the lawyer considered the event to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).

On an unspecified date in Oct-2020, the patient recovered from the event of 'paralysis'.  At the time of initial reporting on 14-Oct-2020, the patient had not recovered from the events 'numbness of upper extremities' and 'weakness', as it was reporter he was better, but still felt weakness and numbness in both arms. Company comment: The patient developed paralysis and hypoesthesia several hours after vaccination with the suspect product, Flucelvax QIV. Chronology is suggestive. The events of the loss of personal independence in daily activities and asthenia occurred on an unknown date within same month, making temporal relationship compatible. No information about medical history and concomitant medications was provided. Considering all above mentioned, causal relationship for all events is assessed as possibly related. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 20" after flu vaccine, pt was waiting/being monitored for possible side effects from the vaccine. Returned her to the treatment room for further evaluation.AAOx3. Calm. Speech clear and appropriate. Ambulates without difficulty. Skin warm/dry. No obvious swelling of tongue or throat. Lungs clear to auscultation all fields. VS: 150/80-60-18-96.9F within normal range except for BP which was 150/80. Client reports she has a h/o HTN and she took her prescribed medication (HCTZ) this am. Also reports an allergy to lisinopril (hives)  Also reports an allergy to lisinopril (hives) and a sensitivity to wheat, cornmeal, aloe, avocado and gluten. Client reports her symptoms (itchy tongue and throat feeling weird) were beginning to subside. Administered Diphenhydramine 25mg as per RNP Flow Sheet 408.24. Continued to monitor pt for an additional 30 minutes. Denies any further symptoms. Advised to seek medical advice from her PCP, in follow up to this event which she agreed to do. Advised to call this clinic if symptoms begin to recur and not to walk back to the clinic with recurring symptoms. Assured pt had clinic phone number.
ALLERGIES: Lisinopril, Sensitive to: wheat, cornmeal, gluten, ale, avocad

I noticed severe lower back pain a few days after the vaccine, but couldn't figure out what had caused it until I also noticed a chicken pox like rash about four to five  days after the vaccine.  I called the doctor's office and they said these symptoms are extremely rare and they would only last a few days.   The rash, which was worst on my upper legs and upper arms, as well as scattered on my back and chest, was itchy and somewhat raised.  Some places were blotchy and raised on the back of my arm close to my armpit.  Most of them were just spread-out red spots.  The rash almost completely disappeared after three weeks, but the back pain has continued, but decreased in severity.  The first week was extremely painful and I could hardly walk or move due to the back  pain.  Moving the wrong way would shoot pain in my back.  This happened for a few weeks and now it's just sore for the most part.   I had experienced pain at the injection site on my shoulder since receiving the vaccine and it was painful for about a week.  I had also had the flu vaccine the same day in the other shoulder, but it only mildly hurt for about a day or two.  I also experienced bad headaches, but they are not entirely abnormal for me so I didn't think much about them.   The biggest concern for me is that my back pain is still not recovered entirely.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My first symptom started on Sunday October 11th.  The right side of my tongue went numb, and I could not feel or taste anything on the right side of my tongue.  I was eating calamari which is not apart of my normal diet, and therefore blamed the numbness on an allergic reaction.  However later in the week, on Thursday October 15th, I started to feel that my right eye was dry and itchy, and that I could not completely close my eye.  The next day, Friday the 16th, I could not move the right side of my face.  I could not smile, close my eye, move my lips, move my eyebrow, or use the right side of my face.  I could not get in to see my doctor until Monday October 19th, and I did not go to the ER because I was not experiencing any life threatening symptoms.  On Monday my doctor diagnosed me with Bell's Palsy which she said was related to an infection.  I spoke with a nurse at my doctors office that had worked for VAERS for many years, and she is the one who suggested that this was probably a vaccine reaction since there were not other evident causes of the Bell's Palsy, and because I started having problems just days after receiving the flu shot.  My doctor placed me on a high dose prednisone prescription with the hope that it would decrease the inflammation of the facial nerve, and start to restore facial function.  as of today, October 22nd, the only change in symptom I have is a decrease in the numbness on the right side of my tongue.
LAB_DATA: Physical and Neurological exam including the accessory muscles.
OTHER_MEDS: Aurovela Fe Cranberry Supplements Vita Fusion Women's Supplement

SYMPTOM_TEXT: believes it is shingles caused by the Shingrix injection /  suspected vaccination failure; shingles; chills / shivering; rash to left genital area; rash to neck, and arms; Difficulty sleeping; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of suspected vaccination failure in a female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Concurrent medical conditions included rash (to right thigh on and off for 30 years).   On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 25th June 2020, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, less than a year after receiving Shingrix and less than 4 months after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced vaccination failure (serious criteria GSK medically significant), shingles, chills, genital rash, rash and difficulty sleeping. The patient was treated with acyclovir. On an unknown date, the outcome of the vaccination failure and shingles were unknown and the outcome of the chills, genital rash, rash and difficulty sleeping were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the vaccination failure, shingles, chills, genital rash, rash and difficulty sleeping to be related to Shingrix and Shingrix.  Additional case details were reported as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient reported case for herself. The patient had a rash on and off to her right thigh for thirty years but never had a rash in the left genital area. The patient could not remember when she had her first Shingrix injection but she had no adverse reaction from it. However, she stated after she had the second injection she had a rash to her left genital area, neck, and arms. She stated that she also had chills, and shivering, and difficulty sleeping. The patient seen her physician who ordered acyclovir for this rash but wanted to report that she believes it was shingles caused by the Shingrix injection. This case was considered as suspected vaccination failure as details regarding laboratory test confirmation and time to onset for the event was unknown at the time of reporting The reporter consented to follow up.
CUR_ILL: Rash (to right thigh on and off for 30 years)

No information regarding the patient's concurrent conditions, medical history, drug reactions or allergies and concomitant medications was provided.    On 20-OCT-2020, the patient was vaccinated with measles, mumps, rubella and varicella (oka-merck) virus vaccine live (PROQUAD) 0.5 milliliter, once, lot # T018279 was confirmed to be valid, expiration date 23-NOV-2021 (route and site of administration were not provided), which was reconstituted with sterile diluent (STERILE DILUENT) lot # T001190 was confirmed to be valid, expiration date was not provided but upon internal validation was established as 29-AUG-2022, and varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) (dose, lot#, expiration date, route and site of administration were not provided), both for prophylaxis. Other suspect vaccines included measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live(M-M-R II) (lot# and expiration date were not provided).   On that day, the patient experienced overdose and wrong product administered. The patient received measles, mumps, rubella and varicella (oka-merck) virus vaccine live(PROQUAD) with varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) but was supposed to received varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck)(VARIVAX) with measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live(M-M-R II). The outcome of overdose and wrong product administered were unknown.

Arm from her elbow to her shoulder is hot; Arm / Swollen; Arm / tender/ whole arm with sharp pain; sharp pain from her elbow up to her shoulder; sharp pain from her elbow up to her shoulder; Muscle soreness; Super tired; allergic to latex; allergic to latex; received the first shot of the Bexsero series about a year ago; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of extremities hot feeling of in a 20-year-old female patient who received Men B NVS (Bexsero) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included Sulfa eye drops with an associated reaction of swelling face, Sulfa drug with an associated reaction of erythema, Benadryl and Bexsero with an associated reaction of no adverse event (1st dose received about a year ago). Concurrent medical conditions included latex allergy (contact induced such as band aids and latex gloves) and sulfonamide allergy.   On 14th October 2020 10:00, the patient received the 2nd dose of Bexsero. On 14th October 2020, less than a day after receiving Bexsero, the patient experienced extremities hot feeling of, swelling arm, pain in arm, pain in elbow, shoulder pain, muscle soreness, tiredness, allergic reaction to drug excipient, contraindicated product administered and drug dose administration interval too long. The patient was treated with ibuprofen (Advil). On an unknown date, the outcome of the extremities hot feeling of, swelling arm, pain in arm, pain in elbow and shoulder pain were recovering/resolving and the outcome of the muscle soreness was not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the tiredness, allergic reaction to drug excipient, contraindicated product administered and drug dose administration interval too long were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the extremities hot feeling of, swelling arm, pain in arm, pain in elbow, shoulder pain, muscle soreness, tiredness and allergic reaction to drug excipient to be related to Bexsero.  Additional details were provided as follows: The case was reported by the mother of patient. The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient had latex allergy that was contact induced such as band aids and latex gloves and had sulfa allergy.  The patient had blocked tear duct and sulfa eye drops were prescribed which made her whole face red and swollen. A few years later the patient got a urinary tract infection and was prescribed sulfa as a tablet and again had a reaction to it. This time her whole body was red like a sunburn and she had to take Benadryl. The patient received Bexsero vaccine and her whole arm from her elbow to her shoulder was hot, swollen, tender, and she was experiencing muscle soreness. The patient was also super tired (took naps in the afternoon and went to bed around 9). The reporter asked if there was sulfa in this vaccine. The reporter stated that reading the page, she saw that it did contain latex. The patient was allergic to latex and sulfa drugs. The reporter stated that there should be warnings to the doctors letting them know what is in the vaccines so they do not unnecessarily harm children and young adults. There were a lot of people allergic to latex and should try your best to come up with a product that did not incorporate latex. The reporter was called back and she indicated that the patient received the Bexsero at around 10 am in the morning at the pediatrician's office. The reporter said that patient's whole arm was hot with sharp pain from her elbow up to her shoulder. It was hot and tender and swollen. On the day of reporting, in the morning the patient got up to go to school and after taking Advil. She said that her arm was just a muscle ache (no longer a sharp pain) so it seemed to be resolving. The patient did not have a fever. The reporter indicated that she was surprised that this happened because it seemed like an adverse reaction more harsh than any other vaccine the patient had ever received. The patient had received the first shot of the Bexsero series about a year ago and did not have a reaction, later than the recommended interval which led to lengthening of vaccination schedule.
CUR_ILL: Latex allergy (contact induced such as band aids and latex gloves); Sulfonamide allergy

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Flu like symptoms; Headache; Fatigue; Fever; Joint pain; Muscle pain; Heaviness in chest; Heavy feeling; This case was reported by a physician via licensee and described the occurrence of influenza-like symptoms in a female patient who received Rabies NVS (RabAvert) for prophylaxis.   Concomitant products included Rabies NVS (RabAvert).   On 1st October 2020, the patient received the 2nd dose of RabAvert. On 1st October 2020, less than a day after receiving RabAvert, the patient experienced influenza-like symptoms, headache, fatigue, fever, joint pain, muscle pain, chest heaviness and sensation of heaviness. On an unknown date, the outcome of the influenza-like symptoms, headache, fatigue, fever, joint pain, muscle pain, chest heaviness and sensation of heaviness were recovered/resolved.   The reporter considered the influenza-like symptoms, headache, fatigue, fever, joint pain, muscle pain, chest heaviness and sensation of heaviness to be possibly related to RabAvert.  Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient received pre-exposure vaccine series. The patient received 1st dose of RabAvert on 24th September 2020 and was fine. The patient received 2nd dose of vaccine and about 6-8 hours later she had flu like symptoms, headache, fatigue, fever, joint and muscle pain, heaviness in chest but later it was more like a heavy feeling all over. The patient had no chest pain, rashes, shortness of breath, cough, wheezes, upper respiratory symptoms (runny nose, congestion), abdominal pain, vomiting diarrhea, hives, closing throat/ airway. It sounded like side effects and not having a true anaphylactic reaction. The patient went to bed on the same evening and felt fine the next morning. The patient was also concerned enough to get a COVID test, but it came back negative. This case has been linked with US2020AMR208129 reported by same reporter.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020AMR208129:same reporter
LAB_DATA: Test Date: 202010; Test Name: Covid test; Result Unstructured Data: (Test Result:negative,Unit:unknown)

Sick; Missed the 6 month window; Administered it intramuscularly into her left thigh; This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of sickness in a 64-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) (batch number H4H34, expiry date 27th November 2021) and (batch number J3M5J, expiry date 6th February 2022) for prophylaxis. This case was associated with a product complaint.   Previously administered products included Zostavax (live shingles) injection and Shingrix with an associated reaction of product administered at inappropriate site (1st dose received on 29th February 2020 with batch number H4H34 and expiry date 27th November 2021 refer case US2020AMR206531).   On an unknown date, the patient received the 2nd dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On an unknown date, the dose was an unknown dose. On an unknown date, less than 2 weeks after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced sickness, drug dose administration interval too long and vaccine administered at inappropriate site. On an unknown date, the outcome of the sickness, drug dose administration interval too long and vaccine administered at inappropriate site were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the sickness to be related to Shingrix.   Additional information was provided as follows: The case was reported by patient herself who was a nurse. She said that she was very experienced.  She had been a nurse for 45 years and had given thousands of shots.  She bought the dose of Shingrix from the pharmacy and they allowed her to reconstitute and administer the injections at their home.  She stored the un-reconstituted vials in the refrigerator.  The pharmacy dispensed her two of the one dose combo packs and both had the same lot number and same expiration date.  She administered the Shingrix shot to herself about 2 weeks ago.  She did not remember the exact date because she said that both she had both been "sick" recently. Prior to reconstitution, when she was pulling the liquid adjuvant out of the vial into the syringe she said it leaked/sprayed all over the place.  She said that at the time you could see the hole where the needle had pierced the rubber stopper but you cannot see it anymore thus she will not be sending any pictures.  Because the first adjuvant vial leaked she used the second adjuvant vial instead and was able to draw it up with no problem and reconstitute it and administer it to herself.  She administered it intramuscularly into her left thigh which led to vaccine administered at inappropriate site The patient had missed the 6 month window which led to drug dose administration interval too long. The case also linked with US2020204764 same reporter. It was unknown if the reporter considered the sickness to be related to Shingrix.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020204764:Husband's case

Over 2 weeks the pain has shifted to a dull ache that is deep steady and worse with use of the shoulder. Hurts to sleep on it, hurts to lift and reach behind/above her head. pain in his shoulders, arms and legs; pain in his shoulders, arms and legs; soreness at injection site; full body myalgia; This spontaneous report was received from a physician and refers to a 72-year-old male patient. On 20-OCT-2020, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent)(PNEUMOVAX23), 1 injection, intramuscularly (IM)  (lot # T017385 and expiry date 01-SEP-2021 verified to be valid) for prophylaxis against pneumococcal disease.  On the same day, the patient experienced soreness at injection site and full body myalgia. Additionally, after 5 minutes of post-administration observation, the patient walked to his car and experienced pain in his shoulders, arms and legs, requiring him to return to the clinic. He was given intravenous (IV) acetaminophen (dose undisclosed) and recovered after 30-40 minutes. The physician reported he felt comfortable letting the patient leave. No lab diagnostics/studies were performed.  The relatedness between the events and the suspect vaccine was not reported.

The outcome of the event was unknown. The causality was related.  Upon internal review, the event of herpes zoster with ophthalmic complications was determined to be medically significant.

Condition worsening in content of chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuritis; Condition worsening in content of chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuritis; Blood return in tubing; Shortness of breath/ SOB with activity; Hoarse; Headache; Feeling ill; Feverish (no fever though); This spontaneous case was received on 15-Oct-2020 from a other health professional and concerned a 64-year-old, male patient.  The patient's concurrent conditions included chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuritis and multiple myeloma for which he was enrolled in cancer trial treatment. The patient's concomitant medications included Hizentra (immunoglobulin g human) for chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuritis and dexamethasone for multiple myeloma.  On 04-Sep-2020, the patient was vaccinated with influenza virus vaccine polyvalent [brand not specified, indication, dose, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported). The batch number was not reported.   On the same day, after receiving influenza virus vaccine polyvalent, the patient experienced shortness of breath (SOB) with activity.  On unspecified date in Sep-2020, reported as just after the influenza virus vaccine polyvalent was given, the patient was feeling ill. He felt, feverish (without fever) and hoarse. Also the patient developed headache.  On unspecified date, the patient's condition was worsening in content of chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuritis. He noticed his condition worsening since discontinuing dexamethasone, so he felt that the steroid with the Hizentra (immunoglobulin g human) was helping. Also, the patient received infusion and that some blood returned in the tubing. The patient did not receive any corrective treatment for the events or had any laboratory tests.  On 09-Sep-2020, the patient recovered from the SOB.  On unspecified date in Sep-2020, the patient recovered from the events of headache and 'infusion site extravasation'.  At the time of initial reporting on 15-Oct-2020, the patient did not recover from the event of 'chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy'.  The outcome for the events of 'hoarseness', 'illness' and feverish were not reported.  The reporter assessed the events of shortness of breath, 'hoarseness', 'illness' and feverish to be related to influenza virus vaccine polyvalent and for other events did not reported causality assessment. The reported stated that alternative cause/etiology was flu vaccine received given just prior to feeling ill- SOB with activity, feverish (without fever)and hoarse. The reporter did not provide a causality assessment for other events.  The event of condition worsening in content of chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuritis was considered serious due to medically significance by a physician within Seqirus's Department.  Company comment: Aggravation of chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyradiculoneuropathy, dyspnoea, dysphonia, headache, ill-defined disorder, pyrexia and infusion site extravasation were associated with the use of the suspect product influenza virus vaccine polyvalent. Chronology seems suggestive only for dyspnoea while for other seems unclarified. The patient's concurrent conditions included chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuritis and multiple myeloma for which he was enrolled in cancer trial treatment and concomitant medications included Hizentra (immunoglobulin g human) for chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuritis and dexamethasone for multiple myeloma. After discontinuation of these concomitant drugs aggravation of the main illness started to emerge making causality unrelated to vaccine and more likely related to cessation of supportive therapy for this immunological illness. All other reported events can be a result of the patient main illness, making causality also unrelated to the vaccine. Infusion site extravasation is not related to the vaccine.; Reporter's Comments: The reported stated that alternative cause/etiology was flu vaccine received given just prior to feeling ill- SOB with activity, feverish (without fever) and hoarse.; Sender's Comments: Aggravation of chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyradiculoneuropathy, dyspnoea, dysphonia, headache, ill-defined disorder, pyrexia and infusion site extravasation were associated with the use of the suspect product influenza virus vaccine polyvalent. Chronology seems suggestive only for dyspnoea while for other seems unclarified. The patient's concurrent conditions included chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuritis and multiple myeloma for which he was enrolled in cancer trial treatment and concomitant medications included Hizentra (immunoglobulin g human) for chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuritis and dexamethasone for multiple myeloma. After discontinuation of these concomitant drugs aggravation of the main illness started to emerge making causality unrelated to vaccine and more likely related to cessation of supportive therapy for this immunological illness. All other reported events can be a result of the patient main illness, making causality also unrelated to the vaccine. Infusion site extravasation is not related to the vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Incapacitated; Felt like she had the flu; Thought she was going to die; This frightened her; Unable to walk; Even trying to move around hurt so much that she cried; Even trying to move around hurt so much that she cried; Unable to eat a lot during this time; Feels very weak; Very nauseated; Headache; Very sick; This spontaneous case was received on 16-Oct-2020 from other non-health professional via Med Communications (reference number: SEQW20-03816) and concerned an 80-year-old, female patient.  The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. The patient received a flu vaccine, but never experienced side effects.   On 13-Oct-2020, in the morning, the patient was vaccinated with Fluad Quadrivalent (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, mf59; dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular; anatomical location: left deltoid) as protection against seasonal influenza. The batch number was not reported. It was confirmed that it was 2020-2021 formulation.  On the same day, after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent, around 3 pm, the patient developed a headache that continued to get worse and worse as the day progressed. By the end of the day the patient was very sick and 'thought she was going to die'. The patient lived alone and that frightened her. She stated it got to the point where she felt like she had the flu, was unable to walk and that even trying to move around hurt so much that she cried and was incapacitated. The patient was very nauseated, unable to eat a lot during this time and also felt very weak. No corrective treatment was applied for events.  At the time of initial reporting on 16-Oct-2020, the patient was recovering from events, as until that date the patient did not see some of these issues started to lessen and she still felt very weak and was still nauseated, but it was not as bad as it was from 13-Oct 2020 to 15-Oct-2020.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  The event of 'disability' and 'flu' was considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  Company comment: Disability, influenza, fear of death, fear, gait inability, pain, crying, feeding disorder, asthenia, nausea, headache and malaise were associated with the use of the suspect product - Fluad Quadrivalent. Chronology seems very suggestive and possibly related for influenza, gait inability, pain, feeding disorder, asthenia, nausea, headache and malaise and unrelated for fear of death, fear and crying.; Sender's Comments: Disability, influenza, fear of death, fear, gait inability, pain, crying, feeding disorder, asthenia, nausea, headache and malaise were associated with the use of the suspect product - Fluad Quadrivalent. Chronology seems very suggestive and possibly related for influenza, gait inability, pain, feeding disorder, asthenia, nausea, headache and malaise and unrelated for fear of death, fear and crying.

However, starting  around 10/9, my back and neck muscles progressively became more sore, and I felt a little muscle fatigue. Then, on midday 10/11, I started to feel more muscle aches (particular in the upper back and shoulders), lightheadedness, headache, and stomach upset. These symptoms were similar to what I felt the week prior, but they increased in their severity on 10/11. In the following days, I continued to have muscle aches and stiffness in my upper back, shoulders, and neck, felt easily agitated/anxious, and had one bout of diarrhea (on 10/21). My symptoms gradually began to improve after 10/21, but the back pain and anxiety have not completely resolved.

I went into my get my flu shot from this location as it it required by my work in order to keep my job. I did not look when the nurse gave my the flu vaccine as it causes me to become lightheaded and pass out. I noticed during the vaccination that it oddly didn't hurt like a usual flu vaccine. I noticed when she put the band-aid on that the flu vaccine was given very high, almost up to my shoulder bone. I came home and it hurt worse than usual, but I thought the pain would go away in a day or so. The pain didn't go away. Instead, for the next week, it kept getting worse. It got to the point where I could not sleep on the left side anymore because my shoulder hurts so bad.  I have dull, aching pain in my left shoulder constantly. The pain starts at where the vaccine was given and radiates down my arm into my elbow. It it made worse by doing any activity with my left arm, even simple things. After a week of pain, I made an appointment at my primary care physician and she said that the pain was caused from the flu vaccine shot being given too high in my left arm. She started me on a dose of steroids as she said that my shoulder was inflamed and swollen and told me to come back to reassess after the steroids were finished. My left arm is still hurting and I will need to seek further treatment.
LAB_DATA: I had a primary care physician visit where she diagnosed my left shoulder pain from the flu vaccine being given too high and prescribed steroids to help lessen the inflammation and swelling on October 19th, 2020. I am still having pain even after this course of steroids, so I will be going back to the doctor to reassess the next treatment for my pain.

My son got vaccinated with the MMR vaccine on June 23, 2020. About two weeks later, he started to complain that his tummy hurt. He also started to take upwards of 45 minutes to 1.5 hours on the toilet trying to poop, but saying that "it won't work." He has never had tummy or constipation issues ever in his whole life. His diet also hasn't changed, but his body definitely has. I mentioned my son's constipation problems to his pediatrician briefly a few weeks after I started seeing symptoms (end of July), but I thought it was something that would resolve itself. It has been months now, and my son complains about 3-4 days out of the week that his tummy hurts, and at least once a day he is on the toilet between 30-60 minutes trying to go to the bathroom. I didn't think it was connected to the MMR vaccine until I started to research further and found that it could be a potential side effect from it. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Had adult male with flu shot today online.  Verbally verified any reactions to flu shots in past and family stated just afraid of needles.  Proceeded with vaccine.  Within first 2 minutes started feeling dizzy and nauseous.  Gave water/ice pack and made sure he did not fall out of chair.  He became pale with blue lips while still conscious and verbal in chair.  I suspected vasovagal response.  He continued to breathe normally.  Then he became non-verbal and twitched slightly asymmetrically for about 30 seconds while breathing eyes open.  I suspected full on faint in chair.  At this point I was going to initiate our emergency protocol including calling 911.  His spouse got him to respond with a "no" when she mentioned an ambulance ride.  He came too and eventually walked out on his own power.  I offered assistance and asked if there was anything else I could do to help.  She thanked me and stated she will take him to MD Office in future and apologized.  I reassured her no trouble at all just want to make sure he is ok.   During all of this they did mention he has had similar responses with a dermatologist administering lidocaine for a procedure.  And again at home with a nurse/neighbor and a butterfly needle (went down hit head on fridge).   I highly suspect this is not a result of the vaccine but rather a severe case of needle phobia.  I did recommend the patient did seek a pre-emptive BNZ prescription for future blood work involving needles.

I received the shot at approximately 1pm and immediately felt pain in my arm down to my fingers. I verbally communicated this at the time. I came home and took a 500mg Tylenol. By 8pm my arm felt very heavy. By 11pm my arm felt is if it was paralyzed/dead weight and I could not lift it. I took two 500mg Tylenols and went to bed. The next morning it was some better in regard to feeling paralyzed as I could move it some but it still felt very heavy. Over the next 7 to 14 days my arm became seemingly weaker, the movement became more restricted and extremely painful.  I called the nurse line approximately 9/30/2020 and was advised to call my orthopedic surgeon (DR.) because I had rotator cuff surgery on that shoulder 4 years earlier (September 2016).  I saw Dr. 10/1/2020. He indicated that the shot was a lil too high and was concerned about frozen shoulder due to my limited movement and pain. He gave me a cortisone shot in the back left bursa. It helped for about 36 hours. I went back to Dr. and was referred for an MRI. I got the MRI on 10/7/2020. On 10/12 I returned to the Dr. for the MRI results. The MRI indicated frozen shoulder and a couple small tears in the tendon. I was referred for physical therapy (PT) for a couple weeks to see if that helps before any further steps. My first PT appointment was that same afternoon.  My next Dr. appointment is 10/26/2020.
LAB_DATA: The MRI indicated frozen shoulder and a couple small tears in the tendon.

had bands that ruptured and caused an ulceration; suffered a stroke; shoulder area is very sore; had a golf ball size lump on the anterior side of the shoulder; had problems with bowel movements; hemorrhoids; something has hit her muscle; Shingrix vaccine and the Flu vaccine at the same time in her left upper arm; extreme discomfort; Lipoma; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of ulcer in a 63-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included gallbladder removal. Concurrent medical conditions included diabetes, blood pressure high and stroke.   On 14th August 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular) and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season. On 14th August 2020, immediately after receiving Shingrix and an unknown time after receiving Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season and ibuprofen, the patient experienced discomfort. In August 2020, the patient experienced lipoma. On an unknown date, the patient experienced ulcer (serious criteria hospitalization), stroke (serious criteria GSK medically significant), shoulder soreness, axillary lump, bowel discomfort, hemorrhoids, muscle discomfort and vaccine administered at inappropriate site. The patient was treated with ibuprofen, non-drug therapy (Heat Therapy) and non-drug therapy (Ice Pack (No Medication)). On an unknown date, the outcome of the ulcer, stroke, discomfort, shoulder soreness, lipoma, axillary lump, bowel discomfort, hemorrhoids and muscle discomfort were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the vaccine administered at inappropriate site was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the ulcer, stroke, discomfort, shoulder soreness, lipoma, axillary lump, bowel discomfort, hemorrhoids and muscle discomfort to be related to Shingrix and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season.  Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not provided. The patient had a stroke on 4th June 2018 and previously had her gall bladder removed. The patient reported that she received the Shingrix vaccine and the Flu vaccine at the same time in her left upper arm shoulder area on 14th August 2020. The patient experienced extreme discomfort which started immediately in her upper arm in the early part of the day. The patient started to use heat and ice the shoulder and took Ibuprofen.   A week after the injections, she had a golf ball size lump on the anterior side of the shoulder.  The patient had an x-ray and it showed nothing.  They did an ultrasound within days of the x-ray and she was diagnosed with Lipoma two weeks after receiving both injections.   The lump did not move and was not soft and mushy.  Her shoulder area was very sore like something has hit her muscle and it would not resolve.   The patient received the Shingrix in the center of her shoulder and the lump was on the side anterior medial.  The patient didn't pay attention where she received the Flu vaccine.   The patient recently had problems with bowel movements and hemorrhoids.  She had bands that ruptured and caused an ulceration and she was hospitalized from 2nd October 2020 to 4th October 2020 because of the rupture. The patient stated that her hospitalization had nothing to do with the Shingrix vaccination.  The patient also stated that she just suffered a stroke but no additional details were provided.  The patient reported that her side effects are still unchanged. The reporter consented to follow up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: palpitations; Fatigue; chills; Malaise; Heat at the injection site; Local discomfort / Injection site; Sinus arrhythmia; Possible right bundle branch block; Thickened endometrium; Dysrhythmia; This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of dysrhythmias in a 76-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included palpitation (during menopause). Concurrent medical conditions included eyeglasses wearer, endometrial cancer and ovarian adenocarcinoma.   On 10th July 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On 10th July 2020, less than a day after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced injection site warmth and injection site discomfort. On 11th July 2020, the patient experienced fatigue, chills and malaise. On 12th July 2020, the patient experienced palpitation. In July 2020, the patient experienced dysrhythmias (serious criteria GSK medically significant), sinus arrhythmia, right bundle branch block and endometrial thickening. In July 2020, the outcome of the injection site warmth, injection site discomfort, fatigue, chills and malaise were recovered/resolved. On 14th October 2020, the outcome of the palpitation was recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the dysrhythmias, sinus arrhythmia, right bundle branch block and endometrial thickening were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the dysrhythmias, injection site warmth, injection site discomfort, sinus arrhythmia, right bundle branch block, fatigue, malaise, palpitation and endometrial thickening to be related to Shingrix. The reporter considered the chills to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information was provided as follows: The case was reported by patient her self who was a retired nurse. The patient received vaccine intramuscularly in the left deltoid. The patient experienced local discomfort and heat at the injection site which resolved. On Saturday 11th July 2020 the patient experienced chills and fatigue/malaise. On Sunday evening 12th July 2020 the patient began experiencing palpitations. She mentioned that she was not sure if the palpitations were related to the Shingrix or not because she had other stressors (she learned that her husband had cancer). On 28th July 2020 she learned the results of her Dilation and Curettage which was that she had a thickened endometrium which required a hysterectomy. An EKG  (Electrocardiogram) was done which showed dysrhythmia, sinus arrhythmia and possible right bundle branch block. Due to the results of the EKG and because the palpitations had not yet resolved her hysterectomy surgery had to be postponed. She did have the hysterectomy surgeryon 14th October 2020. The palpitations had stopped by 14th October 2020. There were no complications during surgery, there was no dysrhythmia during the surgery. The patient had endometrial cancer and possible adenocarcinoma of the ovary as well. She might require chemotherapy. She had not yet had a follow up EKG but she was scheduled to have one. The reporter consented to follow up.
LAB_DATA: Test Date: 202007; Test Name: EKG; Result Unstructured Data: (Test Result:see text,Unit:unknown); Comments: EKG- showed dysrhythmia: sinus arrhythmia and possible right bundle branch block.
CUR_ILL: Endometrial cancer; Eyeglasses wearer; Ovarian adenocarcinoma

A 66-year-old male patient received pneumococcal 13-val conj vac (dipht crm197 protein) (PREVNAR 13) Lot# AP2987, Expiration Date 31Jul2021, intramuscular in left deltoid on 10Sep2020 at 0.5 mL single dose for immunization. The patient medical history included generalized osteoarthritis, allergies due to pollen, Barrett's esophagus.  Concomitant medications included influenza vaccin on 27Aug2020 at 0.5ml on left deltoid for Immunization.  The patient previously took pneumococcal vaccine polysacch 23v (PNEUMOVAX VACCINE) on 29Nov2011 for immunisation. Patient received Prevnar 13 in September, he didn't get the vaccine in the office, got it done through a clinic. He had developed some complications as pain in left shoulder, neck and left arm which was the injection site in 2020. He received a pain medication acetaminophen;hydrocodone for it. So the doctor evaluated and determined the patient had shingles, shingles was diagnosed on 21Sep2020. The doctor put him on gabapentin (NEURONTIN), and it helped him. The patient was also put on Valaciclovir (VALTREX), for shingles, for 7 days.  But it came back and was still causing discomfort, he was also taking steroids; he was losing his strength and range motion since 17Sep2020, he cannot lift his hands above his head, they also did an ultrasound on 12Oct2020, it was showing a density, acute density, and the size was 3mm by 4mm x 3mm, so they will have to review further. He was also put on antibiotics in 2020, as it may be an infection fluid. She can give what they were calling the density on the ultrasound: it was a hypoechoic structure in the left upper extremity. Clarified shingles did not come back after gabapentin, shingles were not there, he was still experiencing pain, loss of strength, and loss of range of motion. He has recovered completely from shingles. The reporter was seeking further information. Lot was AP2987 and she wanted to report this and to see if there was anything wrong with the lot number. The patient called the facility with his first complaint on 17Sep2020. He said the neck pain was gone, but he was still having pain from his left shoulder to left elbow. The reporter stated she didn't think it required hospitalization, it was not life threatening, but it was serious, as the patient was losing strength and range of motion, so pain in his neck and shoulder and losing strength and range of motion was medically significant. ultrasound done on 21Sep2020; hypoechoic structure in the left upper extremity found. The density found on ultrasound was ongoing, she cannot provide if it was not there anymore, as there has not been another ultrasound done. Sample of the product was not available to be returned if requested as it was given at a clinic. The outcome of Infection was unknown, outcome for other events was not recovered. The reporter thought the events "pain in his neck and shoulder", "losing his strength" and "range motion, density, acute density" was related to the product.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information currently provided, the reported events more likely represent concurrent shingles with complications;  the device part of the suspect vaccine may also contribute to the vaccinated limb mobility decreased and abnormal ultrasound image showing small size fluid collection.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

Eye is red; Full dose not administered; Some landed in the patient's eye; Leaking syringe/the vaccine squirted out; This spontaneous case was received on 31-Aug-2020 from pharmacist via agency (reference number: SEQW20-01079) with additional source received on 02-Sep-2020 (being processed together) and concerned an 84-year-old, female patient.   The patient's concurrent condition included high blood pressure. The patient's concomitant medications included lisinopril, metoprolol and HCTZ (hydrochlorothiazide), all used for unreported indications.   On 31-Aug-2020, while administering Fluad Quadrivalent vaccine [influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, MF59, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: deltoid and dose: not reported] for an influenza prophylaxis, the vaccine squirted out and hit the patient in the eye (explicitly coded as 'Accidental exposure to product'). The batch number reported was 279794 and expiration date 29-May-2020.  It was reported that vaccine started to leak out before the shot was done and that the full dose was not administered (explicitly coded as 'Incomplete dose administered' and 'Syringe leak').   On the same day, after receiving Fluad Quadrivalent vaccine, the patient's eye was red. The patient was not treated with any medication.  At the time of initial reporting on 31-Aug-2020, the patient had not recovered from the event of 'eye redness'.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  This case has been entered onto Seqirus' manufacturing quality assurance tracking database and allocated reference number.  Quality Assurance investigation for this product complaint concluded that the root cause of this event was most likely due to user handling which led to leaking from the luer lock. A contributing factor for this event was the complexity of the safety needle used for administration. In review of this complaint it was determined there was no manufacturing fault that led to the leaking luer lock during administration. There was no requirement for any market action based on all information received, as there was no patient safety risk and the overall defect rate for leaking luer locks is two Defect/Million Syringes distributed.   This case is linked to case 202004293 (the same reporter).  Additional information received on 16-Oct-2020 from Product Technical Complaint (PTC) group: Quality Assurance Investigation Results were provided. Indication re-coded from 'influenza prophylaxis' to 'influenza immunisation'. Event 'Exposure via eye contact' deleted. The narrative was amended accordingly.   Company comment: Ocular hyperaemia along with multiple medication errors and device issue was associated with the use of the suspect product Fluad Quadrivalent. Reportedly, during administration of the product, the vaccine squirted out and hit the patient in the eye. The patient's concurrent conditions included high blood pressure and concomitant medications included lisinopril, metoprolol and HCTZ (hydrochlorothiazide) - all for unknown indication. With information presented, ocular hyperaemia is assessed as not related to the vaccine substance. For reported special situation (incorrect dose administered, accidental exposure to product and syringe leak) causality is assessed as not related per company conventions.; Sender's Comments: Ocular hyperaemia along with multiple medication errors and device issue was associated with the use of the suspect product Fluad Quadrivalent. Reportedly, during administration of the product, the vaccine squirted out and hit the patient in the eye. The patient's concurrent conditions included atrial fibrillation, atherosclerosis, dyslipidemia, benign prostatic hypertrophy, insulin resistance, gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) and gout.  The patient's concomitant medications included Indocin (indometacin), Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid), chloroquine, magnesium, Crestor (rosuvastatin), Prevacid (lansoprazole), fish oil, carvedilol, irbesartan, chromium picolinate, tadalafil, Nature's Bounty probiotic, Vit D3 (colecalciferol), Mulivitamin unspecified, all used for unreported indications.   On 31-Aug-2020 at about 3:30 pm, the patient was vaccinated with Fluad Quad (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived, dose: 0.5 ml, indication: influenza prophylaxis, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: deltoid). The batch number was 279798, expiry date: 15-Jun-2021.   On 01-Sep-2020, at around 2 am, about ten and a half hours after receiving Fluad Quad, the patient woke up with burning pain in his arm and all over his body and headache. The patient reported it was hurting so much he could not move to reach his phone. In the morning, when the patient woke up the burning pains and headache were gone, the injection site was not tender nor red. The patient felt only mild myalgia that was getting better by the hour. The patient also had a temperature of 99.9 F but he did not retake his temperature.   At the time of initial reporting on 01-Sep-2020, the patient recovered from the events ï¿½pain burning', ï¿½movement disorder' and ï¿½headache' and was recovering from the event ï¿½myalgia'.  The outcome of the event ï¿½fever' was not reported.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  Company comment:The patient developed pain, movement disorder, headache, myalgia and pyrexia one day after vaccination with the suspect product, Fluad Quad. Chronology is plausible. No alternative aetiology was provided. Based on provided information, causal relationship between the suspect product and all events is assessed as possibly related.
