SYMPTOM_TEXT: Worried that some of the patient's blood might have gotten on her; The vaccine squirted out and it hit the HCP's arm; The vaccine squirted out and it hit the HCP's arm; This spontaneous case was received on 01-Sep-2020 from pharmacist via Agency (reference number: SEQW20-01140) and concerned a 28-year-old, female pharmacist.  The patient had no relevant medical history and was not taking any concomitant medications.  On 31-Aug-2020, while was administering to a patient Fluad Quadrivalent vaccine (influenza vaccine, inactivated influenza virus surface antigen (subunit), egg-derived), the vaccine squirted out and hit the health care professional's (HCP) arm (explicitly coded as 'Occupational exposure while administering product' and 'Syringe leak''. The batch number reported was 279794 and expiration date 29-May-2021.  On the same day, the HCP was worried that some of the patient's blood might have gotten on her (due to the needle in the patient's arm) but said that she did not notice that it happened.  At the time of initial reporting on 01-Sep-2020, the outcome of the event was not reported.  The reporter did not provide a causality assessment.  This case has been entered onto Seqirus's manufacturing quality assurance tracking database and allocated reference number 1065599.  An investigation into batch 279794 did not reveal anything that could account for events 'worry', 'occupational exposure while administering product' and 'syringe leak'. Quality Assurance investigation for this product complaint concluded that there was no manufacturing fault that led to the leaking luer lock during administration. The most likely cause for this complaint was improper handling of the syringe during the attachment of the needle to the luer lock. Historically the use of safety needles had led to an increase in number of leaking syringe complaints due to the complexity of the safety needle apparatus. During the attachment the complexity of the safety needle apparatus led to the user not attaching the needle tightly, thus caused a leak. In addition, there was no trend present for leaking luer locks as the current defect rate for Fluad Drug Product was two Defects/Million and there was also no trend within batch 279794.  This case is linked to case 202004284 (due to the same reporter).  Additional information was received on 16-Oct-2020 from Seqirus' manufacturing quality assurance department: Quality Assurance Investigation Results were provided. Narrative was amended accordingly  Company comment: Reportedly, while health care professional (HCP) was administering to a patient Fluad Quadrivalent vaccine, the vaccine squirted out and hit the HCP's arm (explicitly coded as 'Occupational exposure while administering product' and 'Syringe leak''. On the same day, the HCP developed anxiety since some of the patient's blood might have gotten on her (due to the needle in the patient's arm). Based on provided information, causal relationship between the suspect product and the event anxiety is assessed as not related. Causality for other two events was also assessed as not related per company conventions.; Sender's Comments: Reportedly, while health care professional (HCP) was administering to a patient Fluad Quadrivalent vaccine, the vaccine squirted out and hit the HCP's arm (explicitly coded as ï¿½Occupational exposure while administering product' and ï¿½Syringe leak'). On the same day, the HCP developed anxiety since some of the patient's blood might have gotten on her (due to the needle in the patient's arm). Based on provided information, causal relationship between the suspect product and the event anxiety is assessed as not related. Causality for other two events  was also assessed as not related per company conventions.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My son got his Varicella booster on 10-14-20.  He cried upon injection and was irritable a bit. All was ok until Monday 10/19/20. He started becoming super irritable. He since started hitting himself in the head and nose. To the point of bruises on temples and nose bone. He looks like he is in pain all the time. I suspect  Encephalitis, he has been rubbing his eyes a lot.  The severe side effects list "brain reactions" as  a severe side effect. What does that entail? How general! Especially with the lack of attention we get as parents of a ASD child, but if it continues we can't have him keep injuring himself.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The injection site was still sore on the 2nd day but I expected that.  Injection site is still tender and it is over a month later. But that is the least of my problems.  Shot rec'd on Friday.  By Sunday night I tried to do something simple like squeeze a tube of toothpaste and not only was I completely unable to do it, it was incredibly painful in my arm. And I yelped!!   In the last month I am still having much difficulty -- the arm wakes me up at night.   I have pains when I am lying still doing nothing.  Doing simple  tasks like pulling a plug out of an outlet or a USB drive out....pain stops me.  I can not lift anything that weights over 2 pounds.  I tried.  Yelped big time on that one!! I reported this to the pharmacy.  They advised that they know of no system in place to report my problem.  I was quite surprised since in my search for help and relief I found this website.  Store did nicely write my name on a piece of paper.  Said they would note it in the computer and told me to call pharmacy Corporate Office.  You can't get through to anyone there.   It is  my feeling that the pharmacist on duty this day that gave me the flu shot either used too long of needle for my small arm or he did a back stick and he hit a nerve or something --  an older man with gray hair and glasses (don't recall a name) with a face not familiar to me as this is my regular pharmacy.   I say nerve because of the stabbing pains I get while doing absolutely nothing with my arm.  Prior to this I have had NO problems with  my arm and I now have about half the use of it.   He stuck something he shouldn't have and I need help!!!   Hindsight.....just because they are a pharmacist doesn't mean they know how to properly give needles. While having my flu vaccination at approximately 9:30 AM on Ocotber 16, 2020, I thought she seemed to be a bit high with the placement of the needle, but since I do not look, I could not see.  It felt a bit "thick" going in, but I was not sure what that meant.   Within  a few hours of having the injection, my muscle felt a bit sore - which is the usual reaction -  but by midafternoon 3:30 pm, there was this very intense pain on the front of my shoulder,  that did not feel muscular.   It intensified into the evening until I went to bed around 9 pm and took 600MG of Advil to calm the pain.  I awoke around 2:30 with such pain in front of my arm, I was awake for about an hour and then took 400 mg of Advil to return to some unrestful sleep as I could not get comfortable.  This has continued every night since - icing the front of my shoulder and taking 600 mg of Advil before sleep and then being awakened between 2-3:30 am due to the pain in my arm.    It is difficult to get comfortable even with the ice and Advil.  During the day on Saturday 10/17, Sunday 10/18 the pain was evident all day but most excruciating when I attempted to move my right arm back - to put my hand in my right pant or jacket pocket or to pull up my pants on the right side.  Additionally, I could not buckle with my right hand but had to reach over with my left.     There were times over those two days and every day since that moving my right arm just the slightest ?wrong way? causes such excruciating pain, it takes my breath away.   On Monday 10/19 I called to make a doctor?s appointment, but they could not see me for two days. I already had a previously schedule PT appointment for Wednesday 10/21, that I did not need for the previous issues but decided to keep it and have MPT examine my shoulder and arm and make a diagnosis.  She examined me and wrote her observations which can be obtained at Physical Therapy.  She recommended to ice it whenever it hurts and limit any range of motions that aggravated it but to do hanging circles to keep the shoulder moving and reduce the risk of frozen shoulder.  We made a follow-up appointment for 10/26. 10/25/20 The pain continues every day and night and has severely restricted my active lifestyle.  It has also interrupted any sense of restful sleep as I am aware of the pain every time I turn over and awakened every morning between 2-3:30AM.  This lack of restful sleep severely affects my ability to be clearheaded and productive in my job.  10/26/20 I visited Physical Therapist again today at 7:45 am.   She did some laser therapy and some message and taped it with KT tape.  She believes that either a tendon or bursae were struck with the needle and that is what is causing the pain.  She also explained that this could be a 4-6-week recovery. My shoulder felt calm when I left PT and for about 7 hours.  If is now fatigued and had some ?toothache? pain radiating out.
LAB_DATA: Please contact Physical Therapy for specifics

Pain and stiffness in left arm; Stiffness in left arm; General malaise; This case was reported by a consumer and described the occurrence of pain in arm in a 53-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season) for prophylaxis.   On 16th October 2020, the patient received Shingrix and Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season. In October 2020, less than a week after receiving Shingrix and not applicable after receiving Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent 2020-2021 season, the patient experienced pain in arm, limbs stiffness and general malaise. On 19th October 2020, the outcome of the pain in arm, limbs stiffness and general malaise were recovered/resolved. Arm erythema, due to flu vaccine. Use Benadryl q 6-8 hours and observe closely.  Follow up in 24 hrs.  Pt was brought into the office on 10/25/19, by his father.  Dr charted that arm was much improved.  Follow up if any change or symptoms worsen.

pain; GI problems; missed a week of work; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of pain in a 36-year-old female patient who received Hepatitis B vaccine for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included mumps and chickenpox. Previously administered products included Diptheria and Tetanus with an associated reaction of peripheral swelling (received in February 1995 and her arm swelled up red) and MMR vaccine with an associated reaction of gastrointestinal disorder (received in 1995 and experienced GI problems and pain). Concomitant products included ethinyloestradiol + levonorgestrel (Nordette).   In October 1995, the patient received the 1st dose of Hepatitis B vaccine. On an unknown date, less than a year after receiving Hepatitis B vaccine, the patient experienced pain, gastrointestinal disorder and activities of daily living impaired. On an unknown date, the outcome of the pain, gastrointestinal disorder and activities of daily living impaired were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the pain, gastrointestinal disorder and activities of daily living impaired to be related to Hepatitis B vaccine.  Additional details were reported as follows: This case was reported by patient for herself. Nordette was discontinued in 2011. After receiving Hepatitis B vaccine, the patient had to miss a week of work and was in pain and had GI problems. The vaccination was required for employment. The patient had a hard time with vaccines. The patient never received Flu shot. The patient's doctor advised against Boostrix in 2005 but she did not receive it instead she wears gloves in public and keeps her hands clean. The reporter did not consent to follow-up. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the seasonal influenza vaccine (unknown type, GSK P7HK7) on Tuesday 10/20/2020 around 3:15 pm as part of a requirement  for employment by Hospital.  Around 12:30 am on 10/21/2020 I woke up to use the restroom.  When I went to stand up I became weak and lightheaded.  I made my way into the restroom, and sat down by the toilet as I was feeling nauseous.  I began to have the cold-sweats and became very confused and disoriented.  I also became short of breath. The episode woke my boyfriend up who came to my aid.  He described me as pale, confused, and incoherent.  I do not recall some of the events that took place during the episode, but my boyfriend described it as something similar to patients running low blood sugar.  The episode lasted about 1 hr.  I returned to bed at this point with a terrible headache, which lasted into the next day.  I also felt weak for most of the following day.
LAB_DATA: The episode was reported to Employee Health but no testing was done.  I was told I was one of several other nurses and hospital employees with similar symptoms after receiving this vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After each vaccine she had a fever off and on for 2 weeks complete regression of speech and motor skills would get worse after each vaccine after the 6 month of age Used to say Momma & Dada at 6 month then stopped Both girls shared similar symptoms. They were meeting all developmental milestones until 6 months of age when we first saw a difference in their behavior. Days of fever, uncontrollable crying, and swelling at the injection site occured with each vaccination they recieved. Following their 3/20/2019 (MMR/DTAP/PCV13) vaccines, symptoms dramatically worsened. They stopped responding to their names, stopped letting people hold/console them, loss of eye contact, baby babble stopped even basic "ma ma" and "da da". Immune problems occured, sick more often, loose bowel movements, crying holding their abdomens, severe diaper rashes, banging their heads on the floor and walls, overwhelmed by noises (sensory issues), flicking of items with fingers. These symptoms prompted us to pursue speech and occupational therapy for the girls. at which time they were diagnosed with a developmental delay from medical professional
PRIOR_VAX: Regression~DTaP (no brand name)~UN~2.00~Patient|Autism symptoms~Measles + Mumps + Rubella (no brand name)~UN~0.00~Sibling|Autism

This is an old event, but I thought I should probably file it for future reference. I sent this exact email Public Health on March 26, 2018.   March 16th - patient  was brought to the Clinic and prescribed amoxicillin for a double ear infection.  March 19th - patient was brought to hospital for his 1 year vaccinations. (Note: he has never had any adverse reactions to vaccinations yet).  March 22nd - I noticed a few red dots on patient's chest in the evening.  March 23rd - In the morning, patient's chest had the same number of pink/red dots as the day prior. I sent him to daycare because he didn't have a fever and wasn't acting sick. I asked the daycare provider to monitor the spots and let me know how he was. As the day progressed, the pink/red dots continued to get worse and he was crying/screaming in pain when his arms/legs were moved. It was visibly noticeable that his elbows and knees were red, swollen and warm and he was experiencing some sort of joint pain. I scheduled an appointment with hospital to be seen that day. We saw Dr. and he said he was obviously having an allergic reaction to something, he assumed the amoxicillin. I had mentioned that he had been vaccinated on Monday the 19th and after a lot of internet searching, it kept coming back that it could be a reaction to the MMR vaccine. It noted that "because the measles, mumps, and rubella viruses in the MMR vaccine are weak versions of the disease viruses, they may cause a very mild case of the disease they were designed to prevent." Dr. indicated that he had never seen such a case, so he didn't think it would be that. As the night progressed, the red dots only continued to get worse. Patient was given 2 mL of Benadryl that evening per doctor.  March 24th - patient was given 2 mL of Zyrtec at 9:00 a.m. per doctor. The day old red/pinks dots were now bruise like in appearance and new red/pink dots were appearing. He was having horrific joint pain; screaming, crying and inconsolable for over an hour (until ibuprofen kicked in again).   March 25th - The majority of the dots were disappearing, but still visible. No joint pain all day.  March 26th - Almost all of the dots are gone. No joint pain.   NOTE; I have quite a few pictures on my cell phone documenting the progression of the reaction that I would be happy to send to someone.   NOTE: I listed the four vaccines that were administered on March 19, 2018; however, based on his records, I cannot distinguish which Hep A vaccine he was administered (Havrix or Vaqta).
OTHER_MEDS: amoxicillin on March 16, 2018 for a double ear infection.
ALLERGIES: Now (2 years later) it is believed that he gets hives from amoxicillin.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am not sure if this is related to the Flu shot or not, but I had the exact same effects last year at this time, and possibly the year before at the same time.  Within a few days of the shot, I had belly bloat and felt like there was something stuck in my throat.  I would also get winded after walking up a flight of stairs.  I took Protonix because I though the belly bloat may have been GERD, which would hamper my breathing.   Plus my legs feel very sore, like to a point of muscle failure.  I am eating much healthier this year than last and I had been riding a stationary bike a few times per week and my legs never started hurting like this until a few days after the flu shot.  Last year, it took about 2-3 months for my legs to start feeling strong again and being able to climb stairs without needing a huge breath at the end.  Like I said, I am not sure if this is flu shot related, but it's suspect as its the same symptoms at the same time of year.  My plan is TO NOT get a flu shot next year and see the outcome.   I am not sure of which lot or anything we were given.

Within a day my son developed eczema that steadily progressed in severity. He began spiting up considerably. We didn't realize ti at first, but he was reacting to foods through my milk. He never showed ANY signs of allergies or sensitivity before this. It wasn't until he began solids that we realized his allergies. Having FPIES, he would begin severe vomiting two hours after ingesting the allergen. He would have to be rushed to the hospital for fluids as he would become lethargic and risked going into shock. There is no test to determine his allergies; it's all based on trialing foods. Foods that he could safely consume a few weeks ago, could turn into an allergen later on.
LAB_DATA: We saw his allergist and a pediatric GI who both confirmed it was FPIES. The GI doctor was the one who brought up the rotavirus vaccine as she admitted is it known to cause gut problems and is associated with this "new" condition.
HISTORY: The rotavirus vaccine destroyed my son's gut causing him to suffer with a rare allergy condition called FPIES
ALLERGIES: now, yes, due to the vaccianation

cellulitis; big red circle swollen at the injection site (left deltoid) / swollen at the injection site (left deltoid) which was spreading down her arm; was uncomfortable; big red circle swollen at the injection site (left deltoid; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of cellulitis in a 72-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included Prior history of live shingles vaccine (received live shingles vaccine on an unknown date) and Prior history of seasonal flu shots with an associated reaction of injection site swelling (received flu shot on unknown date, refer case US2020AMR211753). Concurrent medical conditions included hard of hearing. Concomitant products included Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden (Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season).   On 16th October 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular) .5 ml. On 20th October 2020, 4 days after receiving Shingrix and an unknown time after receiving Influenza vaccine Quadrivalent unspecified season, the patient experienced cellulitis (serious criteria GSK medically significant), extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, discomfort and erythema of extremities. The patient was treated with sulfamethoxazole + trimethoprim (Bactrim Ds). On an unknown date, the outcome of the cellulitis, extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, discomfort and erythema of extremities were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the cellulitis, extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, discomfort and erythema of extremities to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The reporter was the patient. It was reported that the patient had the flu shot one month prior Septmber 2020). The patient did not have the lot/exp of the Shingrix. The patient had no issues with the flu shot received in September 2020 but that in the past she has had flu shots that sometimes swelled (at the injection site). The patient received dose 1 of Shingrix 0.5 ml injected into left deltoid intramuscularly. The pharmacist told her that the Shingrix shot could hurt more (than the flu shot) and warned her that she was likely to get a (injection site) reaction.  On 20th October 2020, the patient went to the doctor because she had a big red circle swollen at the injection site (left deltoid) which was spreading down her arm and was uncomfortable. The doctor diagnosed her with cellulitis and prescribed oral Bactrim DS (double strength). The patient said within 2 days (of being on the antibiotic) it went down and now it was almost resolved.  The physician advised patient not to get the second dose in the Shingrix series. The reporter consented to follow up.; Sender's Comments:  US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020211096:same reporter US-GLAXOSMITHKLINE-US2020AMR211753:Same patient

SYMPTOM_TEXT: GBS following the 13-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV13); This is a literature report  INTRODUCTION: Guillian Barre syndrome (GBS) is an acute immune mediated polyneuropathy which presents as monophasic paralyzing illness typically provoked by a preceding infection. The overall incidence of GBS is 1-2 cases a year per 100,000. An increased risk of GBS has been associated with the influenza vaccination. Despite the association of GBS with the influenza vaccine, there are limited cases of GBS documented with the pneumococcal vaccination. Authors present a case of GBS following the 13-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV13). CASE PRESENTATION: 61-year-old male with a past medical history of a stroke, coronary artery disease, and hypertension presented with lower extremity weakness and decreased sensation. He reported tingling in his feet which had been progressing up to his knees, with associated weakness. He had received PCV13 2 weeks prior to admission. He denied upper respiratory infections, or diarrhea. Lab were significant for leukocytosis 13.0 cells/microL. Muscle strength was 1/5 in the left lower extremity and 3/5 in the right lower extremity. Sensory motor deficits were noted up to the level of the mid shin bilaterally. Lumbar puncture demonstrated 0 RBCs, glucose 65 mg/dL, and protein elevated 79 mg/dL. CSF culture was negative. Nerve conduction study revealed evidence of severe sensorimotor demyelinating peripheral neuropathy. Work-up including a viral respiratory panel and influenza nasal swab were negative. The patient was started on intravenous immune globulin (IVIG) infusion at 1 g/kg once daily for a total of 5 days. DISCUSSION: Guillain-Barre Syndrome (GBS) is a rare acute flaccid paralysis syndrome commonly preceded by symptoms of upper respiratory tract infection or diarrhea within the prior 3 months. The underlying etiology of GBS remains unclear, but the pathophysiology in most cases of GBS is due to stimulation of autoimmunity that produces auto-immune antibodies that attack the myelin sheath of the nerves in the peripheral nervous system. In the case of this patient, he appropriately received PPSV23 prior to 65 years of age because of his chronic lung disease but he did not have a compelling indication to receive PCV13. There is inconclusive data that the greater immunogenicity of PCV13 leads to a higher incidence of immune reactions potentially leading to GBS. CONCLUSIONS: Pneumococcal vaccination is generally safe and effective with a very low chance for serious adverse events. Carefully administering PCV13 when truly indicated can further minimize the potential for harm. The development of injection site reactions should be carefully monitored as higher IgG-specific antibody titers could increase risk of GBS. Despite some of the recent reports of GBS associated with the pneumococcal vaccine, the overall benefit of preventing life-threatening infections largely outweighs the potential risks for adverse drug events.  Pfizer is a marketing authorization holder of pneumococcal 13-Val Conj Vac (Dipht CRM197 Protein) the country of incidence. This may be a duplicate report if another marketing authorization holder of pneumococcal 13-Val Conj Vac (Dipht CRM197 Protein) has submitted the same report to the regulatory authorities.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information currently available, there is a plausible time association as Guillian Barre syndrome occurred 2 weeks following the 13-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine.  As an individual case report there is no evidence to establish a causal relationship with the study product.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

This case involves a male patient of unknown age who was vaccinated with a dose of FLUZONE QUADRIVALENT (0.5 ml single dose syringe, lot number: UT7005JA and expiration date 30-Jun-2021) via an unknown route in the arm on an unknown date for prophylactic vaccination on an unknown date. However, while administering, the vaccine was running down the patient's arm from the injection site.   The patient's medical history, past medical treatment(s), vaccination(s), family history and concomitant medication were not provided.   This was a case of vaccine underdose, exposure via skin contact and product leakage (latency was same day).  Upon clarification received on 14-Sep-2020, there was no noted damage or leakage to the syringe prior to injection. pharmacist states that she was unsure where the leakage was specifically coming from. She pushed the vaccine into the patient's arm and then the leakage was noted, and she pulled the needle out. Pharmacist wants to know if she should re-vaccinate the patient.  At the time of reporting, no adverse event was reported to the patient.  This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error.

Patient was given the flu shot with her mom and little sister present.  The patient was a little nervous about getting the vaccine.  After vaccine was given, mom and children walked around the store a little but and then proceeded to walk to car to leave.  As patient got into the car, mom says she fainted.  Mom then brought her back into the store and laid her on the floor at the front of the store entrance.  By the time I got to the scene EMS had already been called and the child was laying on the floor and talking.  I asked her if she knew her name and age and she did.  There was another bystander who took her pulse and felt it was slow.  The child also looked pale.  While waiting for EMS to arrive the child was talking more and then able to sit up.  Her pulse was taken again and was getting better.  She was also given a bottle of water.  No complaints at this point of dizziness or feeling sick.  EMS arrived and checked her vitals and determined she was ok but also gave mom the choice to be taken to the hospital to be looked at.  Mom refused as she lived close to the hospital if she needed to be taken.  It was also determined that maybe the child needed to eat a snack/was hungry so she was given a bag of Doritos while EMS was still there and was able to eat.  We followed up with mother the next day and she reported that the child felt really good and went to school that day.  The mom thinks she is having a growth spurt and was probably hungry at the time of the vaccine visit and also nervous which may have contributed to the fainting.

Within a minute of getting this vaccine, my teeth then gums started to tingle then go numb.  Face felt flush.  Within 3 minutes my mouth got extremely dry, like cotton.  It became very hard to swallow.  It felt like a ping pong ball was in my throat as I drove home.  Breathing became difficult.   Difficulty swelling lasted about 60-90 min.  Within about an hour it started to subside.  I sipped water, did not think I could make it to the local ER.  After two hours, it seemed the event was over.  Then around 5pm that evening, I had similar symptoms again, but less severe, which lasted about 20 minutes.  Very scary.  My arm at injection site  is also very sore,.  I had body aches similar to flu that same evening which continued to the following day. Still  taking place.  I was warned that could be a side effect of the vaccination.
LAB_DATA: I did not have medical tests or lab work done.

The patient is a 68 yo female with a history colitis and GYN CA in remission who experienced a new dermatitis with onset temporally related to receipt of Shingrix #2 (receipt 24 SEP lot # 7AS54). The dermatitis is a macular, papular erythematous, pruritic dermatitis with sites to scalp, arms, back, chest, abdomen. There are no vesicles, pustules, petechiae or oral/mucosal lesions. She reported onset day 8 (verbalizes lesions present earlier, this was when she sought care) and was seen in ER day 9, 11 & 15 and saw PCP day 11 and 19. She has reported systemic symptoms of headache, dizziness and nausea(immediate post receipt) diarrhea with hematochezia (day 2-4), dyspnea, CP, difficulty swallowing and vision blurring (day 11), EKGs, CXRs, and lab work is essentially normal (including troponin T and CRP) or explained by steroid. Treatment has included famotidine, antihistamine, oatmeal baths and 3 courses of steroid (60 mgs x5 days, 20 mgs x3 days and 60 mgs x 7 days). We added cetirizine, labs for inflammatory markers and punch bx (see prior notes). On 28 OCT 2020 she reports dermatitis is mostly gone. She has stopped cetirizine because it was interfering with sleep. Oatmeal baths continue to be helpful. She is otherwise feeling well.
LAB_DATA: Labs WNL, no evidence of elevation in inflammatory markers. Path: - Dermal perivascular lymphocytic inflammation with associated dermal eosinophils (see comment). - Negative for fungal organisms by cytochemical stains. Comments The biopsy demonstrates a normal epidermis. The underlying dermis demonstrates tight, perivascular ("coat sleeve") lymphocytic infiltrates associated with dermal blood vessels throughout the papillary dermis and focally within the middle dermis. Abundant dermal eosinophils are present within the papillary and middle dermis along with increased numbers of mast cells and associated dermal edema. No eosinophilic flame figures or leukocytoclasia is identified. The aforementioned histologic findings are most consistent with erythema annulare centrifugum with less likely diagnostic considerations including other gyrate erythemas (e.g. eosinophilic annular erythema, erythema gyratum repens) and pityriasis rosea.
HISTORY: - Colitis (dx May 2020, f/u colonoscopy scheduled 05 NOV 2020; autoimmune w/u and Bx not yet done) Osteoarthritis -IC2 Serous carcinoma of the fallopian tube.  Initially diagnosed in SEP 2014.  S/P Resection at UNC in OCT 2015.  S/P dual agent chemotherapy with carboplatin and paclitaxel monthly, 6 total doses received, last 06 MAR 2015.  See HAIMS for UNC documentation. -Gastritis, s/p endoscopy, ? Gastritis vs. sequela from NG tube. -Hyperlipidemia -Hypothyroidism -Focal nodular hyperplasia of the liver, followed by UNC GI, records pending. -Vertebral lesion, incidental finding on CT chest, MRI performed OCT 2015 (HAIMS), suspect atypical hemangiomas, with followup MRI performed APR 2016, no changes or lesions, leading differential continues to be atypical hemangiomas. One additional followup MRI in APR 2017. -Grade II LV diastolic dysfunction (pseudonormalization) with evidence of elevated left atrial filling pressures. Seen on ECHO AUG 2015. -Irritable bowel syndrome, constipation predominant. Surgical / Procedural: Surgical / procedural history  - Left oophorectomy (1980) -Total abdominal hysterectomy w/ right salpingo-oophorectomy (OCT 2014) -Infracolic omentectomy (OCT 2014) -Right pelvic and right para-aortic lymphadenectomy (OCT 2014) -Peritoneal biopsies and pelvic washings, secondary to pelvic mass (OCT 2014) -Porta-Cath right chest wall (OCT 2014) -Upper endoscopy (2014).
PRIOR_VAX: Describes syncope afte IIV in college age 20's
ALLERGIES: - Codeine: urticaria (does not recall onset window, denies oral/face/throat tongue swelling) - Haldol: given for HA, throat restriction within minutes, given injection for anaphylaxis - Latex: contact dermatitis, no systemic symptoms - Denies intolerance or adverse reaction to any foods - No hx severe reaction to hymenoptera or other stinging insects.

HPV with CIN 1; HPV with CIN 1; Group B Streptococcus carrier; Vaccine exposure during pregnancy; This is an observational study case, received from other health professional on 21-Oct-2020 and concerned a 33-year-old, pregnant female subject of body weight: 178 lbs, height: 67 inches and body mass index (BMI): 27.9, enrolled a prospective observational safety study.  The subject's concurrent condition included body mass index increased. The patient's past medical history included urinary tract Infection with group B Streptococcus. The subject's concomitant medication included Prenatal DHA Vitamin for pregnancy, Flintstones (unspecified vitamins) for pregnancy and amoxicillin for urinary tract infection with group B Streptococcus.  The subject's obstetrical history included five previous pregnancies with two full term live births, two spontaneous abortions and one preterm live birth. The subject had no history of offspring with major congenital malformation (MCM). The subject had no maternal or paternal history with MCM. The subject did not use tobacco, alcohol or illicit drugs during pregnancy.   The subject's last menstrual period (LMP) date was 25-Jun-2020, estimated delivery date (EDD) was reported as 01-Apr-2021 and corrected estimated date of delivery (CEDD) was reported as 02-Apr-2021. The type of pregnancy was singleton.   On 11-Sep-2020, at gestational age of 11 weeks (calculated per LMP), the subject was vaccinated with Afluria QIV (Flu Vaccine Egg Split QIV CSL) (influenza vaccine; dose, route of administration and  anatomical location: not reported) (explicitly coded as 'Vaccine exposure during pregnancy') for influenza immunisation. The batch number reported was P100230203.   On the same day, ultrasound, Counsyl fundamental panel with fragile X and Counsyl chromosomes 13, 18, 21 and sex chromosome analysis revealed no MCMs.  On the same day, after receiving Afluria QIV, it was determined that the subject was group B Streptococcus carrier.  On 28-Sep-2020, 17 days after receiving Afluria QIV, the patient developed human papilloma virus infection (HPV) with Cervical intraepithelial neoplasia I (CIN 1)  At the time of initial reporting on 21-Oct-2020, the patient had not recovered from the events 'cervical intraepithelial neoplasia I', 'human papilloma virus infection' and 'bacterial infection due to streptococcus, group B'.   The reporter did not provide a causality assessment to Afluria QIV.  The events 'cervical intraepithelial neoplasia I', 'human papilloma virus infection' and 'bacterial infection due to streptococcus, group B' were considered to be medically significant by a Physician within Seqirus's Pharmacovigilance and Risk Management Department.  Company comment: Cervical dysplasia, papilloma viral infection and beta haemolytic streptococcal infection were associated with the use of the suspect product - Afluria QIV. Bacterial infection was detected the same day after vaccination (chronology suggestive) and other two 17 days after (chronology plausible). Causality is assessed as unrelated for streptococcal infection (due to biological implausibility) and also unrelated for other two events. Presence of papilloma infection may be the cause of cervical dysplasia and human papillomavirus is a common sexually transmitted infection (STI). Exposure during pregnancy  is assessed as unrelated per company conventions.; Sender's Comments: Cervical dysplasia, papilloma viral infection and beta haemolytic streptococcal infection were associated with the use of the suspect product - Afluria QIV. Causality is assessed as unrelated for streptococcal infection (due to biological implausibility) and also unrelated for other two events. Presence of papilloma infection may be the cause of cervical dysplasia and human papillomavirus is a common sexually transmitted infection (STI). After vaccination, the patient suffered from herpes zoster, postherpetic neuralgia (PHN) and fibromyalgia. As a result of those symptoms, the patient was seen and treated by medical providers. As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) use, the patient's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to vaccination. The patient also experiences mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of the patient's condition. As a result, the patient sustained severe and permanent personal injuries. Further, as a tragic consequence, the patient suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. As a direct and proximate result, the patient had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages.  The reporter considered the herpes zoster, PHN and fibromyalgia to be disabling events.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I, Pharm.D., gave Fluzone HD vaccine to the patient in the Deltoid muscle and a great deal of blood filled all the barrier bandage. I kept it on for a minute then took it off, the blood stopped coming out but it looked the area was swollen up under the skin, I placed a gauze pad with a gentle pressure for a minute in case more blood may start coming out but none came out and it was apparent at this point the area was swollen about 1.5 inches in diameter and 1 cm in height around the shot area. I kept the patient waiting for about 10 more minutes and asked him questions. He said that he never had allergic reaction to a shot before and he had a flu shot every year for decades. The skin color stayed the same for the entire period (normal skin color) and the swelling went down slightly after him being in the booth/kiosk for 15 minutes. Since he didn't have any concerns and was not feeling ill or dizzy, he was ok in leaving the pharmacy area. The next morning when I woke up my shoulder was in pain and I noticed I couldn't barely lift it much past my waist without pain. I was not able to put on my T shirt like normal or lift my arm over my head.  I still didn't think too much about it but as the day went on it continued to hurt and felt worse deep shoulder pain. Then I had a realization moment and said to my husband, I wonder if this shoulder pain is from the injection yesterday? It certainly seemed like it since there was no other aggravating factor or reason for the pain.  I took motrin and had some relief but still having deep, range of motion limiting pain in the shoulder and radiating up left neck. I am very concerned because I have never had any injury or issues whatsoever with my shoulder. And now looking back I felt I was right when I initially thought the injection was given high on my arm. When I removed the bandaid it was near the top of my arm, not in the main fleshy deltoid area.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 24 hours after injection (Sept. 26), tenderness in left armpit, upper deltoid above injection site.  Later that day noticed enlarged, rubbery to rigid, painful, lump on upper side of left clavicle.  Lump was somewhat mobile, but movement caused discomfort.  By second day after injection (Sept 27), pain in upper left deltoid less, but not gone.  Left armpit near the pectoral region remained tender, but not painful. Lump (swollen lymph node?) on top side of left clavicle still present and painful.  By evening and that night, noticed growing tenderness around left groin area.  Not actual pain, and no signs of swellings or lumps, but definite soreness and tenderness. Third day after injection (Sept 28), swollen node/lump on left clavicle still swollen and painful, particularly when pressed or moved. Seatbelt in vehicle pressed against it frequently when driving, causing pain.  Left armpit and pectoral areas no longer painful.  Left groin area still ached and tender well into the night.  Fourth day after injection (Sept. 29) lump over left clavicle subsided, no longer painful.  Left groin area no longer tender or sore by end of day/evening. By fifth day after injection (Sept 30) no further signs of side effects, pain or tenderness.

Immune-mediated inflammatory reaction/ causing and/or exacerbating an inmmune response; Loss of userange of motion in the right shoulder joint/ decreased mobility; Rotator cuff injury/tear; right shoulder injury; Musculoskeletal injuries; Damage to his nerves and nervous system; Shoulder injury resulting from vaccine administration ("SIRVA"); Pseudoseptic arthritis of the right shoulder/ The patient sustained injury/ Aseptic inflammatory arthritis; Lack of immunity/failed pneumococcal vaccine administration; improper administration of a PNEUMOVAX23 into right shoulder; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation involved a pharmacy, referring to a patient of unknown age and gender. No information was provided regarding medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medications. On or about 04-OCT-2018, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) in right shoulder for prophylaxis (strength, dose, route of administration, lot#, and expiration date were not reported). The patient sustained injury as a result of alleged improper administration of pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) vaccine (incorrect route of product administration). Also, the patient claimed based on the alleged defective design and manufacture (poor quality product administered, product quality issue, product design issue and manufacturing issue) of the pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23). The outcome of injury was not recovered and for poor quality product administered, product quality issue, product design issue, manufacturing issue and incorrect route of product administration was not reported. The reporter considered injury to be related to pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23).  Follow up (F/U) information was received on 21-OCT-2020, from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation involved a pharmacy, concerning an adult male patient. Pt was prescribed pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) by physician the same date of vaccination. The patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) in the right arm. On the evening of Thursday 04-OCT-2018 (reported as after received the pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23)), the patient suffered a severe and permanent injury to his right arm/shoulder required surgery, inpatient rehabilitation, future care and therapy, and permanent loss of function. The patient began had pain/discomfort in his right shoulder, he called to pharmacy and indicated that shoulder pain was normal and that he should use ice. On Sunday 07-OCT-2018, patient had increased and significant pain and discomfort in his right shoulder and he went to pharmacy where he was advised to take acetaminophen (TYLENOL) and ice. On Monday 08-OCT-2018, he went to a hospital with complaints of inter alia, right upper extremity pain and swelling, upon examination in the Emergency Department (ED), he was found to had swelling in this right deltoid and his acromioclavicular joint was tender to palpation, fluid collection presented in the area of his right shoulder, slight erythematous color of upper arm to clavicle, a laboratory data evidenced an elevated sedimentation rate and c-reactive protein rate. Therefore, an orthopedic surgeon was consulted. It was reported, an aspirated synovial fluid was performed and the fluid was noted to be yellow and turbid and had a white blood cell count of 82000 with 94% polys (neutrophils) and was believed to had septic arthritis, the aspirated synovial fluid was sent to be cultured, but not revealed growth of any bacteria/pathogen. Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) with and without contrast showed inter alia, a large amount of fluid in the subacromial/subdeltoid burse bursa with less pronounced fluid in the glenohumeral joint and extensive synovial thickening and enhancement that was concerning for post vaccination synovitis. The patient was taken to the operation room this same date, for incision and drainage of superficial and deep abscess and the diagnosis at the time was to be shoulder septic arthritis. During the procedure, physician noted that there were pus collections and a massive rotator cuff tear, following a through irrigation and debridement, a drain was placed and the patient was taken from the operation room with a surgical drain a plan for intravenous (IV) antibiotics, and consulted with an infection disease specialist. Also reported during the surgical procedure, the physician performed 3 wound swabs were taken and sent for routine bacterial culture analysis and after 48 hour, all 3 wound swabs cultures showed no growth of any bacteria/pathogen. The patient hospitalized through 13-OCT-2018 at which time he was discharged to an inpatient rehabilitation facility for further care, management and treatment. On or about 26-OCT-2018, the patient was saw by infectious disease specialist and noted, inter alia, all of the cultures taken were sterile and that the other possible diagnosis was pseudoseptic arthritis of the shoulder, which had been reported followed pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23). It was reported that the right shoulder injury was caused by administered pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) in an improper location (incorrect route of product administration). It was reported the negligence and/or negligent acts, increased the risk of harm and/or proximately caused to suffered the following injuries: pseudoseptic arthritis of the right shoulder, aseptic inflammatory arthritis, immune-mediated inflammatory reaction, increased risk of infection, lack of immunity/failed pneumococcal Vaccine, Polyvalent (23-valent) (PNEUMOVAX23) vaccine administration, rotator cuff injury/tear(s), shoulder injury resulted from vaccine administration, pain and suffering, right shoulder injury, musculoskeletal injuries, caused and/or exacerbated and immune response, loss of used and/or range of motion in the right shoulder joint, needed inpatient hospitalization, surgical intervention, inpatient rehabilitation, IV and oral antibiotic therapy, future care and therapy, physical and emotional suffering, embarrassment and humiliation, needed for additional surgical and/or medical procedures, additional hospitalizations, injuries documented in his medical records, loss of life's pleasure, scarred and deformity, disfigurement, decreased mobility, past medical expenses, damaged to his nerves and nervous system and spousal loss of consortium. The outcome of arthritis, nerve injury, joint range of motion decreased, musculoskeletal injury, limb injury, shoulder injury related to vaccine administration, rotator cuff syndrome, immune-mediated adverse reaction was not recovered and for vaccination failure was not reported. The reporter considered arthritis, nerve injury, joint range of motion decreased, musculoskeletal injury, limb injury, shoulder injury related to vaccine administration, rotator cuff syndrome, immune-mediated adverse reaction and vaccination failure to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).

On an unknown date, the patient experienced incomplete course of vaccination. The patient was treated with prednisone. On 15th September 2019, the outcome of the difficulty breathing and asthma aggravated were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site erythema was recovered/resolved and the outcome of the injection site itching, injection site swelling and incomplete course of vaccination were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the difficulty breathing, asthma aggravated, injection site erythema, injection site itching and injection site swelling to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were reported as follows: The patient said that the day before Shingrix vaccination had a runny nose which typically occurs every fall due to seasonal allergies from tree. The patient received 1st dose of Shingrix and next day after vaccination, had difficulty breathing and an asthma exacerbation that lasted approximately 3 to 4 days. The patient went to an urgent care to undergo treatment and was prescribed Prednisone 60 milligram for 10 days. The reporter also reported redness on her left arm around the injection site that was approximately the size of a softball. The affected area was described as itchy and raise approximately 1/16th to 1/8th of an inch. The redness reportedly lasted over one week. At the time of the event, the patient had ongoing abdominal pain and irritability (the patient was generally a cranky colicky baby).  Concomitant vaccinations included POLIO VACCINE (POLIO) and HIB VACCINE (HIB) for prophylactic vaccination (not sure if they were given on same day).  On an unknown date (in Jun or Jul-2020), the patient received a 0.5 ml once dose of suspect DIPHTHERIA-15/TETANUS/5 AC PERTUSSIS VACCINE (batch number and expiry date not reported, strength: standard) once via intramuscular route in the left leg for prophylactic vaccination. These events were assessed as medically significant.  On an unknown date, the patient was hypertonic (hypertonia), went limp (gait disturbance) and was crying uncontrollably (crying) (unknown latency, non-serious events) following the administration of DIPHTHERIA-15/TETANUS/5 AC PERTUSSIS VACCINE.   The doctor was able to immediately stimulate him and he came back very fast. She did not have his chart with her and was at home. She had given Daptacel to other children and they were fine. pain in her shoulder (75 percent of motion)/ in her left shoulder/ pain in left arm as 3/10; pain in her shoulder (75 percent of motion)/ in her left shoulder; not being able to lift much weight; This spontaneous report was received from an administrator who was reporting on 35-year-old female patient. She has no pertinent medical history, no known drug reactions or allergies, she was not in pregnant and had no concomitant therapies. Her concurrent conditions were not reported.   On 10-JUL-2020, the patient was vaccinated with her first dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) 0.5 milliliter administered intramuscularly in the left deltoid (strength was not provided; lot number R030453 was confirmed to be valid, expiration date 23-JUL-2021 was confirmed) for HPV prevention. On 09-SEP-2020, she received second dose of hpv rl1 6 11 16 18 31 33 45 52 58 vlp vaccine (yeast) (GARDASIL 9) also intramuscularly in the left deltoid (strength, exact dose, lot number and expiration date were not reported) for the same indication.  On 15-SEP-2020, after second dose of the vaccine, she reported pain in her shoulder (75 percent range of motion), on an unknown date in 2020 she also complain that she is not able to lift much weight. She sought medical attention and on examination, the patient had full range of motion but the doctor is ruling it vaccine related injury. It was recommended that the patient use warm compresses and oral acetaminophen (TYLENOL) or ibuprofen for pain management, but she preferred to use "ARNICA" (it was unknown if it was topical or oral "ARNICA"). On 12-OCT-2020 the patient was brought in for examination, she continued to complain on 75 percent range of motion with left arm and not being able to lift much weight. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Got flu shot in left deltoid and Gardasil 9 in right deltoid on Tuesday (10/20).  Gardisil stung on injection with some bleeding, but stinging was present in both of other 2 injections in series and they then had essentially no ongoing pain. Both shoulders still a little sore (right greater than left) Friday (10/23) but was able to do a LIGHT 20 min rowing workout. Left arm essentially pain free by saturday 10/24. In right arm on Saturday there was significant pain (worse than previous day) and stiffness in right shoulder.  limited mobility. Difficulty with ADLs (unable to lift arm to brush hair or take on/off shirts overhead without help, difficulty opening drawers/doors with right arm) due to pain. Somewhat responsive to NSAIDS. Pain has gradually lessened by today (day of reporting, 10/30, 10 days post vaccine) but still painful and stiff in mornings and can still illicit 8/10 pain in Right shoulder with certain motions, especially when extended overhead and can barely get shirts on/off. Have not rowed or exercised or anything that could inflame shoulder since 10/23.
CUR_ILL: Did egg cryopreservation (first half of IVF) with retrieval procedure on 10/6

Shortly after receiving 2 vaccines in (L) arm - he walked out of room on his own & suddenly collapsed on to the wall in the hallway. I rushed to assist when I heard the bang on the wall & found him sitting in an awkward position - unaware of his surroundings. I laid him down on the floor & elevated his lower extremities. He slowly recuperated & became oriented to place/person/time. He stated he felt better & understood that he fainted & stated that it happen to him when he gets blood drawn. The nurse & I lifted him when he felt he could walk, sat on a chair & kept monitoring him for another 10-15 minutes. We took his blood pressure, which was slightly elevated (135/65) & gave instructions to him & his mother for him to rest, drink fluids, eat & not drive today. They were understanding of the instructions and proceeded to leave the office. I called the house @ 4:15PM to ask for a F-U report, got An Answering machine & LMTCB. 10/30/20 10:30 AM ADDENDUM: I reached out to Mom again & she returned call informing that Patient was back to normal - yesterday.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient was diagnosed with postherpetic neuralgia; Patient developed bronchitis; Suffered a painful and debilitating shingles outbreak across her face, in her ears, and around her eyes; This initial spontaneous report was received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation referring to a female patient (pt) of unknown age. The pt's pertinent medical history, concurrent conditions or concomitant medications were not reported. On or about 17-OCT-2016, the pt was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (lot#, expiration date, dosage and route of administration were not provided) for routine health maintenance and for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster). On an unspecified date, shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt suffered a painful and debilitating shingles outbreak across her face, in her ears, and around her eyes. These injuries persisted for weeks and the pt was diagnosed with postherpetic neuralgia. Additionally, the pt developed bronchitis. It was also specified that the pt suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. The events were caused by zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).  The events were considered to be disabling due to serious, permanent and incurable injuries.

Unilateral ptosis/ left-sided upper eyelid drooping; Proptosis; Orbital myositis; Fever; Chills; Diaphoresis; left-sided headache; prickly sensation in both hands; acute onset of worsening left periocular swelling; diplopia\Double vision; left-sided tearing; Sinusitis/stable left sinus disease/left ethmoid, maxillary, and frontal sinus thickening; left-sided eye pain; Extraocular motility decreased; had edema and erythema of the left upper and lower eyelids; had edema and erythema of the left upper and lower eyelids; left temporal bulbar conjunctiva was injected; left temporal bulbar conjunctiva was injected and chemotic; rectus muscles appeared enlarged; discomfort; This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of ptosis in a 58-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included migraine headache, craniotomy (for left parietal (WHO grade 1) meningothelial syncytial meningioma resection 4 months prior to presentation) and chickenpox (as a child but no history of known shingles). Previously administered products included Penicillin with an associated reaction of pruritus and lidocaine with an associated reaction of tachycardia (intolerance: dizziness). Concurrent medical conditions included hypertension, hyperlipidemia, meningioma and penicillin allergy.   On an unknown date, the patient received Shingrix. On an unknown date, 2 days after receiving Shingrix and an unknown time after starting Oxymetazoline, the patient experienced ptosis (serious criteria hospitalization), proptosis (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), orbital myositis (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), fever (serious criteria hospitalization), chills (serious criteria hospitalization), diaphoresis (serious criteria hospitalization), headache unilateral (serious criteria hospitalization), tingling of extremity (serious criteria hospitalization), periocular swelling (serious criteria hospitalization), diplopia (serious criteria hospitalization), eyes tearing (serious criteria hospitalization), sinusitis (serious criteria hospitalization), eye pain, eye movement disorder, eyelid edema, erythema eyelid, conjunctival injection, chemosis, muscle swelling and discomfort. The patient was treated with fluticasone propionate (Fluticasone), ciprofloxacin, oxymetazoline hydrochloride (Oxymetazoline), doxycycline, vancomycin, sodium chloride (Nasal Saline Irrigation), methylprednisolone sodium succinate (Solumedrol), prednisone and antibiotics nos (Oral Antibiotics (Nos)). Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of unilateral ptosis, proptosis, and orbital myositis in a 58-years old female patient, who was vaccinated with Shingrix (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis. The patient's medical history included hypertension, hyperlipidemia, left-posterior parietal craniotomy for left parietal (WHO grade 1) meningothelial syncytial meningioma resection 4 months prior to presentation and migraine headache. The patient had a history of chicken pox as a child but no history of known shingles. The patient's allergy list included penicillin (itching) and lidocaine (intolerance: tachycardia and dizziness). Family history included a father with a history of granulomatous with polyangiitis. The patient had no history of an autoimmune condition. No information on patient's concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, 3 days prior to presentation, the patient received Shingrix (administration route unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided) in the left deltoid. [She had received the Shingrix vaccine (GlaxoSmithKline) 3 days prior to presentation in the left deltoid]. On an unspecified date, within hours after the vaccination, the patient developed fevers, chills, diaphoresis, left-sided headache, and prickly sensation in both hands. The patient presented with acute onset of worsening left periocular swelling and diplopia for 2 days. The patient later noted left-sided upper eyelid drooping and left-sided tearing 1 day prior to presentation and presented to an outside emergency department 2 days after the vaccination. Her initial emergency room record, prior to ophthalmology evaluation, showed no evidence of ptosis or tearing in either eye, and CT head scan on presentation found stable left sinus disease. The patient was discharged with a diagnosis of sinusitis and prescribed oral doxycycline 100 mg twice daily for 10 days and fluticasone nasal spray (50 mcg/actuation) 1 spray nightly for 28 days for sinusitis. The next day the patient presented to institution's emergency department with left-sided eye pain and swelling and new-onset diplopia. Ophthalmology was then consulted, at her second ED visit, but first evaluation with ophthalmology. The patient denied discharge, irritation, foreign body sensation, floaters, flashes, shade over vision, blurred vision, sudden vision loss, photophobia. Ophthalmological examination revealed visual acuity of 20/20 in each eye, normal pupillary exam, and intraocular pressures of 16 and 21 mm Hg in the OD and OS, respectively. Visual field examination revealed limited ability to count fingers in the superior field of the OS. Extraocular motility was reduced in the OS (-3 in upgaze and -1 in adduction). Hertel exophthalmometry at a base of 100 mm was 12 mm on the OD and 16 mm OS). Margin reflex distance was 2 mm in the OD and -1 mm on the OS. The left lacrimal gland region appeared without induration or tenderness. The patient had edema and erythema of the left upper and lower eyelids, and her left temporal bulbar conjunctiva was injected and chemotic [On presentation, the patient had erythema and edema of the left upper and lower eyelids, left ptosis, left elevation deficit, and left proptosis]. The rest of the ocular exam was otherwise unremarkable. The patient was afebrile on presentation with a blood cell count of 10.9 k/uL. Orbital CT revealed left preseptal thickening with enhancement, and a small focal thickening adjacent to the left lamina papyracea thought to represent subperiosteal phlegmonous change or early abscess, with confluent opacification of the left anterior ethmoid air cells. The left inferior and medial rectus muscles appeared enlarged with sparing on the tendons. [Coronal CT scan of the orbits on presentation, showing enlarged left medial and inferior rectus muscles. The patient was also noted to have left ethmoid, maxillary, and frontal sinus thickening]. The patient was admitted to initiate intravenous vancomycin (1.25 gm every 12 hours) and ciprofloxacin (400 mg every 12 hours), and oxymetazoline nasal sprays (2 sprays, twice daily), nasal saline irrigation (60 mL to each nostril, twice daily), and fluticasone (2 sprays in each nare, daily). Over the next 18 hours, the left-sided proptosis increased to 6 mm and remained stable over the following day, without any changes in vision, extraocular motility, or cranial nerve exam. Autoimmune workup showed a normal WBC, TSI, ANA, ACE, ANCA, and IgG4. Other serologic testing included ESR = 72 mm/hour (normal 0-20 mm/hour), C-reactive protein = 9.4 mg/dl (normal less than 0.9 mg/dl), and rheumatoid factor = 17 IU/ml (normal less than 16 IU/ml). Thirty-six hours after admission, intravenous solumedrol, 250 mg every 6 hours, was initiated. Nine hours after initiation of steroids, the patient noted drastic improvement in her discomfort and double vision. Extraocular motility improved to -0.5 in upgaze and -0.5 adduction and proptosis was reduced to 3 mm. Approximately 24 hours after initiating IV solumedrol, the proptosis had reduced to 2 mm, with stable extraocular motility (-0.5 in upgaze and -0.5 adduction). The patient was discharged for outpatient management prednisone taper starting at 60 mg orally per day and oral antibiotics. Follow-up examination 1 week after discharge revealed visual acuity of 20/20 in each eye, Hertel exophthalmometry of 12 mm in each eye at a base of 100 mm, full extraocular motility and resolved eyelid edema and erythema. The patient finished her course of oral steroids 15 days later without evidence of relapse. This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization.  The author commented, "This case of unilateral ptosis, proptosis, and orbital myositis occurred within 2 days after administration of shingles vaccination. Shingrix has a high level of efficacy in reducing the incidence of zoster infection, with 97.2% efficacy in those more than 50 years of age and 89.8% in those more than 70. The most common side effects with Shingrix vaccine included local pain, redness, and swelling and generalized effects such as myalgia, fatigue, headache, shivering, fever, and GI symptoms. No publications were found of new ocular or orbital inflammation after administration of shingles vaccines. Herpes zoster ophthalmicus (HZO) presents in the first division of the trigeminal nerve. Typically, HZO is associated with pain and a periocular vesicular rash in the CN V1 distribution. HZO may also present with eyelid changes (rash, secondary bacterial infection), conjunctival injection and chemosis, corneal changes (pseudodendrites, punctate epithelial keratitis, stromal keratitis, nummular keratitis), uveitis (cell and flare, synechiae, iris atrophy), retinal findings (acute retinal necrosis, progressive outer retinal necrosis), and postherpetic neuralgia. HZO has less commonly been reported to present with orbital inflammation. Case reports include diffuse orbital inflammation and myositis; however, the patient reported here had no other signs or symptoms of HZO. Given the temporal relation with the shingles vaccination, no occurrence of vesicles or rash, and rapid resolution after steroid treatment, the authors propose that this patient experienced an autoimmune reaction to the shingles vaccine. There are alternative possibilities for the presentation. As discussed above, orbital myositis has been described with use of statin medications, which was a long-term medication for the patient. While a serum creatine kinase (CK) level was not obtained in this case, an elevated CK level may have strengthened the diagnosis of orbital myositis. Additionally, if orbital symptoms recurred on the second dose of Shingrix, this may further strength the association between Shingrix and orbital myositis; however, the authors did not obtain patient approval to evaluate this. The likelihood of ADR is separated in 4 categories: doubtful, possible, probably, and definite. Based on that scale, this reaction would be considered possible and the authors propose that this reaction to Shingrix is possible but not definitive. No clear conclusions have been made in the literature as to the mechanism of vaccine-related autoimmune conditions. Vaccine adjuvants may cause an orbital or systemic myositis presentation, and the adjuvants may inadvertently cause an autoimmune myositis. This case of orbital myositis occurring after Shingrix vaccine expands the known list of vaccines that may produce orbital inflammation; however, the exact pathophysiology of orbital inflammation in the context of vaccination remains to be elucidated."

Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of injection site itching; injection site rash (diffuse erythematous maculopapular rash); feeling of numbness and weakness in both legs; headache, myalgia, and malaise in a 54-years old female patient, who was vaccinated with Shingrix (GlaxoSmithKline) for prophylaxis. The patient had no significant past medical history. No information on patient's medical history, family history, concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient received Shingrix (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided). The age of vaccination was not provided. On an unspecified date, an unknown period after the vaccination, the patient presented with diffuse erythematous maculopapular rash, itching and a feeling of weakness in both legs. The patient's symptoms started with itching and erythematous macular rash at the site of shingles shot followed by headache, myalgia, and malaise which did not improve much with Benadryl. The next day, the patient felt numbness and weakness in both legs. On the third day, the patient awoke with a diffuse red rash on the face, trunk, lower extremities, fewer lesions on upper extremities. Her review of systems was negative except as mentioned. On examination, the patient was found to have a diffuse erythematous maculopapular pruritic rash, but no sensory, motor, cranial never or cerebellar signs. Infectious disease was consulted who recommended IV acyclovir considering early varicella with given morphology. The morphology of lesions did not change over a period of times and the VZV PCR of lesions came negative hence acyclovir was discontinued after three days. The patient's symptoms and rash improved over the hospital stay with supportive treatment, and the patient was discharged home on the fifth day of admission. This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization. The author commented, "Shingrix is recommended by the Committee as the preferred shingles vaccine over live zoster vaccine (Zostavax) to prevent shingles and postherpetic neuralgia in immunocompetent adults age 50 years and older. The safety of shingrix was evaluated from the pool date of 8 clinical trials of more than 10,000 participants which showed 17% of vaccine recipients had grade 3 adverse events (preventing normal everyday activities). Grade 3 injection-site reactions (pain, redness, and swelling) were reported by 9.4% of vaccine recipients and grade 3 solicited systemic events (myalgia, fatigue, headache, shivering, fever, and gastrointestinal symptoms) were reported by 10.8% of vaccine recipients. For grade 3 reactions, the median duration was 1 day for all systemic reactions and pain and 2 days for redness and swelling. The nature and duration of rash described in our patient has not been documented in any of the clinical trials." The author concluded, "Emergence of new adverse reactions which have not been reported are plausible with broader use of vaccine. Clinicians must have high index of suspicion for early recognition." This article corresponding to this case is not available for regulatory submission due to copyright restriction.

Additional case details were reported as follows: The patient reported case for herself. The patient received vaccine in left deltoid. She did not know if it was given intramuscularly because she did not look at the size of the needle. She did not have the lot number/expiry date but did provide the name and contact information of the pharmacy who administered it. She stated that she did not remember having any side effects after receiving the shot but she said she probably had some discomfort of the (injected) arm. Eight weeks after having the shot she developed a terrible case of shingles on her head, eye, temple, scalp area. The patient was not fully recovered because she still had residual nerve pain on the left side of her head. The patient did not went get Shingrix shot number 2 and she had past the 6 month window, which led to incomplete course of vaccination. She stated that her primary care physician wants her to get the Shingrix shot number 2. She spoken with a pharmacy and they told her that she would have to re-start the series but the patient did not want to restart the series. The reporter consented to follow up. This was a medication error with harm.

Patient presents with a rash which first appeared two days after receiving the Shringrix vaccine. It is gradually getting worse. There are islands of erythema with clear and opaque vesicles embedded. The rash is tender but not painful. The distribution is on the left jaw, left lateral neck and left posterior neck (V3 and C2 dermatomes). No exposures could be elicited which would indicate a delayed hypersensitivity reaction such as poison oak.  Viral culture sent and patient started on valacyclovir for 7 days. Shingrix is an inactivated vaccine so I searched high and low for another cause for his cutaneous vesicular rash but non could be identified. I came to the conclusion that somehow the patient got shingles from Shingrix. If the viral culture comes back positive, I plan to request a consultation with concern that the batch of vaccines may not be completely inactive.

Patient came to pharmacy window asking for flu shot. Ran prescription and a prompt for prevnar13 came up. I've counseled on the vaccine in regards to what it is, how it works, potential side effects. She stated she wanted to receive the prevnar13 shot as well. It was covered under Medicare Part B. After patient received both vaccines of the HD flu and prevnar13, I was made aware by my technician afterwards that she actually has gotten the prevnar13 awhile back and had let me know that the All Transactions tab only shows up to 17 months previously from the current date. Her last prevnar13 shot was completed on 09/29/2017 .  Patient currently on 10/30/20 has received both the Prevnar13 and Fluad HD vaccine.  I've spoke with the patient and had let her know upon checking she did receive the prevnar13 vaccine previously. She mentioned she hadn't had any issues with the last pneumonia shot (pneumovax23) other than some muscle tenderness. She had emotional concern of 2/10 but explained most likely she wouldn't receive a large benefit from the same vaccine but wouldn't harm her as she's gotten the vaccine previously. Pt was contempt with the answer and was glad a follow up call was done. Currently, no known issues had arise and had let patient know to contact the pharmacy if there is any questions or concerns.

Service member received smallpox and anthrax # 1 on 19 Jul 06 without any apparent difficulties. On 30 Jul 06 @ 2 AM he began having constant, non-radiating chest pains described as both dull and sharp at various intervals. The pains ranged in severity from 4-5/10 to 8-9/10 VAS, were worse when lying down, with increased physical activity and with rapid or deep respirations. Additionally he describes episodes of SOB with exertion, an awareness of rapid heart beat sensation within his chest and a cough productive for small amounts of clear mucus. While running during a physical training exercise he collapsed with a witness episode of loss of consciousness (only for a few seconds).There was no bowel or bladder control or any seizure activity. He took no medication for pain relief. He was admitted to  Medical Center where he had an abnormal EKG ï¿½sinus rhythm with diffuse ST elevation with upright T-waves and P-R segment depression in multiple leads consistent with acute pericarditis. Labs-elevated cardiac enzymes ï¿½ troponin I 7.42, CPK 532,  CPK-MB 22.2, CKP-MB percentage 4.1%; D. dimmer slightly elevated 572; slightly elevated AST & total protein 8.4 ; CBC- low MCV 76.8, low MCH; BMP ï¿½ Normal.  He was placed on telemetry with serial cardiac enzymes and EKGs. An echo was performed and he was medicated with Prednisone, Ibuprofen and Protonix. Smoker

Fever of 101, muscle aches, nausea began 03/07/2020, lasting approx. 12 hours.  Woke on 03/08/2020 with red, swollen lips.  Took 50 mg Benadryl, swelling began going down within a few hours.  When swelling was gone, small vesicles began to appear across upper and lower lips, lasting approx. 2 weeks.  Swelling of lips and vesicles continue to appear every few days-few weeks.  Each subsequent episode is slightly less than previous episode and symptoms disappear more quickly, usually within 2-4 days at present.  In April 2020, vesicles began to form above upper lip, which continues to become red from time to time, and again each episode is more minor than previous. At present, vesicles seem to only appear in corners of mouth.  Saw health care provider in April and given antiviral, which cleared symptoms within 1-2 days, although they have continued to appear as noted above.
OTHER_MEDS: Hormone replacement therapy, famotidine 20 mg, Calcium 1200 mg, glucosamine sulfate.
